<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BeltwaySpill     08-13 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beltway Spill,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Causes Massive Traffic Jam Near Nation's Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANGLEY, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both loops of the Capital Beltway around
Washington were closed for more than four hours, 160 homes were
evacuated and nine firefighters were injured when a truck carrying
a volatile chemical overturned and caught fire during Friday's rush
hour.
   The truck, carrying 11,000 lbs. of granular potassium
permanganate, caught fire at 3:20 p.m., according to Fairfax County
Fire Department spokeswoman Pam Weiger.
   The chemical is a respiratory irritant and can cause skin burns.
   Four of 175 containers were broken open, and firefighters kept
water flowing over the smouldering crystals to keep fumes from
spreading until clean-up crews could clear the scene, Weiger said.
   At the height of the fire, yellow smoke shot 150 feet into the
air.
   Traffic was backed up for miles while authorities from a number
of jurisdictions tried to reroute traffic. The inner loop was
reopened about 7 p.m., but two lanes of the outer loop were not
opened again until 9:30 p.m.
   Four firefighters were hospitalized with breathing difficulties
from the chemical fumes, Weiger said.
   Five people from the Fairfax hazardous materials unit were
treated at Fairfax Hospital for heat exhaustion caused by being
encapsulated in suits for several hours, she said.
</TEXT>
