<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WellRescue     08-13 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Well Rescue,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Rescue Man Who Fell Down Well, Grandson Who Tried to
Save Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters on Friday hoisted to safety a
66-year-old man who fell 35 feet down a private well and a
16-year-old grandson who tried unsuccessfully to rescue him,
authorities said.
   Duane Nelson, a retired physician, had donned rigging to descend
into the well on his property to clean sand that had accumulated at
the bottom. He either fell or lost consciousness, ending up at the
bottom of the well, authorities said.
   His grandson, Kevin Stillwell, of Mesa, Ariz., went down to
help, but his rigging attachment apparently broke, said Rick
Oliver, firefighter-paramedic for Spokane County Fire Protection
District 9.
   Stillwell also lost consciousness, apparently from lack of
oxygen, and fell atop his grandfather, Oliver said. Both were
trapped in the well for about an hour.
   Nelson, whose property is in Greenbluff, north of Spokane, was
airlifted to Sacred Heart Medical Center here, where he was in
critical condition Friday evening with multiple injuries, a nursing
supervisor said. Stillwell was treated and released at another
Hospital.
   Rescue workers had difficulty lowering themselves into the well
because of their bulky protective clothing and the narrow shaft
opening, authorities said.
   Oliver said he then was lowered head first while rescue workers
pumped oxygen into the well with a fan and garden hose.
   Suddenly, ``One of the people (the grandson) began to move,''
Oliver said. ``I stopped, and we started yelling at him, and he
regained consciousness.''
   The son managed to put a lifebelt around himself and around his
grandfather to keep his head out of the waist-deep water, Oliver
said.
   After Stillwell was pulled to safety, Oliver went down and
secured a rope to the grandfather, who was also lifted out.
</TEXT>
