<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NavyShips     08-13 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Ships,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Department Postpones Deployment Of Aegis Cruiser</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department said Friday it has
delayed the deployment of a new Aegis guided-missle cruiser to the
Persian Gulf as part of a reassessment of U.S. military operations
in that area.
   ``This is a temporary postponement while the current situation
in the Gulf is reassessed,'' Navy Cmdr. Mel Sundin said referring
to the USS Mobile Bay's delayed voyage to the Gulf.
   The cruiser was scheduled to leave its Mayport, Fla. home port
Friday to replace the U.S. Vincennes which ends its Gulf tour in
September. The Vincennes, another Aegis cruiser, shot down an
Iranian Airbus on July 3, killing all 290 aboard.
   ``As the secretary (of defense) said earlier this week _ We've
always said we shape our forces according to the threat,'' he said,
indicating the possible effect the recent Iran-Iraq cease-fire
agreement.
   Sundin said ``a final decision on deployment will be made as
ongoing assessment indicates what level of forces are needed to
ensure continued safe and unimpeded operations in the Gulf.''
   Although there were no immediate plans to pull any of the 27
ships assigned to the Gulf, other than those previously scheduled
for rotation, a Pentagon statement said a decision had not been
made on the deployment of four relief ships scheduled to leave for
the Gulf next week.
</TEXT>
