<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-IndianTreaty     08-13 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Indian Treaty,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Treaty That Ended Indian War Bought By Tribe's Descendants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Villagers from Klukwan have paid an art
dealer in New Mexico an undisclosed sum for what is believed to be
a 112-year-old peace treaty between the Stikeen and Chilkat Indians.
   The treaty ended 12 years of bloodshed between the tribes.
   The documents was signed, perhaps in blood, at Fort Wrangell in
1876 by Chief Shakes of the Stikeen Indians and Chief Se-gua-sha of
the Chilkat Indians.
   The treaty wound up in the collection of Santa Fe, N.M., art
dealer David Kramer. Villagers from Klukwan bought the document
from him last week.
   Klukwan, where descendants of the Chilkats still live, is
located in the Chilkat Bald Eagle Reserve, about 22 miles north of
Haines. It is the oldest Tlingit settlement in southeastern Alaska;
the Chilkat and Stikeen tribal groups were part of the Tlingit
nation.
   After the treaty is authenticated, it will be put on display at
the planned Klukwan Eagle Observatory and Cultural Heritage Center.
Construction of the center should be completed in three years, said
Klukwan Heritge Foundation President Janice Clayton Hill.
   The treaty includes a pair of red wax seals with narrow ribbons
next to the chiefs' marks, and a blue seal indicating it arrived at
Fort Sitka on Feb. 3, 1876.
   Kramer said he has had the treaty for about 10 years. He said he
bought it from the estate of an Indian artifact collector, who
obtained it in Seattle in the early 1970s.
   After being contacted by an associate of Kramer, Hill said she
and Village Council President Joe Hotch questioned elders and dug
up old records to verify there were battles between the Chilkats
and Stikeens in that time period, and apparently a treaty.
   ``We got enough information to make us realize the historical
importance of this to us,'' she said.
   Kramer said variations in coloration in the document's text
indicate it may have been written and signed in blood. ``It appears
to be blood, but it would take a test to confirm it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
