<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmLabor     08-13 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Labor,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Number of Farmworkers Down, Wages Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of workers employed by farmers this
summer declined slightly from a year ago, but their wages are up,
according to a quarterly survey by the Agriculture Department.
   The survey taken last month indicated 1.2 million hired workers
were employed by farmers, compared with 1.27 million a year earlier.
   Those did not include 303,000 ``agricultural service'' workers
provided by crew chiefs and labor contractors. A year ago 258,000
were counted.
   ``Temperatures soared to over 100 degrees throughout much of the
nation during the survey week of July 10-16,'' the report said
Friday.
   ``Winter wheat harvest was 82 percent complete by the week's
end, 10 points ahead of the five-year average,'' the report said.
``Cotton harvest was under way in the Texas Rio Grande Valley.
Peach harvest was in full swing along the east coast. California's
vegetable harvest consisted mostly of broccoli, cauliflower,
carrots, celery, melons and onions. Harvest of cherries,
raspberries and blueberries was active in Oregon and Washington
state.''
   The report said the national figures for hired workers had a
sampling error of 3.6 percent.
   Average pay for all workers hired directly by farmers was $4.90
per hour, up 12 cents per hour from a year earlier, the report
showed.
   For workers provided by contractors, there was no national wage
rage available. However, workers in California averaged $5.74 per
hour, down from $6.48 a year ago, while those in Florida received
an average of $5.19 per hour, up from $5.13 a year ago.
</TEXT>
