<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0220EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Ford-EPA     08-13 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ford-EPA,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Cites Ford For Alleged Emission Control Warranty Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency is
threatening Ford Motor Co. with $230,000 in penalties for allegedly
failing to fix defective emissions control components under
warranty.
   The automaker said it hoped something could be worked out and
accused the agency of changing its interpretation of the federal
law that sets standards for automotive emissions.
   An EPA notice of violation, made public Friday, said Ford in 23
instances from 1984 through this year denied warranty service for
emission-control components that failed because a non-covered
component.
   The EPA's field operations director, Richard Kozlowski, said the
agency's position reflects the meaning of the Clean Air Act of 1974.
   ``The act is the act, and it refers to the vehicle meeting
emissions standards, not the particular parts,'' he said.
   Ford, however, said the agency should change rules that apply
industry-wide rather than singling out Ford.
   ``It is not a new issue,'' said Donald Buist, Ford's automotive
emissions and fuel economy director in Dearborn, Mich. ``What we've
got here is a new interpretation of a longstanding emissions
policy.''
   Kozlowski, however, said EPA's interpretation is one ``we've had
... from day one.''
   ``Our point is that if the manifold fails in a way that causes
the catalyst to fail, replacing the catalyst on the warranty
doesn't fix the problem,'' he said. ``It will fail again and again.
The only way to fix the problem so the vehicle meets standards is
to replace the part that causes the failure.''
   He said other automakers, ``whether they do it for goodwill, to
keep us off their back, or whether they believe it is covered,''
fix emission-related components whose failure is caused by
non-covered equipment, and the EPA believes Ford should do the same.
   The EPA said the $230,000 in civil penalties could be lessened
if Ford were to change its policy on emission-defect warranties.
   Should Ford and EPA not settle the complaint within 90 days, the
agency's normal procedure would be to refer the matter to the
Justice Department with a recommendation that a civil complaint be
filed in federal court, the notice of violation said.
   Buist said Ford intends to resolve the matter through
discussions with the EPA. `` `Resolution' means to the satisfaction
of both parties,'' he said.
   The EPA notice of violation, dated Aug. 5, was made public by
the Coalition for Auto Repair Choice, a trade association
representing the auto parts and repair industries.
   Both Ford and the EPA acknowledged that the notice had been
issued.
   A spokeswoman for the coalition, Pamela Kostmayer, declined to
say how the EPA notice was obtained.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
