<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Talks 2ndLd-Writethru a0841 08-13 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Talks, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0841,0768</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Offers to Renew Contra Talks in Managua or Washington</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS graf after 2nd, `Ortega, who...</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   with rebel leader
rejecting Managua as talk site. SUBS grafs 11-13 pvs, `Adolfo
Calero...United States,' with 4 grafs of new Calero comments. Pick
up 14th pvs, `The peace...
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua on
Friday offered to renew peace talks with U.S.-supported rebels
either in Managua or Washington.
   Ortega, who is on an official visit to Ecuador, also criticized
the U.S. Congress for approving new aid to the rebels and called it
an act of ``aggression.'' He demanded that such aid be stopped.
   Adolfo Calero, a rebel leader, on Friday rejected Managua as the
site for peace talks, saying the ``climate doesn't exist'' for them
to be held there. He also demanded that Ortega personally attend
future talks.
   In a separate meeting with reporters in Quito, Cuban President
Fidel Castro said he was willing to help bring ``a fair peace'' to
Central America.
   On Thursday, Costa Rican President Oscar Arias, who won the 1987
Nobel Peace Prize for his efforts to bring peace to Central
America, said he asked Castro for assistance in achieving that
goal. Arias said at the time that nothing concrete had been
achieved.
   Representatives of the left-wing Sandinista government and the
Nicaraguan rebels known as Contras agreed on a cease-fire March 23
under a regional peace plan that Ortega and four other Central
American presidents signed in August 1987.
   The cease-fire often has been violated but extended by both
sides, most recently by Nicaragua unilaterally until Aug. 30. But
the two sides have deadlocked on a permanent truce and have failed
to agree on a site or date for talks since the last round ended
June 9.
   Leaders of the Contras said they would hold no further meetings
in Managua, the Nicaraguan capital. The Contras claimed the
Sandinistas refused to allow them freedom of movement.
   ``We invite the Contras ... to come to Managua'' Aug. 26-29,
Ortega told a news conference.
   ``We see no sense in having the meeting in another country,'' he
said. ``The only place outside of Managua that we would accept
would be Washington. In Washington, it would be possible to achieve
something because Washington is part of the aggression against
Nicaragua.''
   On Wednesday, the U.S. Senate approved by a 49-47 vote a
Democratic plan to provide $27 million in humanitarian assistance
to the Contras. Senate Republicans, who had sought military as well
as humanitarian assistance, voted against the proposal.
   ``We are not going to Managua, because there we are treated like
prisoners. We would arrive (in Managua) only to be in the hands of
and to suffer the arbitrariness of the Sandinista regime,'' Calero
said in remarks broadcast by the rebels' clandestine Radio
Liberacion.
   Calero set a number of conditions before the rebels would return
to the bargaining table, including the reopening of the Roman
Catholic station Radio Catolica and radio news programs shut down
by the Sandinistas in July.
   Calero also demanded the release of more than 40 opposition
figures detained by the government when police violently broke up
an anti-government demonstration July 10 in Nandaimes, about 40
miles south of Managua.
   President Ortega also must be present at any future negotiating
session, Calero said.
   The peace plan, which aims to negotiate an end to the 7-year-old
war in Nicaragua as well as leftist guerrilla wars in El Salvador
and Guatemala, calls for cease-fires, democratic reforms and an end
to outside military assistance to rebels.
   Speaking with reporters Friday, Castro said:
   ``In truth, whatever we might be able to do for a fair peace, a
peace with dignity, we would always do.''
   But Castro said no country should have to pay for peace by
giving up its freedom.
   ``Peace does not depend on us. Peace depends on the
aggressors,'' he said. ``It is much more correct to say peace
depends on the policies that the United States follows, not those
that we follow.''
   U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz, Castro and Arias were
among those attending Wednesday's inauguration of Ecuadorian
President Rodrigo Borga, a moderate leftist who replaced Leon
Febres Cordero, a conservative.
   It was Castro's first trip to South America in 17 years. The
presidents of Argentina, Uruguay, Colombia and Venezuela also were
present for the inauguration.
   Ortega arrived the day after the inauguration, because Febres
Cordero cut off diplomatic relations with Nicaragua in 1985.
</TEXT>
