<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SeatBelts     08-13 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Seat Belts,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DOT Says Seat Belt Use Up to 43 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The percentage of people using seat belts has
almost quadrupled in the past five years, but fewer than half the
nation's motorists buckle up, according to the Transportation
Department.
   Surveys in 19 cities showed that more than 43 percent of U.S.
motorists use the safety devices, the department said, attributing
the major portion of the increase from 11 percent five years ago to
mandatory seat belt use laws in many states.
   A total of 32 states and the District of Columbia require
front-seat occupants of vehicles to wear seat belts.
   ``Increasingly public acceptance of safety belts is saving lives
and preventing injuries,'' Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley
said Friday, estimating that 4,000 lives were saved because of seat
belt use in 1987.
   The 19-city survey covered 49,095 observations of motorists from
February through May of this year. It showed 43.4 percent of the
front-seat occupants wore safety belts, according to the
department's National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
   Similar surveys in 1982 showed belt use to be at about 11
percent, the agency said.
   The survey indicated a wide range of seat belt use, with
motorists most likely to wear their belts in Dallas (71.4 percent),
Houston (65.6 percent) and Seattle (60.3 percent). The cities with
the lowest use rate were Providence, R.I. (15.4 percent),
Fargo-Moorhead, N.D., (21.7 percent) and New York City (24.6
percent).
   Belt use was sharply higher in cities where laws require
motorists to use the belts, the agency said. It said that in 13
cities in states with safety belt use laws, belt use was 48.3
percent, while in six cities without such laws it was 30.4 percent.
   Here is the rate of belt usage in each of the 19 cities
surveyed, according to the highway safety agency.
   Cities not covered by a belt-use law:
   Providence, R.I., 15.4 percent; Fargo-Moorhead, N.D., 21.7
percent; Boston, 31.2 percent; Atlanta, 36.4 percent; Birmingham,
Ala., 39.5 percent; Phoenix, Ariz., 40.6 percent.
   Cities covered by a belt-use law:
   New York, 24.6 percent; Pittsburgh, 28.1 percent; Chicago, 31.7
percent; New Orleans, 43.3 percent; Baltimore, 46.7 percent; Los
Angeles, 47.3 percent; Minneapolis-St. Paul, 47.8 percent; Miami,
51.9 percent; San Francisco, 53.4 percent; San Diego, 59.4 percent;
Seattle, 60.3 percent; Houston, 65.6 percent; Dallas, 71.4 percent.
</TEXT>
