<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Michelson obit; AMs separates moved as a0767 on Ramsey
and a0760 on Faltersack.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Anne Ramsey</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anne Ramsey, an actress whose grotesque
character in ``Throw Momma From the Train'' won her an Oscar
nomination, died Thursday of throat cancer at age 59.
   She often appeared with her husband, actor Logan Ramsey, in
projects, including Clint Eastwood's ``Any Which Way You Can.''
Mrs. Ramsey appeared in two Barbra Streisand films, ``Up the
Sandbox'' and ``For Pete's Sake'' and played Nick Nolte's addled
mother in ``Weeds.'' In ``Goonies,'' she uttered the line, ``Put
that kid's hand in the blender and hit puree.''
   Her television credits included roles in ``The Young and the
Restless,'' guest appearances on ``Hill Street Blues,'' ``Night
Court'' and ``Knight Rider,'' and movies-of-the-week roles in
``White Mama,'' ``The Boy in the Plastic Bubble,'' ``Blind
Ambition'' and ``Marilyn.''
   Mrs. Ramsey will be seen in four still-to-be-released films:
``Dr. Hackenstein,'' ``Scrooge,'' ``Good Ole Boy'' and ``Homer and
Eddie.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Fred Faltersack</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fred Paul Faltersack, a sleight of hand
expert who helped Houdini develop some of his illusions, died
August 7 of congestive heart failure. He was 94.
   Faltersack met Harry Houdini while working his way through San
Jose State University and the famous musician appeared at a theater.
   He took Houdini to see the Winchester Mystery House, a tourist
attraction with optical illusions and other amusements, where
Faltersack worked as a tour guide. And in later years, he helped
Houdini build some of his illusions.
   In the early 1930s, Faltersack was appointed as a special
representative of the International Brotherhood of Magicians,
entitling him to make contact with top European magicians. He later
became a founding member of Mystic 13, a prestigious group of
American magicians.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>William White</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINONA, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Francis White, 64, former publisher
and owner of the Winona Daily News, died Thursday.
   An Army veteran of World War II, White graduated from the
University of Minnesota's journalism school in 1949. He worked in
all departments of the Winona newspaper before becoming its
business manager in 1951 and purchasing the newspaper from his
father in 1961.
   White was publisher from 1961 to 1980 and president of the
Republican and Herald Publishing Co. from 1961 until 1980, when he
sold the newspaper to Lee Enterprises Inc.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Jared How</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANKATO, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jared How, former publisher of the Mankato
Free Press daily newspaper and owner of several weekly newspapers
in Minnesota, died Friday of cancer at the age of 76.
   How joined The Free Press advertising department in 1937, later
becoming city editor and then manager of the printing division. He
became publisher and vice president in 1956, and president in 1962.
   How purchased the Twin Falls (Idaho) News-Times in 1961. He sold
it in 1968, the same year he bought the Owatonna People's Press,
another daily. In 1976, How purchased weekly newspapers in Hallock,
Red Lake Falls and Middle River. In 1979, How sold his newspaper
holdings to Ottaway Newspapers Inc.
   How remained Free Press president until 1981, publisher until
1982 and, until his death, chairman, consultant and acquisition
adviser.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Herb Michelson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Herb Michelson, an author and special
writer for The Sacramento Bee, died Friday of a heart attack. He
was 57.
   Before going to the Bee, he worked for the Oakland Tribune and
the Akron Beacon-Journal for three years. He also worked as a
producer for KPIX-TV and an assistant news director for KGO-TV in
San Francisco.
   Michelson began covering Oakland Athletics baseball for the Bee
in 1968, becoming a full-time staff writer in 1975. He was a daily
columnist for the Bee from 1978-1984, and moved to the paper's San
Francisco bureau in 1984.
   A graduate of Indiana University, he published six books, mostly
on sports, including one about former A's owner Charles O. Finley.
</TEXT>
