<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HijackingSuspect     08-13 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijacking Suspect,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Material Witness Held In Terrorist Case Fears For Family, Lawyer
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lawyer for a Middle East man jailed here
as a material witness in the 1985 hijacking of a Jordanian airliner
says her client fears for the safety of his family in Beirut.
   Mouin Abdul Ajam was arrested in California on Thursday and
brought here following a hearing before a federal magistrate in
Sacramento, according to court records in that city. Authorities
believe he could implicate Fawaz Younis, a suspected Lebanese
terrorist, in the hijacking.
   Ajam is ``extremely concerned'' that if he cooperates with the
prosecutors in the case, his family in Beirut will be killed in
retaliation by terrorist groups sympathetic to Younis, said Jessica
McGuire, an assistant federal public defender who represented Ajam
in Sacramento.
   ``He has every reason to fear retaliation against his family in
Beirut,'' she said. Ajam complained that the U.S. government is
``not taking enough precautions regarding his family,'' she said.
   Ms. McGuire declined to give more information about her client,
citing his concerns for the safety of his family.
   Younis, a former member of Lebanon's Shiite Amal militia, was
arrested last September after he was lured aboard an FBI-chartered
yacht in the Mediterranean, is awaiting trial here on charges that
he led the June 11, 1985 hijacking of a Royal Jordanian airliner in
Beirut.
   Ajam was named in an arrest warrant outlining Justice Department
concerns that he might not cooperate in the prosecution of Younis,
Ms. McGuire said.
   Federal prosecutors here have also filed a motion to compel Ajam
to give a sworn deposition about the case, said sources familiar
with the case who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Justice Department spokesman John Russell declined to comment.
   Federal prosecutors have jurisdiction to prosecute the Younis
case because the plane was carrying several Americans. No date has
been set for Younis' trial in U.S. District Court here.
   Ajam is one of several Middle Easterners who prosecutors have
said could give evidence against Younis.
   Prosecutors disclosed in court last month that two airline crew
members are in protective custody after agreeing to come to this
country and testify against Younis.
   U.S. Magistrate Esther Mix in Sacramento ordered Ajam detained,
and U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker, who issued the
warrant for Ajam's arrest, has scheduled a bail hearing on Monday.
   The Royal Jordanian Airliner was hijacked at the Beirut Airport
by four armed men and forced to fly to several locations in the
Mediterranean. Following its return to Beirut the next day, the
jetliner was blown up after 74 passengers and crew members were
taken off the aircraft.
   The trial is being delayed while prosecutors appeal Parker's
ruling that the FBI illegally obtained statements from Younis
during a four-day interrogation following his arrest at sea. The
judge ruled the admissions couldn't be used as evidence against
Younis because the defendant didn't understand his constitutional
protection against self-incrimination.
</TEXT>
