<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Australia-Reefs     08-13 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Australia-Reefs,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Say Coral Reefs May Provide Knowledge About Weather
Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER O'LOUGHLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOWNSVILLE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coral reefs contain a wealth of
information on climate changes that occurred centuries ago and
could help predict the world's weather, scientists say.
   About 750 scientists from 53 nations attended a symposium on
coral reefs that ended Friday.
   They also discussed the fate of coral reefs attacked by
crown-of-thorns starfish that devour living coral. Most of the
participants believed the reefs recover quickly, but others said
the reefs could be dead for centuries.
   ``The most important thing to come out of the conference was the
recognition that coral reefs are the repositories of a wealth of
data going back millions of years,'' said Peter Davies, chairman of
the symposium at James Cook University.
   The university is a few miles from a section of the
1,200-mile-long Great Barrier Reef off Australia's northeastern
coastline.
   ``Reefs have got all the data on sea-level change, weather,
climate, the greenhouse effect,'' Davies said.
   Scientists use the term ``greenhouse effect'' to refer to
pollution that accummulates in the atmosphere and traps energy from
the sun, causing the Earth's temperature to rise.
   Davies said that scientists using such techniques as drilling
core samples of living corals of great age could measure old
climatic changes.
   ``The information in the corals will let us make sensible
predictions,'' he said. ``They are like a huge library. ... It was
reported here for the first time that we are seeing the same or
similar structures in old corals in the Sinai Desert as we see in
living corals now.
   ``And those corals in the Sinai were uplifted and exposed into
what is now arid land 250,000 years ago.''
   Davies also said scientists are studying the biochemistry of
corals in search of a substance that could protect humans from
sunburn.
   ``Corals in shallow water produce a natural suncreen. If they
didn't, they'd die of sunburn,'' Davies said, and the research has
``a large potential.''
   Crown-of-thorn starfish are found throughout the world, but
periodically they appear in vast numbers in parts of the Great
Barrier Reef and may destroy up to 90 percent of the coral on a
reef.
   Scientists said it has not been determined why the starfish
appear when they do, and there is no known method of controlling
them.
   Davies said most evidence indicates the starfish are part of the
reef cycle and the reefs quickly recover.
   But Robert Endean, a professor at the University of Queensland,
told the conference it would take centuries for large corals to
recover and then only if the starfish did not return while they
were regrowing.
   Australian scientists said they had tried injecting the starfish
with copper sulphate, catching them by hand, installing underwater
wire fences and infecting them with bacteria, but nothing worked.
   The scientists were told the Australian armed forces once sent
divers to kill the starfish, but the cost came to about $20 per
dead fish.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880813-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Noriega     08-13 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Noriega,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Observes 5th Anniversary In Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega marked
his fifth anniversary as Panama's military leader by delivering a
diatribe against the United States, which has tried to oust him
from power.
   Noriega, head of Panama's Defense Forces, said the Reagan
administration created a false crisis in an attempt to revoke the
1977 Panama Canal Treaties, which turn over control of the vital
waterway to Panama on Dec. 31, 1999.
   The United States is ``using lies, falsehoods and politics to
keep North American youth in (military) service (in Panama) under
the risk of war that their government is provoking,'' he declared
Friday.
   ``Many Panamanians wrongly thought ... Panama and the United
States were beginning a permanent honeymoon, forgetting that for
the United States a treaty is no more ... than a useful but
emphemeral act. The United States signs treaties knowing that it is
going to violate them,'' he said.
   About 12,000 U.S. military personnel are based in Panama to
protect the canal. The headquarters of the U.S Southern Command,
which directs all American military activities in Central and South
America, also is in Panama.
   Noriega spoke before an audience of thousands of government
officials, supporters, soldiers and civilian militia at an old
section of Albrook Air Force Base that has been taken over by
Panama under the canal treaties.
   The general began his speech by waving his fist toward the U.S.
Command headquarters nearby and saying: ``Welcome to the territory
of Panama in the Canal Zone. Welcome until you march.''
   Noriega, chief of the Defense Forces and the power behind the
civilian government, is under federal indictment in the United
States on charges of drug trafficking and money laundering.
Washington has sought his ouster since early this year, applying
economic sanctions that have helped push Panama into its worst
depression since the 1930s.
   The general, who took command of the Panama Defense Forces on
Aug. 12, 1983, has refused to bow to U.S. and internal pressure for
his resignation and departure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
