<DOCNO> AP880813-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0244EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ColdMedicineRecall     08-13 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cold Medicine Recall,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Recall on Mislabeled Bottles of Promethazine VC Plain Cold Remedy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bottles of a prescription allergy and cold
medicine syrup called Promethazine VC Plain that contain a thick,
white lotion instead of the normal clear, orange-yellow syrup
should not be ingested, the Food and Drug Administration warned.
   The agency said Friday that the white lotion may be lindane, a
medicine for parasitic mites known as scabies, that could cause
severe convulsions if taken by children.
   Pint bottles of My-K and Rugby brands of Promethazine VC Plain
syrup made by My-K Laboratories, lot 15880, were being recalled
from pharmacies, the FDA said.
   The FDA asked consumers to watch for the white lotion because
the bottles purchased from drug stores may not have the lot number
or distributor's name as some pharmacists may have transferred the
product to smaller bottles.
   Pharmaceutical Basics Inc. of Morton Grove, Ill., which recently
purchased My-K Laboratories, began the recall after a pharmacist in
Racine, Wis., discovered a pint bottle of the lindane lotion
mislabeled as promethazine syrup.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
