<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FamilyKilling     08-13 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Family Killing,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney Trying to Win New Trial for Convicted Killer Unveils New
Evidence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARCADIA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney and an author presented a
packed auditorium Friday with two sworn affidavits indicating a
babysitter confessed to poisoning seven children and that their
imprisoned stepfather is innocent.
   The statements presented by attorney John Robinson and author
Mark Lane are part of an effort to win a new trial for James Joseph
Richardson, 52, who has served more 20 years of a life sentence for
poisoning his eldest child with the insecticide parathion.
   The affidavits from Belinda Romeo and Doris Harris, workers at
the Hardee Manor Nursing Home in Wachula, said Bessie Reece
admitted the 1967 murders of the children, age 2 to 8.
   Ms. Romeo claims to have cared for Ms. Reece from January 1985
to last year at the nursing home.
   According to Ms. Romeo's affidavit, Ms. Reece said, ``Yes, I
killed those children. ... I killed them but I don't know why.''
   ``I was certain she understood my question,'' Ms. Romeo said in
the statement.
   Ms. Reece, now 67, was a neighbor of Richardson's in Arcadia. At
the time the children were slain, Ms. Reece had been on parole from
a sentence for killing her husband.
   More than 20 years after the killings, the case still holds
enough interest here that residents filled the auditorium of the
community center, a former elementary school.
   Robinson defended Richardson at a highly publicized four-day
murder trial in 1968 in which prosecutors claimed Richardson
sprinkled the insecticide on the children's lunch of hog jowl and
beans. Richardson was charged with all seven deaths but was
convicted only in the death of his oldest stepdaughter. Charges
were dropped against his wife.
   Investigators charged that Richardson intended to collect $1,000
in life insurance on each child from a policy that he had tried to
buy _ but had not paid for _ from a traveling salesman on the night
before the mass murder.
   The statements of guilt attributed to Ms. Reece were said to
have been made after she entered the nursing home but before state
officials deemed her mentally incompetent.
   DeSoto County Sheriff Joe Varnadore said through a department
spokesman Wednesday that he has reviewed the new evidence but
hasn't decided whether to reopen the investigation.
   Richardson, 52, is at the Tomoka Correctional Institution in
Daytona Beach, where he is scheduled to become eligible for parole
in 1993.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880813-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TruckRecall     08-13 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Truck Recall,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paccar Recalls As Many as 10,000 Peterbilt, Kenworth Trucks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paccar, one of the country's largest big truck
manufacturers, has recalled as many as 10,000 Peterbilt and
Kenworth trucks that may have defective power-steering gearboxes.
   The Bellevue-based company said the trucks subject to the recall
were produced after March and range in value from $60,000 to more
than $100,000 apiece.
   Paccar spokesman Jack McRae said the gearbox supplier, Ross Gear
Division of TRW, asked Paccar to suspend delivery of its top-of-the
line class 8 trucks because of potential defects. McRae said Paccar
and TRW officials met Friday to determine the precise problem and
how to resolve it.
   McRae said the company planned to keep production going, then
store the trucks until the problem is isolated and fixed. Paccar
produces more than 2,000 of the trucks each month.
   ``To the best of my knowledge, this is the most significant
recall we've had,'' he said.
   Other makers also use the gearbox, McRae added.
   No accidents or injuries have been reported, McRae said. As soon
as Paccar found out about the problem it sent out messages to
dealers urging them to tell owners of Peterbilt and Kenworth trucks
built since March to pull them off the road, the company said.
   Paccar issued a statement at the close of the business day
Thursday about the problem.
   The stock market initially failed to take notice. An hour into
trading Friday, the stock was ahead 12.5 cents at $36.875 a share.
After a Dow Jones News Service headline on Paccar appeared 75
minutes into the trading day, the stock quickly plunged. Four hours
later, about an hour before the market closed, Paccar had fallen to
$33.50 a share on volume of 482,000 shares. In all of June, Paccar
volume was 760,700.
   McRae said based on what little the company knows about the
problem so far, it will not cause serious financial loss.
</TEXT>
