<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0256EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AbortionRules     08-13 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Rules,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Says It Will Deny Money to Clinics That Advise on
Abortions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration will begin applying
new regulations denying federal money to family planning clinics
that give women information about abortions unless the clinics are
covered by court injunctions barring enforcement of the rules.
   A spokesman for several family planning groups said the decision
was a political ploy timed to please conservatives before next
week's Republican National Convention.
   As a practical matter, the announcement Friday by the Department
of Health and Human Services will have no immediate impact since it
applies only to new grant applications or renewals that come up
after Oct. 1.
   Even then, federal court orders in Denver and Boston forbid the
rules from applying to the majority of clinics nationwide.
   The Justice Department has appealed those rulings, but they
remain in effect pending further action that likely will reach the
Supreme Court for final determination.
   Scott Swirling, head of the National Family Planning and
Reproductive Health Association, said politics was behind the
announcement.
   ``This is simply a show before the Republican convention to
please the anti-abortion constituency,'' said Swirling, whose
association is an umbrella group for most family planning
organizations.
   Planned Parenthood of America, one of the plaintiffs in the
suits that won the injunctions, is a member of Swirling's
association.
   The HHS announcement came after Arthur B. Culvahouse Jr.,
counsel to President Reagan, sent HHS Secretary Otis R. Bowen a
memo saying the regulations should ``be implemented in all
jurisdictions in which injunctions are not in force.''
   The Reagan administration has been stymied consistently by
Congress in persistent attempts to win legislative changes spelling
out the rules it is attempting to implement administratively.
</TEXT>
