<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0957</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Playwright-screenwriter Neil Simon, author of
``The Goodbye Girl,'' has filed for divorce from his wife of more
than a year.
   Simon cited irreconcilable differences for his split with Diane
Lander Simon, according to his petition, filed Friday in Superior
Court. The couple was married Jan. 13, 1987, and separated in June
1988.
   Property rights will be determined later, according to the
petition, filed by attorney Lesley A. Andrus.
   Many of Simon's hit plays also have become popular films,
including, ``Barefoot in the Park,'' ``The Odd Couple,'' ``Brighton
Beach Memoirs'' and ``Plaza Suite.''
   Simon was earlier divorced from actress Marsha Mason, who
starred in ``The Goodbye Girl.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Gene Epstein saw the Trump
Princess dock a few feet from his yacht, he never dreamed the giant
$30 million yacht owned by real estate developer Donald Trump would
be a magnet for gawkers at his own boat.
   Epstein and owners of neighboring yachts at an Atlantic City
marina grouse that Trump isn't concerned about the hordes of
tourists who not only stare at the six decks of the Princess but
peer into nearby portholes and in some cases even climb aboard.
   Trump says that the state marina, which he renovated, is open to
all.
   ``What has happened is that the Princess has become the hottest
piece of property in the country, and thousands of people are
coming to see it,'' he said Friday. ``People are allowed to walk on
a public dock.''
   ``My privacy is completely invaded,'' said Epstein, who is
docked four boats away from the Princess. ``People are literally
sticking their heads into my boat.
   ``Trump has the marina security guards standing by his boat, but
they don't stop people from climbing on our boats.''
   Trump, in a lease agreement with the state, invested $20 million
to fix up the once deteriorated marina that faces his Trump Castle
Hotel Casino.
   ``It was falling down, and now it's the most beautiful marina in
the world,'' he said. ``These people are unhappy because the rates
will increase substantially, commensurate with the quality of the
marina.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Sophie Masloff's choice of a slogan for
her city clean-up campaign, ``Sophie's Choice,'' has certainly
attracted attention, but not of the kind she wanted.
   The slogan brings to mind a William Styron book and film of the
same name, which told the story of a Polish woman in a World War II
concentration camp forced by the Nazis to choose which of her two
children would be killed.
   ``I love Sophie dearly. I wish she had chosen another slogan by
virtue of the fact it can raise an issue,'' said Richard Marcovitz,
rabbi at Congregation B'nai Israel.
   ``I think it was in bad taste,'' added Councilwoman Michelle
Madoff.
   The mayor defended her choice Thursday. ``It's just a catch
phrase. That's why I chose it, not for any significance at all,''
she said.
   ``This Sophie's Choice might not win an Academy Award, but it's
my No. 1 priority,'' said Mrs. Masloff.
   The clean-up campaign includes new street sweeping machines,
more trash containers, repaving 70 miles of city streets this year
and cleaning every vacant city lot by October.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buddy Miles, well known in the
1960s as the drummer in Jimi Hendrix's Band of Gypsies, is enjoying
another day in the sun.
   This time he's the voice of the lead singer in the Post Raisin
Bran TV commercials, which feature a quartet of singing, animated
clay raisins.
   The new wrinkle in Miles' career came while he was working on an
album with Carlos Santana, said the 40-year-old entertainer.
   The Raisin Bran commercials spawned a million-selling album of
oldies remakes with Miles singing the lead. But the head raisin is
still working the road.
   His refurbished seven-piece Buddy Miles Express is doing a
series of Southern California shows and the Motown hit ``Heard It
Through The Grapevine,'' sung by the television raisins, is part of
the repertoire.
   ``Why not? It comes off of a platinum album, and right now
people are really into listening to that kind of music. Plus,
they're great songs,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Football star Mark Gastineau and actress
Brigitte Nielsen called a full-scale press conference to announce
they plan a small-scale wedding with only their ``true friends'' as
guests.
   The date will be sometime this winter, as soon as his divorce is
final.
   ``We want something very romantic,'' said Nielsen, 25, recently
divorced from actor Sylvester Stallone.
   Gastineau, a New York Jets defensive end, has yet to sever his
marriage to his first wife, Lisa, a model, from whom he separated
in 1986.
   Gastineau and Nielsen confirmed last month's reports that as a
symbol of their eternal love, they had their names tatooed onto
each others buttocks.
   ``It means I really love this person and I'm going to be with
her for eternity,'' said Gastineau, 31, who is attending Jets
training camp at Hofstra University in the nearby Long Island
community of Hempstead.
   ``I can really call this true love,'' said the bride-to-be,
showing off her ring, featuring diamonds in the shape of a nine.
Gastineau's jersey number is 99. ``I am the happiest I have ever
been.''
   ``We want lots of kids, 10 of them,'' declared Nielsen, who said
her movie career will be secondary to ``being with Mark.'' Each has
a child by a previous marriage.
</TEXT>
