<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0332EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-WWII     08-13 0778</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-WWII,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Navy Gunner Says His Memory Of War Incident Differs With Bush's</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHESHIRE, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Navy gunner who says he saw
George Bush being shot down on a World War II bombing run says his
memory differs from the vice president's recollection of what
happened over the South Pacific on Sept. 2, 1944.
   Chester Mierzejewski, 68, a retired foreman of an aircraft
factory, said Friday that he wonders whether the then-Navy pilot,
and soon-to-be Republican presidential nominee, could have saved
two crewmates.
   One of those who went down with the plane in the South Pacific,
radioman John Delaney, was his friend, Mierzejewski said. But he
added he has ``no animosity'' toward Bush and calls him ``a very
nice guy.''
   The New York Post, which first reported his story, said no one
other than Mierzejewski claims to have seen Bush's plane be hit and
go down. Mierzejewski held a news conference outside his home after
his account appeared in the newspaper Friday.
   Bush has spoken of the war-time downing in interviews and has
recalled his combat record in campaign speeches.
   Mierzejewski said he witnessed the incident as a turret gunner
in a plane ahead of Bush's. He said he only reluctantly agreed,
after being prodded by a neighbor, to discuss the case in public.
   He said he wrote Bush in March to urge him to check with
advisers and make sure his recollection of the event was factual,
but got no response.
   ``I do not want to see your campaign hurt by statements you may
make regarding all that occurred when your aircraft was hit,'' he
wrote, saying he did not intend to dispute Bush in public.
   He did not accuse Bush of purposely distorting what happened,
saying the passage of time sometimes affects memories, and added
that ``from what I have heard you state, this may be the case
regarding your recollections of being shot down.''
   Bush's press office issued a statement Thursday saying he has
recounted the incident many times and ``to suggest that his account
is inaccurate is absurd.'' A telephone call Friday, seeking more
comment, was not returned.
   Mierzejewski, attached to the same squadron as Bush, was a
turret gunner in the squadron commander's plane during a
tight-formation bombing raid against a Japanese radar installation
in the South Pacific.
   Bush has said the plane was in smoke and the wings were burning
when he bailed out of his bomber, leaving behind two crewmates
presumed dead. Bush was picked up by a Navy submarine.
   Mierzejewski said he was only about 100 feet from the plane Bush
was flying, could see him in the cockpit, and ``I saw him get hit.
As he got over the water, and it began slowing down and losing
altitude, he bailed out.''
   While he said he saw an initial puff of smoke, he said it
quickly disappeared. After that, ``I didn't see any noticeable
smoke'' and ``I saw no fire,'' Mierzejewski said.
   He said he was very upset after the incident because he wondered
why Bush did not try to make a water landing which, if successful,
would have given the crew about two minutes to escape.
   ``If there was any doubt at all in his mind or any possibility
at all that these kids were alive, by attempting a water landing he
could have saved the people in the plane,'' he said.
   Mierzejewski said that a month after the downing he saw Bush and
that Bush told him: ``I knew those two were dead because I called
the back room and there was no answer.''
   In a television interview last December, Bush said one of his
crewmates had also apparently gotten out of the plane and that he
believed the other man died inside the craft.
   ``I felt I had to give him the benefit of the doubt (about what
happened) until he kept changing his versions,'' said Mierzejewski.
   An intelligence report on the loss of Bush's plane reported that
``smoke and flame'' engulfed Bush's engine, according to the Post.
It said the report was signed by the squadron commander, Douglas
Melvin, and a now-dead intelligence officer. Melvin is hospitalized
with Parkinson's disease and could not be interviewed, the Post
reported.
   Squadron members interviewed by the Post disagreed about whether
Mierzejewski would have had the best view of Bush's plane.
   Mierzejewski said he is an independent voter and has not decided
whether to vote for Bush for president. Larry Herman, a neighbor
who arranged for Mierzejewski to be interviewed by the Post, said
he is a Democrat but is not politically active. ``There's nothing
political about it,'' said Herman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880813-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Honduras-US Bjt   08-13 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honduras-US, Bjt,0711</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduras Urges Joint U.S.-Soviet Mediation in Central America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduras' foreign minister accused
the United States of shirking its responsibility in bringing peace
to Central America, and he said the Reagan administration should
work with the Soviet Union on a plan to end the region's wars.
   Nicaragua's president, Daniel Ortega, offered Friday to hold new
peace talks with U.S.-supported Contra rebels either in Managua or
Washington. He said the government was ready to meet rebels in
Managua on Aug. 26-29.
   Adolfo Calero, a rebel leader, rejected Managua as the site for
talks but did not address the possibility of talks in Washington.
He demanded that Ortega attend any future negotiating sessions.
   Honduran Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras said the United
States' and Soviet Union's backing of warring parties in Central
America threatens the security of his nation, a key U.S. ally.
   ``The United States must assume responsibility as a
negotiator,'' he told The Associated Press in an interview Friday.
``There must be negotiations with the four Central American
democracies, the United States with Nicaragua, and the United
States with the Soviet Union.''
   His reference to democracies meant the U.S.-allied governments
in Guatemala, El Salvador, Costa Rica and Honduras.
   Contreras said Washington should develop a Central American
demilitarization plan with the Soviet Union.
   In El Salvador, the Soviets support guerrillas of the
Marxist-led Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, which has
waged an insurgency since 1980 against the U.S.-backed government
there.
   In Nicaragua, the United States has financed rebels, known as
Contras, since 1981 in an attempt to topple the leftist Sandinista
government, which is backed by the Soviet Union.
   Hundreds of thousands of refugees have sought refuge from both
wars in neighboring Honduras, and fighting occasionally has spilled
over into the country. In addition, the Contras have maintained
base camps in Honduras.
   About 1,000 Nicaraguan rebels in recent weeks have crossed into
Honduras in search of food and supplies distributed by the U.S.
Agency for International Development. They joined an estimated
250,000 Nicaraguan and El Salvadoran refugees already here.
   Contreras said he would rather see the Contras fed along the
border than roaming the interior. ``They are armed,'' he said.
   The foreign minister said superpower military assistance to the
region's rebels threatens his country.
   ``Every time the American Congress approves aid for the Contras,
the Soviet Union thinks it is justified in providing more to
Nicaragua,'' Contreras said.
   ``The net result is that Honduras, politically, socially,
economically and from the security point of view, is worse off in
1988 than we were in 1977,'' he said. ``Our main concern is
security. We need to re-establish the military equilibrium.''
   The U.S. Senate on Wednesday approved $27 million in
humanitarian aid for the Contras, with the possibility of $16
million in military supplies later.
   The Honduran armed forces total about 25,000. Nicaragua's army
numbers about 80,000, and the Salvadoran military totals more than
50,000.
   Honduras has allowed tens of thousands of American troops to
stage military maneuvers in its territory.
   U.S. military and economic assistance to Honduras increased from
less than $10 million before 1979 to about $200 million in 1988,
the foreign minister said. But he said the aid had not eased
Honduran security concerns.
   ``We allow the military maneuvers. They practice and they leave
and Honduras stays the same,'' Contreras said. ``On the other hand,
the Soviet goods come (to Nicaragua) and stay.''
   In remarks broadcast by the rebels' clandestine Radio
Liberacion, Calero set a number of conditions before the Contras
would return to the bargaining table, including the reopening of
Nicaragua's Roman Catholic station Radio Catolica and radio news
programs shut down by the Sandinistas in July.
   Calero also demanded the release of more than 40 jailed
opposition figures. He rejected the idea of holding peace talks in
Managua, but he did not mention Ortega's suggestion that they could
be held in Washington.
   Ortega called for renewed talks while on an official visit to
Ecuador. He also criticized the U.S. Congress for approving new aid
to the rebels, calling it an act of ``aggression.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
