<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Contras     08-13 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contras,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras And Civilians Leave Provincial Stronghold</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Honduras-US, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels fighting Nicaragua's leftist
Sandinista government fled a provincial stronghold for Honduras,
where the U.S. government is feeding hundreds of refugees from the
nearly 7-year-old war.
   Col. Enrique Bermudez, one of seven members of the Contra
directorate, said 25 fighters and 750 civilian supporters trekked
from central Chontales province for a month and crossed the steep
mountains and the Coco River separating Honduras and Nicaragua.
   He said Thursday night the exodus happened because ``we can't
feed the people there'' and added: ``It's better for them to leave
because the Sandinistas would harass them. We protect those
people.''
   Visitors ferried to the Honduran-Nicaraguan border by the U.S.
Agency For International Development, or AID, quoted some of the
Nicaraguan refugees as saying Contra leaders ordered them to leave.
   U.S. Embassy spokeswoman Anne Sigmund said AID was providing
food to about 300 refugees. ``That's the number we know crossed. We
understand more are coming,'' she said.
   CIA supply flights to the Contras inside Nicaragua ended Feb.
29, when a U.S. military assistance package ran out. The Honduran
government granted permission for the AID supplies to be
distributed to the refugees.
   Contras and Sandinistas estimated earlier this year that about
3,500 Contra fighters were in Chontales and receiving air drops of
basic food and military supplies. About 6,500 rebels are believed
to be along the Honduran border seeking supplies from AID.
   The Contra leadership is asking for renewed military aid from
Washington, saying peace negotiations with the Sandinistas are
deadlocked. The Senate on Wednesday approved $27 million in
humanitarian aid.
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega, on an official visit to
Ecuador, on Friday called approval of the aid package an act of
``aggression'' and proposed new peace talks with the rebels be held
Aug. 26-29.
   Adolfo Calero, a rebel leader, on Friday rejected Managua as the
site for peace talks and demanded Ortega personally attend any
future negotiating sessions.
   The Contras and the Sandinistas signed a cease-fire pact March
23 to seek a negotiated settlement to the civil war. Peace talks
broke down June 9 and a unilateral government extension of the
cease-fire ends Aug. 30.
</TEXT>
