<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese 1stLd-Writethru a0408 08-13 0790</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0408,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Lawmakers Criticize Meese's Final Order as Attorney
General</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To raise reference to procedures, moves 14th graf pvs, bgng
A
Justice, to 12th graf; Subs 18th graf pvs, Earlier in, to clarify
arguments against act; picks up 19th graf pvs, Meese, 56.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic lawmakers say departing Attorney
General Edwin Meese III's order calling for independent counsels to
investigate members of Congress suspected of criminal conduct is
unnecessary and vindictive.
   Meese, in his final act Friday after 3{ controversial years at
the Justice Department, said he wanted to ensure that legislators
and top executive branch officials be treated equally under the law.
   But legislators pointed out that Meese has established a system
with crucial differences for members of Congress.
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., said Meese had a good idea but he
``messed it up'' by stipulating that the attorney general _ not a
court _ would appoint the independent counsel.
   ``It's fine to have special independent counsels prosecute
members of Congress; in fact, that option is available now,'' said
Levin. ``But attorneys general ought to be able to use
court-appointed counsels and local U.S. attorneys.... It is that
authority Meese has attempted to eliminate today.''
   Meese, who has been the subject of two separate investigations
by independent counsels since he came to Washington as counselor to
President Reagan in 1981, said his action was not meant as a
parting shot at his critics in Congress.
   Instead, he said, ``Having all high officials covered by the
same general procedures makes good sense.''
   Top officials of the executive branch are covered by the 1978
Ethics in Government Act, which was designed to prevent any
conflict of interest charges in investigations of high-ranking
government employees.
   Members of Congress are not included specifically in the law
under which a three-judge panel names the independent counsel after
a preliminary investigation by the Justice Department.
   Under Meese's order, if the attorney general receives specific
and credible information indicating that a senator or congressman
has violated criminal law, he must launch a preliminary
investigation of up to 90 days.
   Based on the results of the preliminary probe, the attorney
general either can close the case or appoint an independent counsel
to investigate. The court would not make the appointment under
Meese's order.
   A Justice Department official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the order would require the attorney general to
follow these procedures if allegations were made against a
legislator. But Meese said that if the legislator was the subject
of a related criminal probe, that could take precedence.
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., chairman of a House Judiciary
subcommittee that reviews the ethics law, said Meese's order was
unnecessary because the act already allows the attorney general to
call for a special prosecutor.
   Frank said the order, signed after Congress had recessed until
after Labor Day, was a ``vindictive and petty act by a man who has
not shown any class since he came here.... One last mark of
irresponsible bitterness of a guy who messed up.''
   Meese said his authority to impose the rule derived from the
attorney general's power to appoint special prosecutors, as was
done in the Watergate scandal.
   He said he waited to sign the order until his successor, former
Pennsylvania Gov. Richard L. Thornburgh, was approved by the Senate
on Thursday so as not to cause Thornburgh any problems at his
confirmation hearings.
   Meese said he discussed the regulation with Thornburgh, and, ``I
believe he agrees with it.'' Thornburgh, who was sworn in at the
White House on Friday, could rescind the rule at any time.
   Earlier in the administration, Meese sought to have the ethics
act declared unconstitutional, but the Supreme Court upheld it June
29. The Justice Department argued the law usurps powers granted the
executive branch under the Constitution.
   Meese, 56, is leaving the government to serve as a distinguished
fellow at the Heritage Foundation, a conservative Washington think
tank, and at the Hoover Institution at Stanford University in
California. He also intends to hit the lecture circuit.
   While at the White House, Meese was investigated by independent
counsel Jacob Stein on allegations that he may have used his office
for personal gain. Stein brought no charges against Meese.
   More recently, independent counsel James McKay investigated
Meese on allegations of conflict of interest and looked into his
relationship with E. Robert Wallach, a lawyer who has been indicted
in a case involving Wedtech Corp., a defense contractor in the
Bronx, N.Y.
   McKay said last month that prosecution of Meese was unwarranted,
although the attorney general probably violated tax and
conflict-of-interest laws. Meese harshly criticized McKay's
comments and said the special counsel's report vindicated him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
