<HEAD>Civil Rights Commission Approves New Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Commission on Civil Rights backed by
a 5-1 vote President Reagan's selection of William Barclay Allen, a
California professor, as the agency's chairman.
   Allen, who has been criticized by civil rights groups, succeeds
Clarence M. Pendleton Jr., who died June 5.
   Allen, a professor of government at Harvey Mudd College in
Claremont, Calif., has served on the commission since April 1987.
He was an unsuccessful Republican candidate for the U.S. Senate in
1986.
   The 44-year-old Allen was designated by Reagan last Monday,
saying then that he will not allow the commission ``to become an
arm of the advocacy groups in the civil rights movement.''
