<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--China-Floods     08-13 0134</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--China-Floods,0136</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Year's Flooding Blamed For 1,406 Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Floods caused by typhoons and torrential rains
have killed 1,406 people this year and caused $1.2 billion damage,
the Central Flood Control Headquarters said today.
   Zhou Zhenxian, an official at the headquarters, said areas along
tributaries of the Yangtze River in southwest China, the coastal
province of Zhejiang, and Guangdong province in the south have been
particularly hard hit by the annual summer floods.
   Zhou said that as of Aug. 12, 1,406 people had lost their lives
and 17.3 million acres of farmland had been flooded.
   But Zhou said the death toll from floods was not high for this
time of year. He said 1,563 had died as of mid-August last year,
and 2,385 were killed in the same period in 1986.
</TEXT>
