<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea-Prisoners     08-13 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Prisoners,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Prisoners Released On Parole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today announced that 36
dissidents and more than 1,300 other convicts will be freed from
prison to mark the 43rd anniversary of the liberation of the Korean
Peninsula from Japan.
   The Justice Ministry said the dissidents will be released Sunday
on parole, along with 1,343 other non-political criminals.
   Aug. 15 marks the anniversary of the 1945 liberation of the
Korean Peninsula from 36 years of Japanese occupation.
   In June, the government released 46 political prisoners on
parole, including Kim Keun-tae, who received this year's Robert F.
Kennedy Award for Human Rights.
   Hundreds of political prisoners have been released from South
Korean prisons since June 29, 1987, when nationwide protests forced
the government to accept demands for democratic reforms.
   Opposition groups maintain there are more than 500 dissidents
imprisoned for political beliefs or anti-government activity.
</TEXT>
