<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MoslemClash     08-13 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Moslem Clash,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>19 Wounded in Clash Between Police and Moslem Extremists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem extremist swinging chains and hurling
stones battled riot police in a Cairo suburb, and 19 people,
including three police officers, were wounded, authorities said
today.
   A senior police official said more than 120 extremists were
involved in the incident Friday night. He said riot police fired
tear gas and used sticks to control the crowd and that more than 70
extremists were arrested.
   One police pickup truck was set ablaze, said the official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity in accordance with department
procedure.
   The official said the clash occurred outside a mosque in the
northeastern Cairo suburb of Ein Shams.
   He said police, acting on a tip, had gone to the Adam Mosque and
were waiting outside to detain a number of extremist suspects who
were meeting inside after evening prayers.
   The police action apparently was part of a nationwide security
operation that began after three Moslem fundamentalists serving
life terms in the 1981 assassination of President Anwar Sadat
escaped from a maximum-security prison in a Cairo suburb on July 17.
   Two of them have died in shootouts with police, and the third
was rearrested.
   ``The clash began after policemen moved to make arrests as the
extremists were leaving the mosque,'' the official said.
   In the fighting outside the mosque, which lasted less than half
an hour, the extremists hurled stones and flaming objects and used
chains against police who attacked with tear gas and sticks, the
police official said
   Three policemen were wounded, one seriously, and 16 civilians
suffered ``medium or minor injuries,'' he said. Some were taken to
hospitals, but he did not say how many.
</TEXT>
