<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EmpireStateFire     08-13 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Empire State Fire,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>1,500 Tourists Evacuated From Empire State Building</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A smoky two-alarm fire that climbed 16 floors
through a utility shaft to the top of the Empire State Building
forced the evacuation of 1,500 tourists and office workers and
temporarily knocked 11 radio stations off the air.
   Eight minor injuries were reported in Friday's blaze.
   ``There was no panic ... It was crowded but there was no
confusion. People acted very, very sensibly,'' said Nick Cavatoro,
spokesman for the 102-story building's owners.
   Both observation decks _ on the 86th and top floors _ of the
Manhattan landmark were to reopen this morning, Cavatoro said.
   Three firefighters were injured and one building occupant
suffered an arm laceration but refused treatment, Fire Department
spokesman John Mulligan said Friday afternoon. One of the injured
firemen was taken to St. Vincent's Hospital after he was overcome
by heat and smoke, Mulligan said. Four other firemen reportedly
were treated later for minor injuries.
   ``The greatest difficulty up there was the extreme heat and
humidity,'' said a sweat-soaked firefighter, Mark Keisey, of the
93-degree heat. ``At times it felt like we were on our last legs.''
   Eight FM radio stations whose antennas are atop the skyscraper
were knocked off the air for at least four hours, and three others
were off for an hour or less.
   ``There was lots and lots of smoke, but that's all. It was
coming out the vents,'' said Tracie Ricks, who works on the 65th
floor.
   The fire was discovered by building employees in a utility room
on the 86th floor, but a few minutes later it was found it had
burned its way up a shaft.
   Fifth Avenue traffic backed up for more than 20 blocks during
the firefighting, said Victor Ross of the city's Transportation
Department.
  
</TEXT>
