<HEAD>Hezbollah Official Denounces U.N. Resolution on Higgins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official of the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God, today attacked the U.N. Security
Council's call for the release of kidnapped U.S. Marine Lt. Col.
William R. Higgins.
   ``We denounce and condemn the U.N. Security Council which
accepted to allow such an agent (Higgins) to confront our people,''
said Abbas Mousawi, a ranking Hezbollah official.
   ``The arrest (of Higgins) was in defense of our nation's honor,
dignity and existence,'' Mousawi added in an interview with the
weekly An-Nahar Arab and International magazine.
   The Security Council on July 29 unanimously condemned
politically motivated kidnappings in the Middle East and appealed
for the immediate release of Higgins, who headed a 76-member U.N.
observer group in south Lebanon.
   Higgins, 43, of Danville, Ky., was abducted near the southern
port city of Tyre on Feb. 17.
   Higgins' pro-Iranian kidnappers, the underground Organization of
the Oppressed on Earth, said April 21 that he was to be tried on
charges of spying for the United States.
   The United States and the United Nations have denied the spying
charge.
   Bassam Abu Sharif, spokesman for the Palestine Liberation
Organization, said in an interview published July 8 that Higgins
was planning an operation before his abduction to rescue eight
American hostages.
   The 18 foreign hostages held by Hezbollah-affiliated factions in
Lebanon, in addition to the nine Americans, are three Britons, a
West German, an Italian, an Irishman, an Indian and two
unidentified men.
   The longest-held hostage is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   Lebanese and foreign security officials believe that Hezbollah,
made up of radical Shiite zealots loyal to Iran's Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini, is an umbrella for the hostage-holding groups.
   Asked whether Hezbollah would help in the release of the foreign
hostgages if it was asked to do so by Iran, Mousawi said: ``We are
not involved in this issue.'' He did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
