<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0632EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDS-DrugAbuse     08-13 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Drug Abuse,0744</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Abusers Respond to AIDS Risk Message, Study Suggests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Though needle drug abusers often change their
practices when told of the risks of AIDS, many still suffer immune
system damage that may make it difficult to ward off the disease, a
study suggests.
   Researchers also confirmed Friday that one's state of mind
affects the immune system, and suggested it may make a difference
with AIDS.
   The work was presented at the annual meeting of the American
Psychological Association.
   The change in drug practices is significant because drug users
are often thought not responsive to health warnings, said
researcher John Watters.
   His study, done in San Francisco, found users cut back on the
sharing of hypodermic needles, which can spread the AIDS virus,
cleaned their needles more and increased their use of condoms
during sex when told of the dangers.
   ``We found dramatic changes'' after a program to educate drug
users began in 1986, said Watters, of the Urban Health Study in San
Francisco.
   Intravenous drug abuse is blamed for about 19 percent of the
nation's cumulative total of some 70,000 cases of acquired immune
deficiency syndrome.
   Workers in the San Francisco program told drug abusers about
AIDS prevention measures, distributed condoms and gave out bleach
to disinfect needles.
   Researchers studied drug and condom practices of 386 drug users
interviewed in 1986 before the program began, and 545 users
interviewed in early 1987 some eight months after the start of the
program. An additional 534 were sampled later in 1987, and 553 in
early 1988.
   Use of ``safe needle hygiene'' rose from 13 percent of the time
drugs were used before the outreach program to 63 percent
afterward. Safe hygiene was defined as using bleach, alcohol,
hydrogen peroxide or boiling water to disinfect needles, or not
sharing needles.
   The follow-up surveys found hygiene used 70 percent of the time
in late 1987 and 71 percent in early 1988.
   The estimated number of sharing partners dropped from an average
of 11 before the outreach program to eight in early 1987, with nine
and five reported in the following two surveys.
   Condom use rose from 3 percent of the time before the outreach
program to 16 percent afterwards, with 23 percent in each of the
follow-up surveys.
   Blood tests found that the rate of users exposed to the AIDS
virus jumped from 6 percent in early 1986 to 13 percent in early
1987, with 9 percent and 11 percent in the following two surveys.
   James Sorensen of the University of California, San Francisco,
who has studied AIDS prevention among drug users in treatment, said
Watters' results on behavioral change ring true.
   But, he warned, `` We need to work very hard to reach people who
haven't been reached.''
   The study of drug users in treatment focused on 30 outpatients
in a long-term methadone program. None had been infected with the
AIDS virus, said Nancy Klimas of the University of Miami School of
Medicine and the Veterans Administration Medical Center in Miami.
   But they showed significant deficiencies in the functioning of
their disease-fighting immune system, she said. For example, the
functioning of their ``natural killer cells'' was about half of
normal, she said.
   Poor nutrition, non-AIDS infections, prior drug abuse or perhaps
the methadone may be responsible, but no cause has yet been found,
she said.
   Don Des Jarlais of the New York State Division of Substance
Abuse Services said previous research has shown that immune
abnormalities in drug users can take years to disappear once they
enter methadone treatment.
   Klimas' study also found that immune system function was better
by several measures in abusers who showed greater ``hardiness,''
defined as commitment to life, a feeling of control and a tendency
to see stresses as challenges.
   Loneliness and confusion were associated with poorer immune
system performance, she said. But no cause-and-effect conclusion
can be drawn from any of the psychological data, she cautioned.
   Another study released Friday found that for homosexual men soon
after AIDS infection, immune system functioning was better in men
determined to get on with life, who focused on and expressed their
emotions, and who had a feeling of psychological robustness.
   Again, no cause-and-effect conclusions can yet be drawn, said
Nancy Blaney of the University of Miami School of Medicine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880813-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0650EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     08-13 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLAINS, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don't mention the idea of selling ice to
the Eskimos to 8-year-old Cody Carr. It might give him more ideas,
and he's too young to run an empire in the the arctic.
   Surrounded by an invasion of grasshoppers in the ranchland of
western Montana, the youngster has cleared $875 in the last month _
selling grasshoppers to fishermen.
   The infestation of grasshoppers began on his parents' ranch near
Plains in July. Wave after wave of hoppers moved through the area,
munching crops, grass and trees.
   But one day, watching the latest wave sweep by, ``I was
thinking, `How can I make money off 'em?''' he recalled this week.
``I went to my mom and asked if I could start a business. I could
sell 'em for fishing bait.''
   With tens of thousands of hoppers jumping free just outside,
Vikki Carr says she was skeptical.
   ``I didn't think we'd sell very many,'' she said.
   But she agreed, as much to keep a bored 8-year-old occupied as
for any other reason. And the next morning, when the hoppers were
logy from the morning chill, they started harvesting.
   As of Aug. 10, Cody, his mother and some helpers had collected
95,000 hoppers from the yard and nearby fields. He sold 1,200
packages _ 28,800 hoppers at two dozen per bag _ to sporting goods
stores in seven western states.
   The money _ $875 so far, after marketing, distribution and
packaging _ is in a college fund. And, Cody's mother says, more
money is coming in every day.
   ``We can barely keep up,'' she said. ``We're getting calls from
all over.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VALENCIA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Symbolizing life's ups and downs, a
couple's mutual infatuation with roller coasters and each other led
to an oddball wedding aboard the Colossus thrill-ride at Six Flags
Magic Mountain.
   Michael Ball, 24, and Debbie Beller, 38, who met two years ago
at a bowling alley, recited vows in the front car Friday with the
Rev. Bill Wood, best man Tom Swartz, maid of honor Dawna Beller and
21 other guests riding behind.
   ``By starting their marriage on a roller coaster they must vow
to ride through life together in motion sickness and in health, as
well as through bumps, jumps and the 110-foot drops that life can
bring,'' the minister said.
   The ceremony began in the passenger loading station at the
amusement park north of Los Angeles and ended 3{ minutes later when
the white-knuckle chapel-on-wheels returned.
   At the ride's conclusion, the couple was pronounced man and
wife, and they kissed.
   ``Although this seems like an unusual wedding ceremony, we
thought it would be a thrilling way to start our new life
together,'' said the black tuxedoed Ball.
   ``This is the most exciting day of my life. Marrying Michael on
Colossus is a dream come true for me,'' said Debbie, wearing a
white gown and veil. ``Life is made of ups and downs, and what
better way to celebrate our commitment to one another than on a
roller coaster.''
   Ball is a computer technician and his wife is a billing clerk.
The Balls will live in Buena Park, Calif., upon return from their
honeymoon, which will consist of a weekend of roller coaster riding
at Magic Mountain.
</TEXT>
