<DOCNO> AP880813-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0654EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Meese-Giuliani     08-13 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Giuliani,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outgoing Meese Criticizes New York Prosecutor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Meese, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani defended an
assistant's use of the word ``sleaze'' to describe outgoing
Attorney General Edwin Meese III after Meese called the comment
``first-year law student stuff.''
   In his last day on the job Friday after 3{ controversial years
at the Justice Department, Meese blasted Giuliani and Assistant
U.S. Attorney Edward Little for the remark, made by Little during
his closing arguments in the racketeering trial of U.S. Rep. Mario
Biaggi.
   ``I think it was poor procedure and poor practice by any
prosecutor,'' Meese said in Washington. ``And I think that any
prosecutor who did that undermines his own case.''
   The trial, which stemmed from scandals surrounding the
Bronx-based Wedtech Corp., ended last week with convictions against
Biaggi and four others.
   The defense had based its case in part on assertions that
corrupt Wedtech executives had connections to high-ranking Reagan
administration officials, like Meese, and thus did not need the
help of Biaggi or his co-defendants in securing government
contracts.
   However, Little called the ``Meese defense'' a smokescreen,
surprising the courtroom by conceding ``Meese is a sleaze'' while
adding that that should not detract from the guilt or innocence of
the defendants.
   Giuliani said Little's words were ``as if they were my own.''
   Near the end of the trial, a special prosecutor in Washington
announced there was insufficient evidence to charge Meese with any
wrongdoing, but he questioned his ethics on several issues. Meese
announced his resignation after the report was completed, saying it
exonerated him.
   Giuliani said Friday the ``sleaze'' comment was ``fully
supported by the record in this case.'' He added that he was
``ready to defend it, anytime, anywhere, anyplace.''
   Little said that, ``had (Meese) been a reputable attorney
general, we wouldn't have had to make that remark.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
