<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Disasters     08-13 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Disasters,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>30 Killed As Two Buses Collide; Quakes Rock Southern Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two buses collided in northern Iran,
killing 30 people and injuring 50, Tehran radio reported today.
   The radio also said two strong earthquakes jolted the southern
city of Bushehr, but no injuries or damage was immediately reported.
   A nuclear power station is under construction close to the city,
but the state-run radio did not mention the facility in its brief
report.
   The two buses collided on the heavily traveled Tehran-Tabriz
highway on Friday, the report said without providing further
details.
   The earthquakes centered in Bushehr measured 6 and 6.2 on the
Richter scale, the radio reported in a broadcast monitored in
Nicosia.
   It did not say when the quakes occurred.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means the ground motion
is 10 times greater.
   A quake of magnitude 6 can cause severe damage.
</TEXT>
