<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ForestFires     08-13 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Forest Fires,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Helps Firefighters in Yellowstone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first significant
rainfall since Memorial Day helped cool fires burning in nearly
200,000 acres of the nation's oldest park, and all roads, hotels
and campgrounds were open today.
   In California, the pilot of a U.S. Forest Service plane was
killed Friday when his plane crashed while working a 1,700-acre
fire in the Sequoia National Forest near Bakersfield, authorities
said. Another firefighter died, apparently of a heart attack,
battling a fast-moving wildfire in Oregon.
   Fires also burned in Idaho and Montana.
   Yellowstone got about two hours of intermittent rain Friday
afternoon, park spokeswoman Joan Anzelmo said.
   ``One short rain shower is not adequate to douse the fires. But
it does help increase humidity in the air and it helps slow the
fires down,'' said Anzelmo.
   The temperature in Yellowstone cooled down Friday afternoon, the
wind slowed and firefighters made some progress, she said.
   The 40,000-acre North Fork fire was the only blaze to grow
Friday, increasing about 3,000 acres. The fire had caused the
closing of the road from Madison Junction to Old Faithful on
Thursday, but was reopened Friday morning. Tourist activity in
Yellowstone remained high, Anzelmo said, despite the fires.
   ``We are continuing to see a very busy park with campgrounds and
hotels each night,'' she said. ``But the last two days, there have
been fairly smoky conditions in the park and the vicinity, so that
has been difficult for everyone.''
   In Montana, cool, cloudy weather slowed a 2,800-acre fire
burning in the Elkhorn Mountains southeast of Helena. Fire crews
continued the slow work of building fire lines by hand in steep
terrain, officials said. The cool weather also helped 125
firefighters battling an 8,000-acre grass and range fire southeast
of Dillon.
   Firefighters contended with winds gusting up to 25 mph as they
fought to control a fast-moving Oregon wildfire that destroyed a
mobile home and a refrigerated storage building near the community
of Mosier in the Columbia River Gorge.
   In central Wyoming on the Wind River Indian Reservation,
officials said a 1,000-acre sagebrush, grass and timber fire was
more than 70 percent contained.
   The lightning-caused fire began Thursday and was expected to be
controlled by Sunday, according to Bureau of Indian Affairs
officials. About 50 to 60 firefighters were on the scene north of
Riverton.
   Idaho's national forests have dropped their ``let-burn'' policy
on wilderness lands because of the drought and are sending hundreds
of firefighters to spot fires caused by a second round of lightning
storms.
   A quarter-inch of rain Friday helped dampen the raging
2,600-acre Walker Creek fire that threatened the town of Inkom in
southeastern Idaho.
   ``It was very significant in putting it down so we could work on
it,'' Caribou National Forest spokesman Frank Carroll said.
   The fire acreage was revised from 4,000 to about 2,600 Friday
night, he said.
</TEXT>
