<HEAD>South Africa Threatens To Expel Argentine Consul</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today said it will
expel Argentina's consul within 30 days unless the South American
country rescinds its expulsion order against a South African consul.
   The threat was contained in a message Minister of Foreign
Affairs Pik Botha sent from Vienna, where he is holding a meeting
on whether South Africa will sign the nuclear non-proliferation
treaty.
   Botha said Argentine Consul H.R. Basso will be given the same
amount of time to leave the nation as South Africa's consul, Dirk
de Wet, was given, unless Argentina reconsiders its expulsion order.
   Argentina earlier in the week ordered de Wet and three other
South Africans out of the country for allegedly violating their
visas. The government said they asked to visit Argentina for talks
with the consul, then participated in a pro-South Africa seminar
organized by the consulate.
   The three men have already left Argentina.
   They are Department of Foreign Affairs Deputy Chief Director of
Communication Planning Gerrit Olivier; the deputy leader of the
mixed-race house of Parliament, Miley Richards; and black mayor
Bennet Ndlazi of Mamelodi.
   Botha said he had instructed his department to summon Basso and
tell him that Argentina's action against de Wet was unreasonable
and unjustifiable.
   ``If a South African representative abroad does not even have
the right to invite guests to be briefed on South Africa, then such
representation is meaningless,'' said Botha.
</TEXT>
