<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Bombs, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0484,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Injured In Two Explosions in South Africa</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with 2 others slightly injured,
security guard hospitalized; CORRECTS that two victims in Pinetown
bombing were mixed-race sted white; ADDS background on apartheid.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mine exploded today in a
shopping center, injuring a black security guard and two whites,
police said.
   On Friday night, a similar device exploded outside a post
office, and police said three people were slightly injured.
   Shopkeepers denied earlier police reports that the Hyde Park
shopping center had been evacuated just before the 11:35 a.m.
explosion.
   A woman shopkeeper saw a parcel outside a clothing boutique and
notified a security guard, but it exploded before he reached it,
said a nearby shopkeeper, speaking on condition of anonymity. He
said there was no loudspeaker warning.
   The security guard was hospitalized, and a white man and woman
were slightly injured. Police said the explosion at the
Johannesburg mall was caused by a limpet mine, which can be
attached to another surface.
   Another limpet mine exploded at 8:15 p.m. Friday in a trash bin
outside the post office on the main commercial street in Pinetown,
near Durban.
   A post office spokesman said that a newly hired cleaner had
saved the building from greater damage because he failed to bring
all the trash bins inside the building.
   The mine exploded in one of the bins that was left outside. It
caused about $15,000 damage and slightly injured two mixed-race men
and a black man making telephone calls from booths outside the post
office, police said.
   There have been nearly 100 bomb explosions in the country since
a national state of emergency was declared June 12, 1986.
   Police blame most of the explosions on the outlawed African
National Congress, the main guerrilla group fighting to overthrow
the white-dominated government and its system of apartheid.
   The ANC seldom comments on individual bombings but says the
bombing and sabotage campaign is part of its strategy.
   Censorship rules imposed under the emergency ruled ban or
restrict reporting about unrest, security force actions, treatment
of detainees, most forms of peaceful protest and a broad range of
statements the government considers subversive.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 26 million black majority has no
vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy
and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
