<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Obit-Passman     08-13 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Passman,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Congressman Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONROE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Otto E. Passman, a fourth grade dropout who
spent 30 years in Congress fighting foreign aid in particular and
government in general, died today in a hospital. He was 88.
   An outspoken convervative Democrat, Passman was the powerful
chairman of the House Appropiations subcommittee on foreign
operations for 22 years, from 1954-76.
   In 15 congressional elections, the Monroe businessman faced no
serious election challenges. But in 1976, Passman, in his 70s, ran
in the Democratic primary against Rep. Jerry Huckaby of Ringgold, a
youthful dairy farmer.
   Assailed by accusations he cheated on his congressional expense
accounts and browbeat foreign governments in grain deals, Passman
lost his re-election bid by more than 8,000 votes.
   Before the election Passman had been accused of padding his
travel expense accounts by claiming the more remunerative
automobile gasoline mileage for his trips to his home district,
although he actually traveled by airplane.
   Passman denied any intent to defraud and repaid the difference.
   Passman also denied more serious allegations of misusing his
office by persuading foreign governments into shipping their rice
in ships owned by the St. John Maritime Co. of California.
</TEXT>
