<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Kill One Palestinian, Wound Three in Gaza Strip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops opened fire today to disperse
stone-throwing Palestinian demonstrators in the Gaza Strip and
killed a 52-year-old man, the army and hospital officials said.
   Military officials said the demonstrators were protesting the
deaths of two Gaza Strip Arab workers in an arson fire Tuesday.
   In the West Bank, a Palestinian collaborator with Israel shot
and wounded three Palestinians from the village of Beitin near
Tulkarm, an official at Rafidiyeh Hospital in Nablus told The
Associated Press.
   Today's fatality brought the Palestinian death toll to 241 since
Palestinians launched a rebellion against Israeli rule in the
occupied territories on Dec. 8, 1987. Four Israelis have also died
in the violence.
   An Arab reporter said Palestinians in the Gaza Strip refrained
from using cars, buses and taxis today to protest Israeli orders
calling on them to buy new automobile license plates. Many stores
were shuttered in Gaza City.
   In the vegetable market of Rafah, on the Egyptian border,
protesters hurled stones at Israeli troops who opened fire to
disperse them, an army spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   One protester was killed and three wounded, including a
15-year-old girl, the spokesman and officials at Nasser hospital in
Khan Yunis said. The officials identified the dead man as Mohammed
Eid Abu Rizek, 52.
   Rioting later spread to Khan Yunis where five protesters were
shot and wounded in their legs, said hospital officials, also
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The army clamped curfews on four neighborhoods in Rafah, the
military spokesman said.
   Military officials said demonstrators were protesting the deaths
Tuesday of two Gaza Strip Arab workers. The workers were asleep in
a shack in Tel Aviv when it caught fire. Police said the fire,
which seriously injured a third man, was set deliberately.
   Another Arab reporter said three Palestinians from the village
of Beitin were shot and wounded by an Arab known to collaborate
with Israel.
   The reporter identified the assailant as Sadek Bele of the
village of Funduq, near Nablus. He said Bele shot at a Palestinian
flag hanging on a telephone pole and when villagers rushed toward
him, he shot at them.
   An official at Rafidiyeh Hospital in Nablus said one of the
wounded men, Taisir Ghanem, 18, who was hit in the groin and
operated on, said he was shot by a collaborator. Another
Palestinian was shot in the head and seriously wounded in the
incident, the official said.
   A district police spokesman, Yosef Fares, told The Associated
Press he was not authorized to answer questions on the incident.
The army spokesman said he had no details about the incident.
   In another development, three Arab workers were severely beaten
Friday by Jewish assailants while at work collecting garbage in the
Tel Aviv suburb of Givat Shmuel, the Israeli-owned Itim news agency
reported.
   The assailants also attacked the Arabs' Jewish employer who
rushed to the aid of his workers and smashed the windows of his
truck, the agency said.
   The attack was unprovoked, Itim reported.
</TEXT>
