<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-Bombs     08-13 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Bombs,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspected Basque Terrorists Bomb French Businesses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected Basque terrorists set off bombs
at six French-owned auto dealerships and a dairy in northern Spain
today, causing extensive damage but no injuries, government
officials said.
   Police defused bombs at two other car dealerships and searched
for bombs along a northern railroad line where an explosion ripped
up rails, said the officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   No one has claimed responsibility for the attacks. The officials
said they suspected the Basque terrorist group ETA, which has
attacked French-linked targets in the past to protest expulsions of
members of its group from France. ETA normally waits several days
before claiming responsibilities for bombings.
   The explosions occurred between 5 a.m. and 7 a.m. in the
northern provinces of Alava, Logrono, and Santander.
   In Santander, bombs ripped through a Renault and two Peugeot
dealerships, destroying cars and mechanical equipment, Renault
spokeswoman Carmen Sollet said. A bomb also damaged the Larresse
dairy in El Astillero, she said.
   Ms. Sollet said damage was in the millions of dollars and the
bombs appeared to be a type used by the terrorists. She said police
defused a bomb at a second Renault dealership in Santander.
   Bombs also went off at Renault dealerships in the towns of
Logrono and Haro. An worker at the Logrono site said the explosion
destroyed the ground floor, blowing out an iron door and destroying
cars.
   In the town of La Guardia in Alava, a bomb caused an estimated
$200,000 damage at a Renault dealership, the civil governor's
office said.
   Also in Logrona, police exploded a bomb they found at a Citroen
dealership after receiving a telephone warning, the civil
governor's office said.
   Police were searching for bombs along a northern railroad line,
where an explosion ripped up some tracks and interrupted service
between the cities of Logrono and Castejon, the government
officials said.
   News reports speculated the attacks may be linked to the
kidnapping by ETA six months ago of Basque businessman Emiliano
Revilla. The reports said his family had sent ransom payments
intended for Basque terrorists in France, which ETA has been unable
to collect because of heavy surveillance by French police.
   ETA, which stands for Homeland and Liberty in the Basque
language, seeks independence from Spain for the Basque region that
includes the provinces of Alava, Santander and Logrono.
   The group has claimed responsibility for killing more than 600
people, mostly police, military and civil guard officers, since it
began its violent struggle in 1968. Since June 1986, the French
government has expelled more than 165 alleged ETA members.
</TEXT>
