<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0410 08-13 0845</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0410,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Narrows VP List; Dukakis Knocks Bush On Environment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 5 grafs, picking up in 3rd graf pvs, The
rival; trims from end</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush, days away from receiving his party's
presidential nomination, has narrowed his list of potential running
mates, an informed source said today. Democrat Michael Dukakis
tagged Bush a ``George-come-lately'' on the environment.
   Bush met Friday with top advisers to discuss the decision on the
No. 2 spot on the GOP ticket. One participant in the meeting,
speaking only on condition of anonymity, said the list now has been
trimmed drastically from the original 16 names.
   While the source declined to name all the individuals under
consideration, the list was believed to include Senate Republican
Leader Bob Dole of Kansas; his wife, former Transportation
Secretary Elizabeth Dole; Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana; Sen. Alan
Simpson of Wyoming; Sen. Pete Domenici of New Mexico and Rep. Jack
Kemp of New York.
   The source said at least one other individual was under active
consideration. But the adviser refused to identify the prospect.
   Meanwhile, in New Orleans where workmen and party officials were
putting the final red, white and blue touches on a convention
designed as a show of the passing of control from President Reagan
to his designated successor, the GOP platform committee completed
work on a 30,000-word document Friday that described the election
as a choice between ``change and progress with the Republicans or
change and chaos with the Democrats.''
   The rival presidential candidates were out of the public eye
after an active day of campaigning Friday.
   At the vice president's residence in Washington, Bush worked on
his acceptance speech.
   Dukakis was spending a weekend at the beach after a five-state
campaign swing during which he blamed rising interest rates on
Reagan budget deficits and criticized Bush as a latecomer on
environmental issues.
   The Democratic nominee said he had opposed new offshore drilling
for oil and gas and noted his efforts to block drilling off
Massachusetts.
   ``I'm not a George-come-lately on this issue,'' said Dukakis.
   The Dukakis campaign also started broadcasting a television
commercial in California and Texas that touted his record as
governor of Massachusetts and said the state's prosperity ``wasn't
a miracle, it was leadership.''
   Republicans were arriving in New Orleans by the planeload for a
convention to celebrate Reagan's presidency and to proclaim Bush
his rightful successor.
   Reagan was to arrive in the convention city Sunday and be the
featured speaker Monday night.
   Bush won't arrive in New Orleans until Tuesday, the day before
he will be nominated without opposition for president.
   Television evangelist Pat Robertson announced he would not have
his name placed in nomination and would release his 93 delegates.
   Barbara Gattullo, an aide, said that when Robertson addresses
the convention Tuesday night, he will ``call for unity.''
   A comic book accusing Dukakis of supporting witchcraft and
bestiality and portraying him wearing a dress, wig and pearls, came
under fire Friday from John Buchanan, chairman of People for the
American Way, a liberal activist group, who urged Bush and the GOP
to repudiate 30-page book.
   Buchanan said that ``the last thing the Bush campaign, the
Republican Party and the presidential campaign need is the
distribution of 10 million copies of a comic book that's chock full
of enough intolerance to offend just about everyone except Jerry
Falwell,'' founder of the conservative Moral Majority, who
introduced the book at a rally Thursday night.
   Elephants, the traditional Republican symbol, were the animal of
choice throughout the convention city. Gray elephants, red, white
and blue elephants, cuddly elephants and inflatable elephants, even
a giant elephant perched atop the hotel overlooking the Superdome,
the enclosed stadium where the convention will take place.
   Workmen laid red, white and blue strips of carpeting across the
plaza between the hotel and the entrance to the Superdome.
   For Bush, the convention was an opportunity to cut the lead
Dukakis has held in opinion polls. Most recent surveys have said
the Democratic candidate was favored among likely voters by margins
ranging from 7 to 14 percentage points.
   But one new poll, released Friday by ABC News, said the race was
statistically deadlocked with Bush favored by 49 percent and
Dukakis by 46 percent, a difference well within the 6-point margin
of error.
   The convention rules committee approved changes that would allow
governors and members of Congress to be seated on the floor of the
1992 convention.
   Rep. Robert Dornan, R-Calif., said it would be good to let the
politicians be seated on the floor of the convention so they could
``rub elbows with the backbone of the party.''
   When the platform draft was completed, GOP leaders boasted that
they, unlike the Democrats, had come up with a document filled with
substance.
   ``We have Michael Dukakis the stealth candidate and the
Democratic Party the stealth party,'' former Rep. Tom Loeffler of
Texas told reporters. ``We're saying what we're going to do. ...
The Democratic platform reflects `Be quiet. Hide. Hide.'''
</TEXT>
