<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 1043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iraq-Hussein Bjt   08-13 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Hussein, Bjt,0751</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cease-Fire Strengthens Iraqi Ruler</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqis fired in the air and danced in the
streets last week to celebrate a cease-fire in the war with Iran,
signs that President Saddam Hussein has emerged from the eight-year
conflict stronger than ever.
   The 51-year-old ruler, a pragmatic populist utterly ruthless to
his foes, now can return to his dream of making oil-rich Iraq a
modern economic and political power.
   The struggle with Iran was Hussein's war. Iraq invaded Iran in
September 1980, only a year after he came to power, after border
skirmishes.
   On July 18, Iran accepted a U.N. cease-fire resolution that Iraq
accepted soon after it was passed a year ago. The cease-fire is set
to begin officially on Aug. 20.
   Iraq's state-run information services are doing all they can to
declare victory. Hundreds of thousands of Iraqis flooded the
streets to dance and fire weapons, responding to government calls
to celebrate ``the day of peace and victory.''
   Only 18 months ago, Iranian forces were pounding at the defenses
of Iraq's second city, Basra, and foreign analysts suggested Iraq
might crack. Western newspapers suggested outsiders should topple
Hussein to fulfill Iranian demands for halting the war.
   Instead, the war seems to have ended in a string of Iraqi
victories over an Iranian war machine drained by the costly attacks
on Basra.
   Hussein holds the loyalty of Iraq's ethnically mixed population
despite a war that cost hundreds of thousands of lives and hundreds
of billions of dollars.
   Before the war, the president already had a firm grip on power
in Iraq, plagued by political instability for years before the
Baath Party took control in 1968.
   Hussein quickly executed opponents within the leadership shortly
after assuming power in 1979 and crushed pro-Iranian religious
fundamentalists in 1980.
   Mindful of numerous coups against past governments and perhaps
his own past as an underground fighter, Hussein has used a huge
security service to keep watch over dissent.
   He also has promoted relatives to several key positions in the
government and military, although he has been quick to dump those
who proved incompetent or disloyal.
   ``The man who leads the Iraqis must be of a quick and nimble
pace,'' Hussein said in 1982, ``so the others will not step on his
heels, then his back, then step on his head and pass him over.''
   Hussein himself took part in an unsuccessful 1959 assassination
attempt against then-President Abdul-Karim Qassem.
   The son of poor farmers, Hussein has combined an iron hand with
a populist appeal. He has a reputation for hard work, bravery and
personal honesty.
   State television often spends a half hour or more showing the
president sitting on a floor chatting with peasants or bouncing
children on his knee. The government has encouraged a cult of
personality around him.
   Yet Hussein told American researcher Christine Helms in 1982
that after watching party members scrambling for power in the
mid-1960s: ``I developed an aversion to power. ... I began to
loathe it.''
   Hussein's outlook was forged by his climb through the
underground politics of the Baath Party, which advocates Arab
unity, socialist economics and rejection of foreign domination.
   His policies are essentially pragmatic. He told Ms. Helms he
``did not think I had to be basically concerned'' with ideology
until 1974, when he was already a senior force in the party.
   Hussein has gradually improved ties with the West and has
demanded attention to profits and discipline in the country's
sluggish state enterprises.
   He is also supremely self-confident. In 1964, still in his 20s,
he led a revolt against the old party leadership, which was in
disarray after being driven from power.
   While in hiding, ``I issued a communique on behalf of the
party's provisional regional command, which did not exist, giving
myself the authority to lead the party,'' he told Helms.
   The war interrupted Hussein's massive effort to use Iraq's oil
wealth to make the country a modern power.
   ``He has lost 10-odd years of his rule in which he could have
literally transformed the country,'' said a senior diplomat in
Baghdad who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``They have given a glimpse of the future to their masses,'' and
with the war over, ``I think they will be in a hurry to start
building,'' he said.
</TEXT>
