<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 1043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HusseinCult     08-13 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hussein Cult,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hussein Is Object Of Massive Personality Cult</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iraq-Hussein, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi officials have created one of the
world's strongest personality cults around President Saddam Hussein.
   Massive murals and portraits of the president peer down over
streets throughout the country. Television is dominated by songs in
praise of the president or film of his visits to the countryside.
   Hussein's photograph beams from the front page of every
newspaper. Airports, art galleries, sports tournaments and literary
prizes are named for him.
   Poets and singers often recite his praises for hours a day on
the television.
   Even the eight-year war with Iran was called ``Saddam's
Qadissiyeh,'' a reference to the 7th century triumph of Islamic
armies in Iraq over the Persian predecessors of modern Iran.
   Members of the ruling Arab Baath Socialist Party must take tests
on the president's works. Diplomats say criticism of the president
can lead to prison.
   Hussein himself commented on the strength of this cult of
personality in a 1983 interview with Kuwaiti reporters. In the
interview, published by Iraq's state printing house, he insisted he
did not inspire the cult.
   ``For seven years now I have been pressing them (information
media) hard to slow down where the topic of Saddam Hussein is
concerned,'' he said. ``They answer by saying that Saddam Hussein
must be a symbol to all Iraqis.
   ``There are several religions, sects and ethnic groups in Iraq.
Consequently, our media have to take this factor into consideration
and arrange matters in such a way that each of these groups has a
share ... in the person of Saddam Hussein.
   ``Have you come across an Iraqi child, in a kindergarten or at
school, that does not mention the name of Saddam Hussein in the
nursery rhyme or the school song he or she sings? Is there a poet
with a poem that does not mention the name of Saddam Hussein X
number of times? Have you heard of a peasant who does not mention
the name of Saddam Hussein when mentioning the revolution?'' he
said in the interview.
   ``You may speak to the Iraqi women, particularly those who are
widows of martyrs. They will tell you that their husbands have
given their lives in honor of, and in sacrifice to, not the
homeland but first to Saddam Hussein, then the homeland and then
the revolution.
   ``We are in fact experiencing difficulty in asking kindergarten
children and schoolboys and girls to leave the name of Saddam
Hussein from the wordings of their rhymes and songs,'' Hussein said
in the interview.
   ``If the case we are talking about were not truly genuine,
people would not tolerate it for more than six months at most,
after which it would be thrown overboard.''
</TEXT>
