<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Bush-Veep Bjt   08-13 0911</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Bush-Veep, Bjt,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Keeping the Suspense on Veep Choice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush knows all about the frantic
suspense surrounding late announcements of a presidential nominee's
running mate. He got his own 11th-hour call from Ronald Reagan in
1980.
   Now, he's doing his best to keep a dozen or so Republicans on
the same edge.
   With his silence on a vice presidential choice, Bush is
providing the only element of suspense in an otherwise suspenseless
Republican National Convention.
   Bush says he hopes to make up his mind before he gets to New
Orleans _ even if he doesn't announce that decision until Wednesday
or Thursday _ but aides insist the vice president still has not
decided.
   He was working on his campaign acceptance speech Saturday while
still keeping his own counsel on the vice presidential selection
process.
   ``It's all being done mainly by the vice president,'' said his
campaign manager, Lee Atwater. The campaign's pollster, Robert
Teeter, is ``helping him to a certain extent on the process,'' but
even he won't know in advance whom Bush will select, Atwater said.
   Nor will his new campaign manager, James A. Baker III, who was
out of town on Saturday, Atwater and other campaign aides suggested.
   ``He's made it clear to all of us that he wants to make this
decision on his own,'' Atwater said. ``He knows the players; he
knows the candidates. And he's ultimately going to make the
decision himself. And I don't anticipate he's going to share it
with anybody except maybe his wife on Wednesday.''
   On that score, Bush has joked that if he talks in his sleep in
the meantime, ``we could be in real trouble.''
   So the waiting game goes on for the dozen or so ``players''
known to be under what campaign aides call ``active consideration.''
   These run across the full spectrum of Republicans, both
geographically and politically:
   _Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., Bush's principal former rival for the
GOP nomination. His strongest point, say Bush campaign aides, is
his popularity across the Midwest. But these aides also say they
are fearful that Democrats would seize on Dole's bitter attacks on
Bush during the primary campaigns to use as campaign ammuniton.
   _Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., another vanquished primary rival but a
favorite among conservatives. Campaign aides say Kemp could also
help bring in blue-collar Democratic votes and would help with
California, but they see his inability to muster votes in the GOP
primaries as a drawback.
   _Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., the assistant Senate Republican
leader and a longtime close friend and fishing partner of Bush. He
could help in the West, but Simpson himself has suggested his
previous support for freezing Social Security benefit increases
could be a liability.
   _Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind., a dark-horse contender added to the
list more recently. Bush campaign aides suggest he is being
seriously considered, both as a fresh face and for his base in the
Midwest.
   _Elizabeth Hanford Dole, former transportation secretary and the
wife of Bob Dole, who appears to be the only woman remaining under
consideraton from an original list that included Sen. Nancy
Kassebaum of Kansas, Rep. Lynn Martin of Illinois and Supreme Court
Justice Sandra Day O'Connor.
   _Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., the top-ranking Budget Committee
Republican who has earned a reputation for deficit-fighting. With
his Italian name, he could also bring ethnic appeal to the ticket.
But some Republicans feel he's too open to a tax increase.
   _Gov. Tom Kean of New Jersey and Attorney General Richard
Thornburgh, who is a former governor of Pennsylvania. Aides suggest
both men could help bring in the votes of moderates.
   Financial data has also been requested from New Hampshire Gov.
John Sununu, South Carolina Gov. Carroll A. Campbell, former
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and Sen. John C. Danforth, R-Mo.
   Govs. George Deukmejian of California and James Thompson of
Illinois had figured in earlier speculation, but both have asked
that they not be considered.
   Lt. Gen. Colin L. Powell, the first black ever to hold the post
of national security adviser, was not among the candidates Bush
campaign officials indicated were under active consideration. But
his name his turned up as a long-shot contender in some recent
speculation.
   Rep. Jim Leach of Iowa, a moderate Republican and Bush adviser,
said that Bush was making the ``right choice'' in holding off a
decision, although he added: ``I don't think he's decided. It's
easy to hold off something if you haven't made your choice.''
   Bush himself was selected as Reagan's running mate late on the
next-to-final day of the 1980 Republican convention, only after
negotiations to select former President Ford for the No. 2 spot had
broken down.
   ``I hope I'll make as good a choice, but I think I'll use a
different method,'' Bush has quipped. He has said he hopes his
process _ including delaying a final decision until almost the last
minute _ will not be ``demeaning to any of the people'' under
consideration.
   In his 1987 autobiography, Bush quotes Mark Twain on the subject
of the vice presidency: ``Two brothers: one went to sea and the
other became vice president. Neither was ever heard from again.''
   Still, Bush adds, ``The message is clear: Although everybody
belittles the office of the vice president, not many people turn it
down.''
   Choosing a vice president ``has always been one of the most
unpredictable rituals of modern American politics,'' the vice
president wrote.
</TEXT>
