<DOCNO> AP880813-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 1202EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--MeetTheFamily Bjt   08-13 0880</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Meet The Family, Bjt,960</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Clan Formidable Weapon in Campaign for White House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private man in public life, George Bush
admits to discomfort in discussing such personal matters as his
family. Typically, he calls them ``our gang'' and reverts to terms
coaches use for their best players.
   As well they may be. For as Bush heads into the fall campaign
against Michael Dukakis, his energetic brood is being unleashed as
a formidable political weapon.
   ``We're not political pros, but we've got political seasoning,''
says George W. Bush, the vice president's eldest son and a top
campaign strategist, in what may be a bit of understatement.
   The Bushes are veterans of many years spent in the public eye as
Bush trekked from Congress to diplomatic posts, in China and at the
United Nations, to the CIA and then to the No. 2 spot at the White
House.
   His wife Barbara has been described as an indefatigable
campaigner who shrugs off talk about herself, such as that she dye
her white hair, but bristles when her husband is criticized.
   George Jr. has run for Congress, with brother Neil his campaign
manager, and his other siblings are active in grass-roots party
politics. All are delegates at the GOP convention in New Orleans.
And all are actively involved in trying to get their father to the
top spot in the White House.
   Heading into the fall campaign, the family is increasingly
``speaking out about love'' that they have for each other, as
George Jr. puts it. In short, all the publicity about warm Dukakis
family relationships have not been lost on Bush strategists.
   ``We've had a very close family for years,'' says George Jr.
``I'm glad they have one too.''
   His father, who says his proudest accomplishment is that ``our
children still come home,'' believes his clan will do fine in the
political battle of the families.
   ``We're just getting our gang out onto the field,'' he said
recently aboard Air Force II. ``We will do all right if it gets
onto that.''
   On one August weekend, the family was at the summer home in
Kennebunkport, Maine, taping television advertisements highlighting
their relationship. The vice president admits that's something he's
not quite comfortable with.
   ``I haven't advertised this as much as I think one has to these
days. But it's important to us, always has been. So we're not
trying to do something artificial. If I were hamming it up and
getting a bunch of disenchanted kids to come so we could have
pictures taken, that wouldn't be very good. But that's not what
happens when we're together,'' Bush says.
   By all accounts, the Bush family has always been competitive.
The time spent at the oceanfront Maine home is not idly whiled
away. There is tennis, horseshoes, other contests.
   ``They play games to win. They're very nice about it. It's
genteel but only up to a point. That tennis ball's coming over the
net about 90 miles an hour,'' says Thomas W. L. ``Lud'' Ashley, a
former Ohio congressman and a family friend for over 40 years.
   Ashley says Bush has ``never sported his family the way some
politicians do'' and adds that Bush and his wife Barbara are not
given to public displays like the Dukakises.
   The Bushes don't talk much about their sixth child, Robin, who
died at age 3 of leukemia. Bush, in his book ``Looking Forward,''
says that during her illness ``Barbara and I susained each other.''
   ``To this day, like every parent who has ever lost a child, we
wonder why; yet we know that, whatever the reason, she is in God's
loving arms,'' he writes.
   The other children were raised in what son Jeb has called ``a
matriarchal family.'' ``Dad wasn't home at night to play catch,''
he told an interviewer. ``Mom was always the one to hand out the
goodies and the discipline.''
   Mrs. Bush put it differently: ``Somebody has to take care of the
nest, and that's me.''
   The family has been protective when Bush has come under fire, as
he did during the administration's Iran-Contra affair. Barbara Bush
once said, ``There are only six things in this world you can't
criticize _ George Bush and my children. I am a mother hen that
way.''
   ``The family has been a source of great strength during the good
times as well as the bad times,'' says George Jr. ``When ugly
things are said about our dad, we tend to circle the wagons.''
   In the race toward November, the Bush clan will be circling the
country.
   George Jr., 42, says he'll be spending time in the Southwest.
His brother Neil, 33, who lives in Denver, will hit the West.
Brother Marvin, 31, who lives in Virginia, has the Southeast. Jeb,
35, leaves his job as Florida commerce secretary to handle southern
California. And sister Dorothy Bush LeBlond, 29, of Maine, will
handle the Northeast. They'll focus on what George Jr. calls ``the
secondary markets.''
   ``We can't expect to get air time in a big-city market, but when
you go to a city like Midland, Texas, my hometown, off the beaten
path, the people out there appreciate your coming and the media
appreciate it,'' says George Jr.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
