<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Sharks     08-13 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sharks,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Attacked by Shark; Another Shark Sighted Off Stinson Beach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRESCENT CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A great white shark attacked a
surfer near the mouth of the Klamath River, and park rangers
started a ``shark patrol'' after a fisherman spotted another great
white 200 yards off a popular beach.
   ``He grabbed me, sucked me under water, and then let me go,''
said Carl Lafazio, who required 27 stitches in his right thigh
after the attack Thursday.
   Lafazio, 27, said after the shark bit him once, it came back for
a final assault but failed when he made it to shore with the help
of four friends. He was in stable condition at Sutter Coast
Hospital.
   About 250 miles south of Crescent City, officials at Marin
County's Stinson Beach, 15 miles north of San Francisco, said they
were taking seriously a fisherman's reported sighting of a great
white shark.
   Ranger Richard Danielsen said Friday a ``shark patrol'' will
continue through the weekend, but said the park district has
decided against issuing warnings about possible sharks in the
waters.
   If rangers in a 16-foot boat see a shark or find mangled seal
carcasses, they probably will close the beach, Danielsen said.
   Bruce Barsotti, 38, said he was at the wheel of his 25-foot
fishing boat Tuesday night when a shark about 13 feet long lunged
out of the water.
   ``I was stunned. I was just in awe ... I couldn't believe the
mouth on it,'' Barsotti said.
</TEXT>
