<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 1212EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Procurement Bjt   08-13 0988</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Procurement, Bjt,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Has Had Procurement Problems Of His Own</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis,
who cites the Pentagon purchasing scandal in almost every campaign
speech, oversees a procurement system described by the
Massachusetts inspector general as ``almost a standing invitation
to fraud, waste and abuse.''
   Inspector General Joseph Baressi, a fellow Democrat, has
delivered scathing attacks on three aspects of the state's
purchasing system: its procedures for buying supplies and
equipment, its guidelines for obtaining services through
consultants and its laws governing purchases by city, town,
district and county governments.
   A spokesman for the Massachusetts governor said many of the
problems have been corrected internally in recent months but
Baressi's office, while praising some of the steps taken to protect
against fraud, said only new laws will correct giant flaws in the
system.
   ``The commonweath routinely enters into large, ill-defined
endless contracts in which genuine competition is illusory and
money is no object,'' Baressi told the Legislature earlier this
year. ``Too often, the vendor is paid both to tell the state what
services to buy and then to sell those very services to the state
year after year.
   ``Except in the areas of construction bidding and designer
selection, the commonwealth's contracting procedures are almost a
standing invitation to fraud, waste and abuse.''
   Baressi's deputy, Stephen E. Cotton, gave a similar account of
exisiting state provisions governing procurement by local
governments, calling them ``vague, confusing, weak, arbitrary and
outdated.''
   Those criticisms are not unlike a comment by a former Pentagon
undersecretary that Dukakis has used recently in his campaign stump
speech.
   Quoting congressional testimony of the former official, David
Packard, Dukakis told several rallies that the Reagan
administration ``has helped create an environment in which, and I
quote, `honest and efficient military acquisition is impossible.'''
   He also blames the Pentagon scandal and other problems in the
Reagan administration on a ``contempt for public service'' and said
the president and Vice President George Bush must accept
responsibility.
   ``There's an old Greek saying and I suspect the Italians have
the same one: `You know, the fish rots from the head first.' It
starts from the top.''
   At home, Dukakis said ``I accept the responsibility'' for
problems in his administration, and said that chief executives are
from time to time hurt by the conduct of government workers.
   Massachusetts revised its contracting procedures for
construction and building design in 1980 after a special commission
found them riddled with faults that invited corruption. But the
state's procurement system _ which involves purchases well in
excess of $1 billion a year _ remains for the most part guided by a
1922 law.
   David Wood, a spokesman for the governor, said the state's new
purchasing agent, Rick Murphy, has implemented several internal
policy changes in the past eight months that he said ``virtually
eliminate fraud waste and abuse,'' among them the establishment of
a legal section that reviews purchasing agreements and a
requirement that all contracts be in writing.
   But Cotton, citing Murphy's support for legislation to revise
purchasing standards, said that the lack of a tough law will limit
the effectiveness of Murphy's internal efforts to improve the
system.
   ``The rules or rather the absence of rules create the
vulnerability,'' Cotton said.
   In the past year alone, there have been several cases in which
the state procurement laws have come under scrutiny.
   In April, the Massachusetts Water Resources Authority, the
agency charged with cleaning up Boston Harbor, put out a request
for bids that invited suppliers to make offers to sell the state
such items as trucks, electric tools, blades, bags, bars, signs and
drills _ without being more specific.
   In February, 19 people were indicted, included three current and
former state employees, for allegedly bilking the state Department
of Public Works of more than $350,000 by either overbilling or
submitting bills for work never done. Baressi has complained there
is a lack of safeguards in existing procurement laws to prevent
such fraud. Many of those charged in the case were private
consultants contracted by the department.
   Baressi also said in a report last year that many state agencies
have split purchases to deliberately circumvent requirements that
items costing more than $500 be put out for competitive bids.
   The inspector general has offered three proposals to strengthen
the system, but all three have languished in the Legislature.
Dukakis supports two of them _ bills affecting state purchases of
equipment and supplies and similar puchases by local governments _
but has given mixed signals on the measure affecting the hiring of
consultants.
   The administration and state commissions have relied heavily on
consultants to do work ranging from changing lightbulbs to helping
orchestrate the multi-billion dollar harbor cleanup, a practice
which has prompted criticism from Baressi and a wide array of
legislators.
   ``A work force of their own,'' is how state Auditor A. Joseph
DeNucci described the burgeoning corps of consultants.
   The state in fiscal 1987 spent more than $400 million on private
consultants and another $800 million to contract services for human
services programs Another $477 million was spent on private
consultants in fiscal 1988, which ended June 30.
   ``There are times when we have had sharp disagreements with the
inspector general,'' said James Dorsey, the governor's chief
spokesman. ``Not about attacking the problem of fraud, waste and
abuse but how best to do it.''
   Chief among those disagreements is the use of consultants.
   ``We find there is a strong argument to make that putting
engineers and scientists and others on the full time state payroll
rather than hiring them as consultants for temporary duty is a
greater waste,'' Dorsey said last week.
   The administration adopted new guidelines that have stricter
limits on the scope and length of work that can be performed by
consultants, but Cotton said they are too vague.
   ``You could drive a freight train through all the loopholes,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
