<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--MayorBarthelemy     08-13 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Mayor Barthelemy,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Orleans Mayor Popular Convention Figure</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-CVN--Convention Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although the game plan calls for Republicans
to dominate news media attention during the party's national
convention week, a Democrat is giving the GOP a run for its money
in garnering the most interviews.
   By the end of the pre-convention week, Mayor Sidney J.
Barthelemy had given at least 75 planned interviews, plus numerous
impromptu chats, according to his press secretary who said she
hadn't had time to make an exact count.
   ``We always don't get the good press,'' Barthelemy said. ``So I
think this is an opportunity to tell the good things, show the
media that this is a city where you can have a good time and do
business and this is a city that takes care of business.
   ``I hope people will leave here and will have a positive view of
the city if they already didn't have one,'' he said. ``I hope that
some of the people in business will leave here with the idea of
returning and perhaps opening a business.''
   That's the message Barthelemy has been spreading to anyone who
wants to listen _ and there have been plenty of reporters lining up
for interviews.
   ``He loves doing them,'' said Jinx Broussard, the mayor's press
secretary. ``He thinks this is the chance to show off the city and
the fact that we're not just the big easy ... we're on the road to
recovery from the oil and gas collapse and a good place to raise a
family.''
   He's talked with the national news media, has been a hot item
with the scores of newspapers in New Orleans for the convention,
has been interviewed by two London newspapers and plans a lengthy
session with foreign journalists during the next week, Ms.
Broussard said.
   Barthelemy's role is that of a good-will ambassador since, after
all, this is a Republican convention.
   ``I would have been an active player in the (Democratic)
convention,'' he said. ``Now, I'm just an active player in hosting
the convention.''
   Barthelemy, who was elected vice chair in charge of voter
registration at last month's Democratic National Convention in
Atlanta, said he's not bothered by the fact the Republicans did not
invite him to issue an official greeting on the convention's
opening night.
   ``Naturally, I would have been glad to do it,'' he said. ``But
it's their convention.''
   Amid the GOP hoopla, the mayor admits the 1992 Democratic
convention is in the back of his mind. During the Atlanta meeting,
his officials spread the message: ``We would like to have you guys
in `92,'' Barthelemy said.
</TEXT>
