<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iraq-Syria     08-13 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Syria,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Calls for Syria's Expulsion From Arab League</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iraq-Hussein, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq on Saturday urged Arab states to expel
Syria from the Arab League, citing Syrian policy in Lebanon, its
attacks on Palestinian camps in Beirut and its alliance with Iraq's
arch-enemy, Iran.
   First Deputy Prime Minister Taha Yassin Ramadan said Arab
nations should cut off all financial aid to Syria and end dealings
with President Hafez Assad.
   ``The minimum Arab leaders could do is expel the traitor Assad
from their fold and to boycott him,'' Ramadan, also a member of the
Revolutionary Command Council, wrote in an article in the governing
Baath Party paper Al-Thawra.
   ``To maintain contacts with (Assad), whether directly or
indirectly, means they are encouraging him and taking part in his
crimes,'' Ramadan said.
   A proposal to expel Syria would have to be considered during an
Arab League summit meeting. It is unlikely Iraq would prevail if
such a proposal came to a vote. The next meeting has not been
scheduled.
   Ramadan's article contained Iraq's strongest attack in recent
memory on the Syrian leader. It came several days after Iraq and
Iran accepted a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire to start Aug. 20 in their
8-year-old war.
   Syria has been a staunch supporter of Persian Iran against Arab
Iraq in the war, which started in September 1980. Attempts to
reconcile Baghdad and Damascus in the past seven years have failed
due to deep mistrust between the two countries.
   Syria sent 40,000 troops into Lebanon and west Beirut to control
fighting between rival militias.
   All major Arab countries belong to the 21-member Arab League
with the exception of Egypt, whose membership was suspended after
it signed the Camp David accord with Israel.
   In a 1978 summit in Baghdad, the league pledged $1.8 billion in
aid to Syria as a ``confrontation state'' bordering Israel.
</TEXT>
