<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     08-13 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radical Students Defy Government Ban On March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students battled police with
firebombs and rocks and beat riot troopers with iron bars Saturday
as protesters vowed to reach the North Korean border for
unification talks.
   Hundreds of students caught police by surprise when they charged
out of Yonsei University to attack troops encircling the campus to
try and stop radicals assembling for a march Monday to the border.
   Troopers were sleeping or resting when students charged them,
hurling firebombs and lashing out with iron bars and clubs. At
least three troopers were knocked senseless and dozens of others
injured as they tried to fend off blows with shields or fled.
   ``Advance national reunification!'' and ``Yankees go home!'' the
protesters chanted.
   Police were forced back by the rampaging students until hundreds
of reinforcments were rushed up from nearby sidestreets to drive
the howling protesters back with volleys of tear gas.
   National Police Headquarters in Seoul said many officers and
protesters were injured, but no figures were available. Police said
dozens of students were arrested.
   About 200 students demonstrating at Myongdong Roman Catholic
Cathedral in the center of Seoul earlier tried to break through
surrounding police lines with firebombs but were driven back.
   More than 3,000 riot police surrounded Yonsei in western Seoul
to block the march to the border truce site of Panmunjom for talks
with communist North Korean student delegates on reunification. The
government banned the march and police are on top alert to block it.
   Meanwhile, a group of North Korean students who hope to
participate in the talks arrived on Saturday at Kaesong, a border
town near Panmunjom, the North Korean Central News Agency said in a
report monitored in Tokyo.
   It said the students marched from the northern part of the
peninsula to Pyongyang, where they boarded buses to continue their
trip toward Panmunjom.
   The report didn't say how many students were involved.
   In South Korea, about 4,000 students, many from other cities,
managed to get past the police cordon around Yonsei University. But
dozens of students were halted and taken away by police who
questioned and searched people approaching the school. Police
officers beat and kicked some detained students.
   Student leaders said they would go ahead with the march despite
the massive police deployment. ``We will never, never give in,''
said one.
   Kim Yong-kap, minister of government administration, said the
students were becoming a threat to stability and the administration
might have to take drastic measures to suppress violent protests.
   President Roh Tae-woo said Friday that violent protests were a
threat to the Olympics, to be held in Seoul Sept. 17-Oct. 2, and
said the government would not tolerate continued unrest.
   Student protests over the past week in support of Monday's march
have been relatively small with just a few thousand people taking
part.
   The students want to meet with North Korean student delegates at
Panmunjom for talks on reuniting the divided Korean peninsula. They
also demand removal of the 42,000 U.S. troops in South Korea under
a treaty and contend Washington backs military rule in the country.
   Most South Koreans oppose the talks, and riot police blocked a
similar march in June. Turnout for the rallies for the latest march
has been lower than in June.
   Several hundred shopkeepers and residents staged demonstrations
in Seoul to demand students stop violent protests. Residents living
around Yonsei demanded students abandon the march.
   ``This is terrible. People are against this,'' a middle-aged
businessmen complained as he watched students fighting police.
   Radical students seized on the reunification issue to try and
mobilize public support for their anti-government campaign. The
students, a small but powerful minority on campuses, have failed to
gain support because of violent tactics and open advances to the
totalitarian north.
   The peninsula has been divided since 1945 at the end of World
War II. North Korea invaded the south in 1950 to start the Korean
War.
</TEXT>
