<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 1251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Obit-Zumwalt     08-13 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Zumwalt,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elmo Zumwalt, Son of Admiral, Dies At Age 42</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAYETTEVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elmo R. Zumwalt III, son of the
admiral who ordered the spraying of Agent Orange in Vietnam and who
was exposed to the defoliant himself, died at his home Saturday
from cancer. He was 42.
   Zumwalt, a lawyer, said he never blamed his father for his
disease. The two co-wrote a book titled ``My Father, My Son,''
which was made into a television movie.
   Zumwalt was diagnosed in January 1983 as having stage 4
non-Hodgkins lymphoma. In February 1985, during his ninth biopsy,
doctors discovered he had stage 3 Hodgkins disease, another form of
lymphoma.
   Agent Orange contains highly toxic dioxin. Veterans had
contended that exposure to it causes cancer and other illnesses.
They said it caused miscarriages by wives of servicemen and birth
defects in their children.
   Zumwalt's son, Elmo Russell Zumwalt IV, suffers from a
congenital dysfunction that confuses his physical senses.
   In an article published in the Washington Post on Oct. 7, 1984,
Zumwalt said: ``My father, Adm. Elmo Zumwalt Jr., was a strong
advocate of the use of Agent Orange in the Vietnam War. That
doesn't mean that I hold him responsible for any disease I may have
incurred. He did what he felt he had to do to reduce casualties. I
did what I felt I had to do. I volunteered for service in Vietnam
because I felt whatever the risks, that was where I belonged. Even
now at the age of 38 I'm confronted by undoubted perils. I am not
sorry I went.''
   On June 30, the U.S. Supreme Court removed the last legal
obstacle to a $180 million settlement between Vietnam veterans and
the manufacturers of Agent Orange. The justices let stand rulings
that dismissed lawsuits by about 300 veterans who had challenged
the 1984 settlement.
   The $180 million settlement now totals about $240 million with
interest. As many as 250,000 people could receive money from the
settlement.
   The elder Zumwalt said he ordered Agent Orange sprayed over the
Mekong Delta to kill vegetation and drive ``the Viet Cong back
1,000 yards off the water's edge.''
   He commanded Naval forces in Vietnam from 1968-1970, then served
as chief of Naval operations until 1974 when he retired from active
duty. His son served in Vietnam from June 1969 to August 1970 as a
lieutenant junior grade commanding a patrol boat.
   ``I do not have any guilt feelings because I was convinced then
and I am convinced now that the use of Agent Orange saved literally
hundreds and maybe thousands of lives,'' the elder Zumwalt told The
Associated Press in 1985.
   In addition to his son, Zumwalt is survived by his wife,
Katherine; and his daughter, Maya, 13.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880813-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 1301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Armenians     08-13 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Armenians,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenians Wait Near Embassy for Chance to Emigrate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the past several weeks, crowds of Armenians
have gathered outside the U.S. Embassy, hoping for word they can
come to America. At night they sleep at friends' homes, railroad
stations or wherever they can find room.
   The embassy stopped processing their applications for refugee
status July 1 because the U.S. State Department ran out of money
for the program.
   Beginning this week, embassy officials expect to start the
process again under a new program that requires refugees and their
families in the United States to pay a bigger share of resettlement
expenses.
   But it will take U.S. consular officials weeks to catch up with
the backlog of 3,000 people who already had been told to report for
pre-departure interviews when the money ran out _ and 1,600 people
who have applied since.
   Abel Kasoyan's journey to Los Angeles to be reunited with his
sister is one of those that stalled in Moscow.
   The 30-year-old Kasoyan, his father, mother, wife and two
children aged 3 and 5 arrived in the capital July 1 from Armenia, a
Soviet republic bordering Turkey and Iran.
   He carried a slip of paper from the U.S. Embassy that told him
to report July 19 for an interview and then a quick departure.
   He still has not been interviewed.
   The family, which sold its belongings, has had to scramble for
food and lodging. ``We lived in the Kursk railroad station (in
Moscow) almost a week,'' he said in an interview last week across
the street from the embassy.
   Others who joined him said they didn't understand how the U.S.
government could run out of money. But they said they still wanted
to go to America.
   ``People have been waiting for years, and now it's impossible
for financial reasons,'' said 54-year-old Gratich Froundjian of
Yerevan, the Armenian capital. ``If it's possible to find millions
of dollars for the Contras in Nicaragua, they can find money for
us, too.''
   The U.S. refugee resettlement program ran out of money because
of a sharp increase in the number of people the Soviet Union is
allowing to emigrate.
   The embassy in June gave permission to a record 2,063 Soviets to
immigrate, more than in all of fiscal year 1987. About 94 percent
of that total were Armenians, U.S. officials say.
   ``We recognize the difficulty they're in and we're trying to be
helpful,'' a diplomat said.
   The embassy tried to contact people to warn them not to come to
Moscow because of the budgetary problems, he said.
   ``We'll move these people just as fast as we can,'' he said. ``I
don't think anybody will be going out next week, but we'll start
interviewing people next week.''
   Several U.S. senators and congressmen criticized the original
suspension of the program until the new fiscal year begins Oct. 1
as a ``terrible signal to those seeking freedom all over the
world.''
   Under the new rules, relatives in the United States must file an
affidavit of financial support or guarantee of employment, and the
immigrants or their relatives must pay for transportation after a
U.S.-sponsored flight to Rome.
   Some Armenians are worried that the additional requirements may
delay their resettlement.
   ``Our relatives have to accept us and support us,'' said Gagam
Petrossyan, 48, of Yerevan, who wants to join his brother in Los
Angeles. ``My relatives still aren't in a position to support me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
