<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LottoBroke     08-13 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lotto Broke,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$3.5 Million Lotto Winner Files For Protection From Creditors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patrick Holland said when he won a $3.5
million Lotto jackpot two years ago in the Washington State Lottery
that he did not want to spend his money foolishly.
   Holland and his wife Patricia filed for protection and
reorganization under Chapter 11 of the bankruptcy law Friday, owing
$450,000 to nine creditors who obtained court orders giving them
rights to his next annual lottery payment.
   ``He was a pauper before he won the Lotto, kind of a starving
construction worker,'' said his former wife, Karen Klingler.
   They divorced before he won the sweepstakes. Now she's a
creditor, and has obtained a garnishment for more than $15,000 in
support payments for their 11-year-old daughter, court records show.
   Holland's third annual payment of $140,000, after a deduction
for federal taxes, is due Thursday.
   With Friday's filing, federal Bankruptcy Judge Frank Howard
signed an order that the next payment go into a trust account for
the time being, said Holland's attorney, Neil Shillito.
   The judge allowed the couple to take $3,500 for living expenses
and administrative costs of the case, but other payments require a
court order, Shillito said.
   ``Once the dust settles in a couple weeks, we'll be in a better
position to know how to go about taking care of the valid claims
against the estate,'' Shillito said.
   Holland, 34, and Shillito have refused to discuss his business
dealings or say how his rags-to-riches story turned back to rags.
   When he won the Lotto in August 1986, Holland told a reporter he
was a building contractor. He said he bought the van of his dreams
and was looking for a fancy present for his daughter but wanted to
avoid squandering his new-found wealth and planned to hire a
financial adviser.
   His ex-wife says he also bought a car, a truck, furniture, TV
satellite dish and a house, and started a dry-cleaning business,
Holland Cleaners Inc.
   The business folded late last year, said Grant B. Anderson, a
former lawyer for the operation. In January, Holland Cleaners
employees who had been working without pay for a month picketed the
business, but a company spokesman said money to pay them had been
frozen since another dry-cleaning company purchased the business in
December.
   The dry-cleaning problem alone ``is a mess,'' Anderson said.
``It's an unfortunate situation.''
   Creditors include two banks claiming about $197,000 for three
loans, including one for the purchase of another dry-cleaning
business, T.L.C. of Tacoma.
   Holland and his wife also owe more than $154,000 in medical
bills, much of it for the birth of their daughter, Michele, on
April 27, 1987, court records show.
   If the creditors do not receive all they're due from the next
lottery payment, they probably will garnish future checks, said Jim
Lancaster, an attorney for Oregon First Bank, which is owed more
than $170,000.
</TEXT>
