<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-Clash     08-13 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Clash,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Killed During Crackdown On Moslem Extremists In Cairo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired birdshot Saturday as they
rounded up suspects in a working-class suburb where Moslem
extremists clashed with security forces outside a mosque, witnesses
said.
   One civilian was killed and several wounded during the roundup
in the Ein Shams district of northeastern Cairo, the witnesses and
hospital officials said. The state-owned Middle East News Agency
said one died and 23 were hurt.
   Authorities were looking for residents who participated in a
clash Friday night between Moslem extremists and police. The
extremists swung chains and threw stones at the police, who fought
back with tear gas and sticks.
   Three policemen and 16 civilians were wounded in the battle in
Ein Shams, said a senior police official who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   He said more than 120 extremists also hurled flaming objects at
police and set a police van ablaze. The official said more than 70
extremists were arrested during the clash Friday night.
   During the roundup Saturday, police fired birdshot to intimidate
people on the streets and entered houses to make arrests, witnesses
said. The news agency said 27 people were arrested.
   Sources at a nearby hospital, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said one person died and several were wounded during the
roundup. They declined to identify those hurt or describe the
extent of their injuries.
   The police official said Friday's half-hour clash began after
police went to the Adam Mosque in Ein Shams and waited outside to
detain a number of extremist suspects who were meeting inside after
evening prayers.
   ``The clash began after policemen moved to make arrests as the
extremists were leaving the mosque,'' the official said.
   The Middle East News Agency said the extremists belonged to the
underground fundamentalist organization Jihad, a local group which
has no connection with Lebanon's Islamic Jihad. Jihad means ``holy
war'' in Arabic.
   The agency said the extremists were planning ``provocations and
acts of violence,'' including incitement of Moslem-Christian strife
and distribution of anti-government leaflets.
   The government says members of Egypt's Jihad killed President
Anwar Sadat at a military parade on Oct. 6, 1981 and later led a
two-day uprising in the southern city of Assiut in which more than
80 people, mostly policemen, were killed. The government believes
the extremists hoped the uprising would trigger a revolution
overthrowing the government.
   In the Sadat assassination and coup attempt trials that
followed, five people were sentenced to death and executed, three
by firing squad and two by hanging. More than 120 were given prison
terms of up to 25 years.
</TEXT>
