<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Attack Video,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massachusetts GOP Produces Attack Video to Debunk `Dukakis Myth'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-CVN--Convention Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Republicans have produced a
video attacking Michael Dukakis and plan to distribute it to other
states' delegations at the Republican National Convention to ``get
the truth out'' about the Democratic nominee.
   The 10-minute video, which will be unveiled Tuesday by
Republican National Chairman Frank Fahrenkopf Jr. and state GOP
Chairman Ray Shamie, shows ``the truth rather than the myth that
Dukakis likes to perpetuate,'' Shamie said.
   ``He talks about things, puts a nice spin on them, but the facts
are quite different. What we're doing is debunking many of his
statements,'' Shamie said in a pre-convention telephone interview.
   Joseph Malone, the Republican Senate candidate trying to unseat
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said other states' GOP chairmen
will get copies and ``each chairman will use it to get the truth
out about Mike Dukakis.''
   ``It will point out what Mike Dukakis said in his speech about
protecting the environment, then point to the fact that
Massachusetts has the most polluted harbor in the nation in the
Boston Harbor and the governor ignored that fact as the harbor
became more and more polluted,'' Malone said.
   ``It will point out his statements on balancing the budget and
then point to the recent budget crisis in Massachusetts,'' he said.
   ``We're very familiar with the miracle,'' Shamie said, a
deriding reference to the state's economic rebound that Dukakis
takes partial credit for on the presidential campaign trail.
</TEXT>
