<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BullRun     08-13 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bull Run,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Escape With Bumps And Bruises As Bull Gets Loose At Rodeo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAK, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bull got loose in the stands during the
Omak Stampede rodeo when a gate was left open, sending spectators
hurrying out of the way and slightly injuring four, officials said.
   The bull pushed open a latched gate Friday night, then moved
through a second gate that mistakenly had been left open and went
from the arena into the stands, which were about half-full at the
time, said Johnny Pope, a professional rodeo announcer who was
working the show.
   While spectators moved out of the way, the bull rambled to the
top of the stands, turned left, headed across the length of the
seating area, then turned again and headed down, bumping one woman,
rodeo officials said.
   Pope said the bull brushed past a man who was hanging over the
fence between the stands and the arena, making him fall over the
barrier. The man hit the front end of a parked ambulance.
   The bull was recaptured after it re-entered the arena.
   The bull had a relatively mild reputation among rodeo clowns,
whose job includes distracting animals in the event someone falls
or is otherwise threatened with injury, Pope said.
   Three men and a woman were taken to Mid-Valley Hospital in this
north-central Washington town and all were released soon afterward
suffering mostly bumps and bruises, said night supervisor Cathy
Grimmett.
</TEXT>
