<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     08-13 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Salutes Bush's Courage, Assaults Reaganomics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POCASSET, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis saluted rival George Bush
as a man of ``enormous courage and tremendous patriotism'' Saturday
while continuing his assault on President Reagan's ``irresponsible
fiscal policy.''
   The Democratic nominee, interrupting a weekend on Cape Cod to
meet with reporters, was asked about a World War II gunner's
challenge to Bush's account of being shot down over the Pacific.
The gunner disputed the vice president's claim that the plane was
on fire when he ejected.
   ``I don't think that kind of thing has any place in a
campaign,'' Dukakis said. ``He served this country. He served it
with tremendous courage. You don't fly 58 missions without enormous
courage and tremendous patriotism.''
   Dukakis continued to link the jump in the prime lending rate to
10 percent this past week to the Reagan administration's deficit
spending.
   ``I'm very concerned, and I think all Americans are concerned,
about what's happening to our economy,'' he said. ``This increase
in interest rates is every bit as much a tax as a legislated tax.''
   The Massachusetts governor and his wife, Kitty, were spending
the weekend at the home of Mrs. Dukakis' sister, Ginny Peters, and
her husband, Al.
   Dukakis said he planned to take a swim Saturday and spend most
of the day reading issues papers and material about the presidency.
After tending to state business Monday and Tuesday, he planned to
head back out to the campaign trail during the Republican National
Convention.
   Dukakis and his wife joked about a comment by Bush's wife,
Barbara, that the public affection between the Dukakises was phony.
   ``You're not supposed to touch me; it's against the rules,''
Mrs. Dukakis said as she came out of her sister's home and sat next
to her husband on a deck overlooking the water.
   ``It's a little bit of paradise off the beaten track,'' Dukakis
said of the Peters home. He also led reporters and a few aides in
singing ``Happy Birthday'' to a member of the press corps.
   Dukakis began focusing on economic issues Thursday after major
banks raised their prime lending rate to 10 percent.
   On Friday he called the increase an ``irresponsibility tax''
triggered by Reagan's deficit spending. Saturday, he referred to it
as a ``family tax'' that would drive up mortgage costs and prevent
millions of people from buying homes.
   The deficit and rising interest rates will create ``enormous
inflationary pressure on the economy,'' Dukakis said. ``It will be
the American people who ultimately will pay the bills.... These are
burdens which average American families should not be putting up
with. They are burdens that are the result of irresponsible fiscal
policy.''
   While Dukakis took the weekend off, his campaign launched its
first television ad of the general election campaign.
   The 60-second spot airing in Texas and California touts Dukakis'
economic successes as Massachusetts' governor and features several
shots from his acceptance speech at the Democratic National
Convention.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
