<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Reagan-Republicans     08-13 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Reagan-Republicans,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Democrats Talk, Republicans Deliver</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Saturday that ``George
Bush and I have been hard at work putting into practice the ideals
you believe in'' while the Democrats only talk.
   In his weekly radio speech, Reagan pledged to campaign actively
for Bush's election as president because of ``my love for America
and my dreams for her future.''
   Bush, he said, ``understands that the question for America today
is not, `What's different?' but `What's next?'''
   The president spoke from the Oval Office. He and first lady
Nancy Reagan fly Sunday to New Orleans, where the president will
address the Republican National Convention on Monday night.
   Reagan devoted much of his speech to his support of aid for
Nicaraguan rebels, his veto of a defense spending bill that he says
would weaken vital Pentagon programs and his advocacy of ``trade
that is both free and, yes, fair.''
   ``So you see, while the leadership of the other party have been
talking, George Bush and I have been hard at work putting into
practice the ideals you believe in, the ideals that at her heart
America has always stood for, strong defenses, low taxes and
limited government, compassion and fair play . . . faith in our
future and an openness to the rest of the world,'' the president
said.
   ``And, yes, those are just the ideals you will hear us
Republicans rededicate ourselves to this coming week in New
Orleans,'' he said.
   ``You know, I'll be addressing the Republican convention on
Monday, opening night, and taking an active role in the coming
campaign,'' the president said.
   ``But even so, my name won't appear on any ballot this fall.
What's at stake for me in this election is my love for America and
my dreams for her future.''
   ``And that's what my support for Vice President Bush comes down
to,'' he said. ``You see, George Bush understands that the question
for America today is not, `What's different?', but `What's next?'''
   Reagan opened his radio address with a review of recent
administration actions, saying, ``Some in the other party are
parading around the country, talking and talking about what they
claim they'd do if they were elected.''
   ``Well, while they talk, we deliver,'' he said.
</TEXT>
