<1ST_LINE>r p AM-GwinnettRecount     08-13 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gwinnett Recount,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Recount Shows Two Candidates Tied In Legislative Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCEVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Republican candidates received the
same number of votes in a primary race for the Georgia Legislature,
and their fate may rest with a woman who was turned away at the
polls trying to vote.
   A recount of the votes Friday from Tuesday's GOP primary showed
state Rep. Ronald W. Pittman and challenger Keith R. Breedlove tied
at 1,633 votes each.
   That may leave the race to be decided by Nancy H. Putney, who
was not allowed to vote Tuesday _ even though she presented a
receipt showing that she is correctly registered.
   Elections officials say she's told them she wants to vote for
Pittman.
   ``It sure does look like that vote has become important, doesn't
it?'' F. Raymond Street, a member of Gwinnett County's Board of
Registrars, said after reviewing the results of the latest tally in
the legislative race.
   County officials have proposed holding a special election for
the seat Aug. 30, when several county races will be decided by
runoffs.
   Either candidate could demand a recount by hand, or Pittman
could demand Mrs. Putney be allowed to vote.
   Election officials acknowledge that Mrs. Putney was allowed to
vote and had a valid receipt indicating she had registered at a
local library, even though she was not listed on their roll of
registered voters.
   ``I just want to make sure that my vote gets counted, so for now
I'm not going to say anything,'' Mrs. Putney said.
</TEXT>
