<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 1435EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-Glance     08-13 0837</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Glance,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summary of Busy Week at Capitol</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate and House of Representatives rushed
last week to clear their slates of pending business before a summer
recess for the Republican convention. Here, at a glance, are the
week's major actions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DROUGHT RELIEF</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed America's largest-ever disaster relief
bill, a $3.9 billion package to provide aid for farmers suffering
crop losses because of the drought or other calamities. The bill
whisked through Congress this week with overwhelming support in
both houses.
   Farmers who lost more than 35 percent of their expected harvest
will receive payments equal to 65 percent of the lost income.
Farmers whose crop losses exceeded 75 percent of the expected yield
would receive payments equal to 90 percent of lost income.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>JUSTICE CONFIRMATION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Senate unanimously confirmed Richard L. Thornburgh as
attorney general, replacing Edwin Mese III, who resigned.
   Confirmations are expected next month for Harold Christensen as
deputy attorney general; Francis A. Keating II as associate
attorney general, and Edward S.G. Dennis Jr. as chief of the
criminal division.
   All four were recommended unanimously for confirmation by the
Senate Judiciary Committee, which acted on Thornburgh's nomination
Wednesday by voice vote, without debate. The other three, who
already are serving at their posts in acting capacities, were
cleared by the panel Aug. 3, but their confirmations by the full
Senate were delayed by last-minute maneuvering as the Senate broke
for the August recess.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOUTH AFRICA SANCTIONS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The House passed, on a 244-132 vote, legislation to withdraw all
U.S. investment from racially segregated South Africa and impose a
near-total trade embargo. The bill goes to the Senate, where it
faces a possible Republican filibuster and, if eventually passed, a
likely veto by President Reagan.
   Supporters hailed the dramatic measure as a last-chance
opportunity to bring strong economic pressure to bear to help end
South Africa's apartheid system of racial separation by expanding
the less sweeping sanctions adopted in 1986.
   But Republicans said the bill represents a ``scorched earth''
policy that amounts to declaring economic war against South Africa,
a war they said would hurt the blacks it is designed to help by
causing millions to lose their jobs.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>INTERNMENT REPARATION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed a bill providing reparations to
Japanese-Americans interned during World War II. The bill provides
for a $20,000 tax-free payment to each of the 60,000 survivors
among the approximately 120,000 Japanese-Americans who were
interned. The legislation, which cleared Congress by a 257-156 vote
in the House on Aug. 4, calls for a trust fund of $1.2 billion,
with appropriations in any one year limited to $500 million.
Legislation providing the actual money must still be enacted.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CONTRA AID</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted 49-47 for a Democratic proposal to provide
Nicaragua's Contra rebels with $27 million in non-lethal
``humanitarian'' aid after Oct. 1. The vote could set the stage for
a second vote on the possible resumption of $16.3 million in
stockpiled military aid later in the year.
   Republicans, none of whom joined in the majority, said the
Democratic plan did not represent a truly bipartisan approach and
could not guarantee aid would reach the rebels inside Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEFENSE BILL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Senate passed its second Pentagon budget bill 90-4, ordering
a major review of U.S. overseas commitments, a limit on American
troop deployments to Japan and South Korea, and a ceiling on
spending for U.S. military personnel stationed overseas. The last
provision requires the allies to pay the difference if deployment
costs of U.S. troops rise above 1988 levels.
   President Reagan last week vetoed Congress' first defense bill
because he objected to cuts in his Star Wars budget and
restrictions on nuclear arms control policy. The new version
retains the same Star Wars reductions, but none of the arms control
limitations. It will now go to a House-Senate conference committee
to resolve differences between the two chambers' versions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FREE TRADE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The House voted 366-40 to approve a free trade pact signed in
January by President Reagan and Canadian Prime Minister Brian
Mulroney. The agreement would phase out most tariffs on the annual
$166 billion in goods and services traded across their common
border. Tariffs currently apply to about 25 percent of U.S.-Canada
trade.
   The Senate is expected to act on the measure when it returns
next month. It won approval Tuesday from the Senate Finance
Committee.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PAY RAISES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The federal government's 4.4 million civilian and military
employees would receive a 4.1 percent pay increase starting Jan. 1
under an agreement by a House-Senate conference committee.
   President Reagan is expected to approve the raise after final
congressional action on the Treasury-Postal Service appropriations
bill which authorizes it. That action is likely when Congress
returns in September.
   The $4 billion total cost of the 1989 raise _ which will hike
the salary of the highest-paid career civil servant from $77,500 to
$80,775 _ is to be absorbed by agency budgets already approved or
nearing approval.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
