<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 1445EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Heat-Beanballs     08-13 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heat-Beanballs,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pitchers Throw More Beanballs In Hot Weather, Study Suggests</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Heat Psychology, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baseball batters get hit by pitches more often
when the temperature is in the 90s, maybe because the heat is
making pitchers more aggressive, a study released Saturday suggests.
   It's not so much that the beanballs are deliberate, but rather
the pitchers may be trying to move batters back from the plate,
said researcher Alan Reifman.
   Establishing dominance by throwing close to the batter could be
taken as an aggressive act, prodded by discomfort from the heat, he
said.
   ``You might plan to throw it close, and your aim is a little
off,'' he said.
   But Reifman, a graduate student at the University of Michigan at
Ann Arbor, stressed that merely finding a relationship between hot
weather and the risk of beanballs does not prove cause-and-effect.
   He presented his work at the annual meeting of the American
Psychological Association.
   He and colleagues found that in the 21 games analyzed for which
the temperature was in the 90s, pitchers racked up an average of
0.57 hit batters per game.
   For the remainder of the total 215 games in the study, the
highest average for cooler weather was 0.33, for games played in
the 80s. Lower rates were found for games at lower temperatures.
   The analysis was based on statistics from every tenth major
league game played in 1986, as listed in the Los Angeles Times.
   The analysis did not account for night games. But it did
statistically remove the influence of pitcher inaccuracy, as
measured by the number of walks in the game, and possibility of
throwing beanballs as retribution, as suggested by the number of
home runs hit by the opposing team.
   William Fox, who teaches about motivation and behavior within
organizations at the University of Florida in Gainesville, called
the work preliminary but interesting.
   ``Like a lot of research, it's a first cut. It's provocative. It
points to the need to do more research,'' he said.
</TEXT>
