<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 1604EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AirportWindShear     08-13 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airport Wind Shear,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Tests Aimed at Exposing Deadly Wind Shears at Major Airports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS SEARLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computer and radar similar to the type used by
highway patrolmen to clock speeders can be used to warn pilots of
deadly but invisible wind bursts that have sent airplanes into
crashes, tests here have shown.
   Conditions called wind shear and microburst have killed nearly
500 American air travelers and injured more than 200 others in the
past 23 years, according to federal government figures.
   But a two-month test at Denver's Stapleton airport of the
Terminal Doppler Weather Radar system has already enabled flight
controllers to warn jet crews of wind shear conditions.
   On July 11 alone, five jetliners on landing approach were
diverted by air traffic controllers after an automatic warning by
the TDWR computer system.
   The wind shears could have made the aircraft plunge out of
control, said Cleon Biter, the National Center for Atmospheric
Research's project manager in the program.
   A wind shear is any abrupt change in wind speed and direction,
while a microburst is a powerful downward rush of air from a
cumulus cloud that strikes the ground and spreads out in all
directions, creating wind shear conditions.
   Abrupt changes in wind speed or direction pose extreme danger to
aircraft, which get their lift from air rushing across the wing. If
air speed across the wing sharply falls off, the wing loses lift
and the plane falls.
   An airplane flying into a microburst momentarily experiences
increased air speed when it meets the air rushing outward. But on
the other side of the microburst the air is speeding away from the
plane, causing a sharp drop in airspeed across the wing surfaces
and loss of lift.
   If the plane has enough altitude it can recover. If it is
landing or taking off, it may plunge to the ground.
   The search for a way to detect the conditions was intensified
after major crashes, such as the crash at Dallas-Fort Worth on Aug.
2, 1985, that killed 137 when a Delta plane flying out of a
microburst was unable to stay aloft.
   The Federal Aviation Administration is funding the radar test,
in which the National Weather Service, the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology and the University of North Dakota also are
participating. The test ends Aug. 31.
   The demonstration tests are the latest in several FAA-backed
Doppler radar projects done at Stapleton to develop an early
warning system for wind shear, said Donald Turnbull, the FAA's
project manager in Washington, D.C.
   ``The highway patrol uses a Doppler radar gun to measure your
speed (in a car). We're using the same (technique) to check the
velocity of air,'' said Dr. Wayne Sand, NCAR's deputy manager of
research applications.
   ``Doppler radar can see well up into the clouds and try to
determine the formation of microbursts. Doppler can look out to
about 40 miles. We're concentrating within an area of six miles of
the airport, the prime area for wind detection, but we're looking
out 40 miles to see approaching wind gusts,'' Turnbull said.
   When the $3 million prototype system's computer decides the
radar has seen a wind shear or microburst, it tells air traffic
controllers at Stapleton, who warn pilots, he said.
   Turnbull said officials hope contracts for 47 of the units will
be awarded by the middle of October, and be on line at major
airports by 1992. Because contract bidding is under way, Turnbull
would not give cost estimates, but earlier reports have put the
unit price at $5.5 million.
   The new system would replace the older Low Level Wind Shear
Alert System consisting of several ground-mounted anemometers
placed around airports to measure surface wind velocity and
direction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
