<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UnusualSentence     08-13 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unusual Sentence,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Offers To Reduce Dealer's Sentence If He Gives Names</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge sentenced a drug dealer
to 15 years in prison but offered to reduce the sentence by one
month for every user or dealer he revealed to prosecutors.
   In order to qualify for the reduction, federal prosecutors must
be able to verify that the names given to them are those of actual
dealers or users.
   U.S. District Judge Joseph E. Stevens Jr. said after the
sentencing Friday that he intended to stir up concern among users
``about whether they're really safe doing what they're doing.''
   The defendant, Alfred Griffin, 57, pleaded guilty on May 2 to
using Western Union wire transfers to conceal money sent to
California to buy drugs for Kansas City drug houses.
   Federal marshals took Griffin, who had been free on bond, into
custody. He said nothing during the hearing.
   ``It's a vey unusual sentence,'' Griffin's lawyer, Bruce Simon,
said afterward. ``I think it's very bizarre, frankly. I have some
serious problems with it.''
   Simon said his client did not indicate immediately whether he
would reveal sources, considering the danger it might pose for him.
   In court earlier, Simon told the judge that imposing a harsh
sentence would not work as a deterrent to dealers.
   ``There's just not enough likelihood of getting caught,'' Simon
said.
   Stevens said he devised the sentencing idea on the spot.
   ``I've been concerned about effective sentencing in the drug
cases for a long time,'' Stevens said.
   Within 120 days, the judge will review whether Griffin has
provided names of verifiable drug traffickers or users. Stevens
said he would then trim one month for each name.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
