<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Bomb     08-13 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Bomb,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Bombs Explode; 6 Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police credited a black
security guard and a woman who once served in the Israeli army with
saving lives Saturday when a mine exploded in a shopping mall.
   The guard was hospitalized and two whites slightly injured after
the explosion.
   Police said Evette Hassom, a 36-year-old Israeli, spotted the
limpet mine and pushed people out of the area when they ignored her
warnings. They also lauded Moses Biyela, who said his white
supervisor disappeared after ordering him to place a bomb
suppression blanket over the object.
   Biyela, 32, suffered severe burns and lacerations when the bomb
exploded three feet in front of him before he could place the
blanket. He was holding the blanket in front of his body, which may
have saved his life.
   Biyela was quoted by the Sunday Star as saying from a hospital:
``Suddenly I was all alone. People were fleeing all around me.''
The security chief who ordered him to put the blanket on the
plastic-wrapped parcel, ``had disappeared. I was very, very
scared.''
   Ms. Hassom spotted the parcel outside the boutique where she
works and determined it was a bomb. She warned shoppers, but most
people ignored her, so she started shoving them toward the exit.
   Ms. Hasson was quoted as saying she was security-conscious
because of her service in the Israeli army.
   Another limpet mine exploded outside a post office Friday night
near Durban, and police said three people were slightly injured.
The mines can be attached to another surface.
   Nearly 100 bombs have exploded in the country since a national
state of emergency was declared June 12, 1986. Police blame most of
the explosions on the outlawed African National Congress, which is
fighting to topple the white-dominated government and end apartheid.
   The ANC seldom comments on individual bombings but says the
bombing and sabotage campaign is part of its strategy.
   Censorship rules imposed under the emergency ban or restrict
reporting about unrest, security force actions, most forms of
peaceful protest and a broad range of statements the government
considers subversive.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 26 million black majority has no
vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy
and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
