<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Conservatives-VP     08-13 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Conservatives-VP,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sen. Humphrey's Group Pushing for Conservative Veep</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-CVN--Convention Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of conservative Republicans, led by
Sen. Gordon Humphrey of New Hampshire, threatened Saturday to put
up their own candidate for vice president if George Bush fails to
select a running mate acceptable to them.
   Humphrey's group, Coalition For a Winning Ticket, is trying to
exert pressure for a conservative running mate to balance a ticket
headed by Bush. ``The fact is the conservatives are not turned on''
by the Bush candidacy, he said.
   ``We did not come here to act as rubber stamps for the party
hierarchy,'' Humphrey said at a news conference. ``We want to be
given a stake.''
   He said his group is telephoning members of the state
delegations to this week's Republican National Convention to find
out if there is support for entering an alternative vice
presidential choice into nomination, should Bush pick a moderate.
   Humphrey said there is support from ``three or four delegations
that have assured us that they are willing to follow our
leadership'' for such a move.
   The conservatives are gearing up for a rules fight to block a
potential move by the Bush campaign to prevent a vote for anyone
other than the Bush-anointed running mate choice at the convention,
Humphrey said.
   On Friday Bush operatives got a change through the Rules
Committee that would dispense with the roll call vote if there were
only one vice presidential candidate in contention. That change
would have to be voted on by the convention to take effect.
   Some Republicans such as Humphrey contend Bush is not a
conservative in the Reagan tradition.
   Of the six vice presidential possibilities that a key Bush
adviser listed as being on a short list in the running-mate
considerations, Humphrey said only two would be acceptable, Rep.
Jack Kemp of New York, and Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana.
   Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas, said Humphrey, is not a hardliner
against new taxes, and Dole's wife, former Transportation Secretary
Elizabeth Dole has never run for office and might need ``on-the-job
training.'' Both Doles, along with Sens. Alan Simpson of Wyoming
and Pete Domenici of New Mexico, are said to be on Bush's short
list.
   Of the people who have at some point been suggested as running
mate possibilities, Humphrey said his group would be satisfied with
Education Secretary William Bennett, New Hampshire Gov. John
Sununu, Colorado Sen. William Armstrong and Rep. Henry Hyde of
Illinois.
   ``But we're not trying to force anyone down anyone's throat. We
think there are a lot of good people who have been talked about at
one time or another that fit the bill.''
   Bush infuriated some conservatives by selecting moderate New
Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean to deliver the keynote speech Monday night.
Kean does not support the hardliners' anti-abortion positions.
   Humphrey said that in the end he will support the GOP ticket
regardless. But he said of other conservatives, ``If they're not
turned on ... get a real middle of the road establishment
Republican, a lot of these people are not going to be enthused and
I think they'll take a walk.''
</TEXT>
