<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Opposition 1stLd-Writethru   08-13 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Opposition, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0531,0775</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuauhtemoc Cardenas: A Candidate Who Won't Stop Running</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf bgng: He is drawing... with one graf to specify
that pro-government television ignoring Cardenas but newspapers
reporting campaign; Picks up 6th graf: ``The country...</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly six weeks after the presidential
election, crowds still shout ``President'' at opposition leader
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, who shows few signs of conceding defeat to the
party that has been in power for 59 years.
   His left-of-center movement and other opposition groups continue
an intense war of words for the public trust with the governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party.
   ``It would be dangerous to ignore it or scorn it or to minimize
it,'' Octavio Paz, one of Mexico's most prominent writers, said in
an essay published last week.
   Cardenas, the son of one of Mexico's most beloved presidents,
has crossed the nation since the election, claiming he defeated
governing party candidate Carlos Salinas de Gortari in the July 6
elections and calling on people to ``defend the vote'' from alleged
fraud.
   He is drawing crowds despite virtually no coverage by
pro-government television stations. Most newspapers continue to
publish reports about his crusade.
   ``The country identifies the future with Cardenas and Salinas
with the past,'' said Jorge Castanada, a prominent political
analyst.
   Although in control and saluted by world leaders as the winner,
the governing party, known as the PRI, is clearly worried.
   Salinas still is certain to be inaugurated on Dec. 1 to a
six-year term succeeding President Miguel de la Madrid. But the
party has promised internal reforms and offered to negotiate with
the opposition.
   Cardenas rejected negotiations.
   ``There is only one path, and that is the law,'' Cardenas, 54,
told The Associated Press in an interview Thursday. ``We aren't
going to have any negotiations or any alliance that implies
recognition of someone who didn't win the July 6 elections.''
   The governing party claimed victory before results came in.
After a weeklong delay in announcing results, the PRI-dominated
Federal Election Commission said the PRI won.
   On Monday, the Chamber of Deputies, acting as the Electoral
College, begins examining the disputed returns and vote fraud
charges. Its formal declaration of a president is expected by early
September.
   Cardenas and the candidate of the rightist National Action
Party, Manuel Clouthier, have called for nationwide demonstrations
Sunday, on the eve of the session. Both have vocal allies on the
electoral board.
   Cardenas said people's lives will improve once they have a say
in how the country is run. They must continue to insist, peacefully
and through legal means, for clean elections and genuine democracy,
he said.
   Whether the PRI will reform and whether Salinas, a 40-year-old
former planning and budget minister, can fulfill a promise to
restructure Mexico's economy without a national consensus remains
to be seen.
   Cardenas says Mexico could become hard to govern if democratic
reforms don't take place.
   ``What are they going to do'' if people rise up and do not
``recognize authorities which committed electoral fraud?'' he
asked. ``This is something the government and the PRI should
reflect on.''
   But he said he does not expect bloodshed. ``The people are
acting with a lot of sensitivity and with a lot of maturity ... No
one wants violence in Mexico.''
   Until this year, the governing party had never lost a Senate
seat and it had won every presidential race with at least 70
percent of the vote. The party has yet to lose a governorship. The
Cardenas coalition plans to field candidates in the two
gubernatorial races at stake later this year.
   Cardenas insists that a clean Electoral College count will
probably show him the winner and give his coalition at least 10 of
the Senate's 64 seats instead of the four the election commission
claimed.
   He also says that if the Electoral College doesn't toss out
fraud-tainted returns and make public the results from each polling
place, it should call a new election.
   Neither is considered likely.
   The commission has yet to reveal tallies from 25,000 of the
nation's 55,000 polling places. But it says its overall count shows
Salinas won with 50.36 percent. It says Cardenas finished second
with 31.12 percent and Clouthier trailed with 17.07 percent.
   As for the PRI-dominated election complaint tribunal, it has
rejected about 90 percent of nearly 600 fraud charges.
   The outcome of the Electoral College session may be virtually
certain, but it won't perform what was once a mere formality
without public notice.
</TEXT>
