<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 1654EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0572 08-13 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0572,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Platform Called ``Repeat of Broken Promises''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS two grafs at end up update with remarks at Laredo.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen on Saturday called the Republican Party platform a
``repeat of broken promises'' from eight years of the Reagan
administration.
   The Texas senator, in a speech to supporters at Texas A & I
University, said he's ``been watching what's been going on at that
Republican convention, what they're talking about in that
platform.''
   ``And from what I've heard of it thus far, it's just a repeat of
some of the broken promises we heard in 1980 and back in 1984,'' he
said.
   The Republican platform committee held meetings in New Orleans
last week and the party's national convention begins there Monday
night.
   ``They've got a balanced budget amendment in that platform,'' he
said. ``Remember that in 1980? They had it in '84.
   ``And they haven't submitted a balanced budget yet to the United
States Congress. Not yet, not one,'' he said. ``Michael Dukakis as
governor of Massachusetts has introduced and passed ten balanced
budgets in a row.''
   Bentsen said the GOP delegates are ``really not in touch with
the working men and women of America.''
   ``They did a poll and found that over 80 percent of them didn't
want any funding of day care,'' he said. ``Now, the vast majority
of the American people understand the need for it.''
   Bentsen press secretary Mike McCurry said the senator was
referring to a poll of Republican delegates conducted by CNN and
USA Today.
   Bentsen is on nine-day campaign trip aimed at preventing an
erosion of Democratic support in his home state. Polls conducted
after the Democratic convention last month showed that Texas would
give its 29 electoral votes to the Democrats. Dukakis is scheduled
to join Bentsen at the end of the trip, and the campaign has bought
television ads to coincide with the effort.
   Vice President George Bush, the certain Republican nominee, also
claims Texas as his home and has been courting the state, too.
   Bush is moving more campaign operations there and has hinted
that the Texas delegation at the GOP convention might be the first
to find out his choice for a running mate.
   ``Is Texas important to this campaign _ you bet it is,'' Bentsen
said Saturday.
   Bentsen, who has said he received 90 percent of the state's
Hispanic vote in his last Senate campaign in 1982, told reporters
Friday night he doubts that President Reagan's appointment of Lauro
F. Cavazos of Texas Tech University as the new secretary of
education would help Bush.
   ``That was so apparent, I don't think it will have any
influence,'' he said. ``As far as getting any political mileage out
of it, I don't think it will. A three-month appointment is not
going to be that impressive to Hispanics.''
   The senator had a full schedule of South Texas events Saturday,
including stops in Laredo and Brownsville. He planned to spend
Saturday night and most of Sunday relaxing at his father's ranch in
McAllen, before heading to Houston for more campaigning.
   In Laredo, Bentsen spoke on local economic issues before the
Border Trade Alliance, a group that promotes better business
relations between the U.S. and Mexico.
   ``We've got to find ways to speed up the flow of people and
goods between Mexico and the U.S.,'' he said. ``But we need more
than a bill board on our side and a factory on the other side.'
</TEXT>
