<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 1710EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Riots     08-13 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Riots,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethnic Riots Kill Seven in Pakistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUETTA, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethnic Pathan transportation workers set
fire to buses of a rival group Saturday, triggering widespread
rioting throughout the city that left seven people dead and at
least 12 injured, hospital sources and witnesses said.
   Pathans and ethnic Baluchi bus and truck drivers traded gunfire
during the clash and a regional government official said army
troops were rushed in to enforce a curfew after rioting broke out.
   The violence followed a dispute between bus and truck drivers of
the two ethnic groups over the most lucrative routes.
   The Pathans attacked buses operated by Baluchis at the city's
main bus station, according to witnesses, speaking on condition of
anonymity. They said seven buses were burned and several others
damaged.
   The violence spread as the battling groups burned more buses and
fired guns at each other around the city of 550,000 people,
witnesses said.
   Authorities gave no official casualty toll, but hospital sources
said seven were killed and more than a dozen injured.
   Police moved in with tear gas but were unable to halt the
clashes until army troops finally restored order, said Mir
Zafarullah Khan Jamali, chief minister of Baluchistan province
where Quetta is capital.
   Jamali said ``the army troops were called late in the afternoon
to keep people off the streets in seven out of 10 city districts.''
   The desert Baluchi people and the mountain-dwelling Pathans have
clashed before in this region near the Afghan border. Two people
were killed and about seven injured in one such flare-up in Quetta
in January.
</TEXT>
