<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 1718EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-13 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain, More Record Heat In East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain was scattered along the Mississippi Valley on Saturday and
along the southern East Coast and central Appalachians, and there
was more high humidity and record heat across the eastern half of
the nation.
   Moisture from the Gulf of Mexico and atmospheric disturbance
produced heavy showers and thunderstorms over the middle
Mississippi Valley and near a stationary front from Wisconsin
across Minnesota to North Dakota.
   Showers and thunderstorms spread along the southern Atlantic
Coast from Florida to the Carolinas, and a few showers and
thunderstorms developed from West Virginia to western New York.
   About an inch of rain fell in just one hour at both Sioux Falls,
S.D., and Key West, Fla. St. Peters, Mo., near St. Louis, got more
than three-quarters of an inch of rain, most of it in just 10
minutes.
   Alexandria, Minn., got 1.83 inches of rain in the six hours up
to 2 p.m. EDT, while Park Falls, Wis., got 1.22 inches and Sioux
Falls, S.D., got 1.01 inches.
   During the night in northern Minnesota, 3.50 inches fell at
Hibbing, and more than 4 inches fell at Grand Rapids and Nashwak.
   A tropical depression had formed off the Florida coast, but ship
reports and other observations indicated that it was poorly
organized and no significant change in strength was expected into
Sunday.
   Detroit and Williamsport, Pa., both hit 90 degrees Saturday, for
the 37th day this summer for Detroit and and 38th time for
Williamsport. Many other cities have similar experiences this
summer.
   Temperatures rose above 100 degrees over parts of western
Oklahoma and southwestern Kansas. Altus Air Force Base, Okla.,
reached 105 degrees at 2 p.m. CDT.
   The airport just inland from Atlantic City, N.J., hit a record
high for the date of 95. But along the beach, temperatures were
only in the 70s, the National Weather Service said.
   Other record highs Saturday were 92 at Alpena, Mich.; 90 at
Binghamton, N.Y.; and 97 at Hartford, Conn. Muskegon, Mich., tied
its record of 90; New York City tied its record of 96; and Traverse
City, Mich., tied its record of 94.
   At the other extreme, Alamosa, Colo., had a record low of 36.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 59
degrees at Arcata, Calif., and Bremerton, Wash., to 106 at Gila
Bend, Ariz. The nation's low Saturday morning was 32 at Gunnison,
Colo.
   For Sunday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the northern Atlantic Coast states across the Great Lakes
region, the Ohio Valley, the upper Mississippi Valley, sections of
the Dakotas and Montana to eastern Washington. Scattered showers
and thunderstorms also were forecast from the Carolinas coast
across Florida, the Gulf Coast states and Arkansas to eastern and
north-central Texas.
   Highs in the 60s and 70s were predicted along the Pacific Coast;
ranging from 75 to 85 over northern New England, from northern
Michigan across Minnesota to eastern North Dakota, and from the
northern Rockies to the Pacific Northwest; above 100 across
sections of the Plains from South Dakota to Texas; between 100 and
112 in the desert Southwest; and in the upper 80s and 90s across
most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
