<DOCNO> AP880813-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 1729EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Protests 1stLd-Writethru a0533 08-13 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Protests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0533,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrations Under Way Before Convention Opens</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Saturday protests in top 6 grafs, picking up in
4th graf pvs, The choice</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators on behalf of the nation's poor
marched to George Bush's hotel Saturday, kicking off a week of
Republican convention-related protests before Bush or most
delegates had arrived.
   During the convention, which begins Monday, a long list of
anarchists, homosexuals, marijuana smokers, advocates for the
homeless and others, blocked from the convention site, will take
their protests to a nearby city park.
   By the weekend, 25 groups had signed up with New Orleans police
for 90 minutes each of free speech in tree-lined Lafayette Square,
several blocks from the convention at the Louisiana Superdome.
   On Saturday, about 250 members of Association of Community
Organizations for Reform Now marched from near the Superdome to the
hotel where Bush, the party's presidential nominee-in-waiting, will
be staying.
   ``As budget cuts, drugs, unemployment go on, our children are
being murdered,'' said Gerry Bell of New Orleans, one of the
protesters. At the hotel, the protesters presented Bush security
officials with a cablegram asking for action.
   On the way there, the group crossed ahead of a small group of
marchers demanding government action to help AIDS victims and stop
narcotics trafficking.
   The choice of Lafayette Square as the demonstration site rankled
a few activists who had hoped to be in front of the Dome. But some
who had picketed or given speeches in the blistering sun at the
Democratic National Convention in Atlanta last month were relieved
at the prospect of stirring things up from a shade-covered podium.
   Twelve New Orleans groups and nine national organizations have
banded together under the label CARE, Coalition Against Republican
Exploitation.
   Associates of CARE have a wide variety of activities planned,
including a kiss-in, an AIDS die-in, guerrilla theater and a rally
to protest the U.S. presence in central America and the Persian
Gulf.
   ``We are involved in non-violent, creative protest,'' said CARE
spokesman Mark Schneider.
   The police department schedule doesn't reveal any ``boxheads''
like the three columnists who showed up in Atlanta with boxes on
their heads to prove the media would make a story out of anything.
   There are skinheads signed up for Wednesday, however, and a
counter-demonstration against their white supremacist views also is
planned.
   Activists for gay rights and women's rights lead the handbill
for Sunday.
   The kiss-in will begin on Canal Street Sunday morning when
marchers pucker up to protest anti-gay sentiments, heading for
historic St. Louis Cathedral for the 11 a.m. Mass.
   The National Organization for Women will parade through the
French Quarter at Sunday noon. CARE will march in protest against
Reagan administration policies en route to a 6 p.m. rally in
Armstrong Park.
   On Monday, an AIDS die-in at City Hall is planned to dramatize
the toll the disease has taken on the gay community.
   ``Anarchists against Republicans and Democrats will be exploding
the myth of government of, by and for the people'' on Monday,
according to a flyer.
   Several organizations dedicated to helping the homeless and
hungry will also make their case at the free speech microphone on
Monday.
   Sikhs, Vietnamese veterans and born-again Christians have
registered to talk on Tuesday.
   ACT UP plans a protest against Imreg, a New Orleans
pharmaceutical company working on AIDS medication, spokesman Mark
Kostopolous said.
   He accused Imreg of profiteering at the expense of gay men.
   The Young Republicans of New Orleans will also speak on
Wednesday.
   Thursday's Lafayette Square schedule includes Theatre Shmeatre,
a group which will act out opposition to government policies.
   Protesting began in earnest Saturday with a smoke-in at
Lafayette Square to focus on ``this administration's complicity in
bringing cocaine to this country,'' Schneider said.
   ``Boycott white powder ... bring back herb,'' says one poster
featuring a clenched fist, a broken syringe and a marijuana leaf.
   ``A Night of Light and Love,'' also on Saturday, was to honor
the memory of those who have died from acquired immune deficiency
syndrome.
   The P.B.S Pinchback Conference, sponsored by the New Orleans
Rainbow Coalition, was scheduled for Saturday, trying to ``expose
the Republican Party for their anti-human policies that are causing
great suffering here and abroad.'' P.B.S. Pinchback was the only
black governor of Louisiana. He served 43 days in 1872.
</TEXT>
