<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RaceDeaths 1stLd-Writethru a0606 08-13 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Race Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0606,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Died in Recent Running Races in Central Park</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Anthony Mezzina...,' to CORRECT man's
hometown to North Bergen, N.J., sted North Bergenfield.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two young men died in the past five weeks while
running races in sweltering heat as part of a competition that pits
company teams against one another, authorities said.
   Fred Lebow, head of the New York Road Runners Club, said the
men, age 23 and 24, were non-runners who competed without adequate
preparation for the 3{-mile races.
   Organizers acknowledged that participants in the second race
were not told that someone had died three weeks earlier in the
first race.
   The races in Central Park, which drew thousands of competitors,
were sponsored by the Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. as part of
its Corporate Challenge series.
   Anthony Mezzina, 24, of North Bergen, N.J., an employee of the
Manhattan brokerage firm Spear Leeds & Kellogg, collapsed during
the race July 14 and died a day later.
   David Reynolds, 23, of Bergenfield, N.J., a technical writer for
Glasgal Communications in Northvale, N.J., collapsed shortly after
completing the Aug. 4 Corporate Challenge race. He died three days
later.
   The deaths were disclosed Friday in an article in New York
Newsday.
   Temperatures were in the 80s at the time of both races.
   Lebow said he and other race officials tried to warn the 10,000
runners in the Aug. 4 race about the dangers of running in the
heat, but didn't disclose the earlier death. Both of the
participants who died had signed waivers stating they were in good
shape and had trained for the race, Lebow said.
   Dr. Andres Rodriguez, the Road Runners Club's medical director,
said he distributed a ``medical alert'' to team captains Aug. 3
warning of the risks. ``I didn't think it was my place to call
attention to (the first death),'' he said.
   After the first death, the day after a July 14 race, team
captains were told to warn runners about running in extreme heat,
but weren't told of the death.
   According to Hanover's John Getzoff, the races are designed to
pit teams from various corporations in a friendly spirit of
competition. The races are held in 13 U.S. cities as well as
Dublin, Ireland; Oslo, Norway; and London. Top teams compete in a
championship race in New York each November.
   Dr. Patrick Griffin, associate director of medical service at
St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center, said Mezzina's body
temperature was 106 when he was admitted and Reynolds' was 107. He
said Mezzina was ``clearly out of shape'' and that Reynolds told
him he had not run more than a mile since high school.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
