<DOCNO> AP880813-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 1803EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     08-13 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roy High School soccer team played soccer
so long they forgot who and where they were and at times even
forgot how to play.
   Their more than 75-hour effort was an attempt to get into the
Guinness Book of World Records for the longest soccer game ever
played.
   The team began play Monday at noon. Seventy-five hours, 30
minutes and more than 520 goals later, the players came off the
field Thursday afternoon with what they hope will hold up as a
world record.
   The official record of 74{ hours is held by a team from Wales.
   ``Of course, there's joy and excitement at breaking the record,
but that's subsided as we've reached the moment,'' said Coach Scott
Snelson, who joined in the marathon so there would be 22 players,
enough for two teams. ``Now drowsiness, aches and pains have taken
over.''
   He said that during the ordeal, the team battled fatigue-induced
hallucinations and illness. Snelson said one team member tried to
build sand castles with the dirt near one of the goals. Another
imagined he was a small boy again, playing with his cars and trucks.
   Four players dropped out, but rules for the record attempt
allowed eight players to leave the game without disqualification,
Snelson said.
   School officials now must document the accomplishment to have
Guinness editors confirm the record.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beatles fans got a chance this weekend to romp
through Strawberry Fields Forever on a Magicial Mystery Tour or
take a Yellow Submarine and arrive Yesterday after A Hard Day's
Night.
   The occasion was Beatlefest '88, a two-day gathering for fans of
the former musical group that opened Saturday at a hotel near
O'Hare International Airport.
   ``If you're a Beatle fan you'll get a tremendous charge out of
it,'' said Irwin Blum, one of the organizers. ``It's a joyful
event.''
   For $15 a day, followers of the Fab Four got to partake in
non-stop Beatles activities in eight ballrooms, including movies,
sound-alike bands, trivia contests, auctions and a flea market.
   More than 6,000 fans from 30 states were expected to attend the
50th Beatlefest since 1974. Many of the fans were attending their
first Beatlefest, while others have made all 50, Blum said.
   ``They're all ages _ 9 or 10 years old, others in their 30s,
40s, and even some in their 60s come,'' he said. ``Some were not
even born when the Beatles were playing. They are a lovely, quiet,
peaceful group of people.''
</TEXT>
