<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Forecasters-Drugs     08-13 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forecasters-Drugs,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Blocks Drug Testing Of Weather Forecasters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government weather forecasters have become
the lastest group of federal employees to successfully challenge
the Reagan administration's random drug testing program.
   In blocking the testing, U.S. District Judge Robert Schnacke on
Friday cited the government's admission that no instances of drug
abuse or drug-related safety problems have ever been documented
among National Weather Service meteorologists. The testing was
scheduled to begin Aug. 26.
   Justice Department lawyer Richard Hertling contended no such
evidence was needed to allow drug testing of a forecaster whose
misjudgment ``conceivably could kill 300 or 400 people flying in a
jumbo jet in a storm. There's no need to wait for an accident like
that to happen.''
   Three other federal judges, two in San Francisco and one in
Washington, have blocked drug testing programs for federal workers,
including federal prison employees, most of the Veterans
Administration staff and Justice Department employees.
   Another judge in San Francisco has upheld post-accident drug
testing of air traffic controllers.
   The programs stem from President Reagan's September 1986
executive order calling for testing of employees in ``sensitive''
federal jobs.
   The Commerce Department, which includes the National Weather
Service, has declared that all meteorologists and technicians hold
``sensitive'' jobs and should be subject to random urine testing,
with about 5 percent to be tested each year. Illegal drug use would
be grounds for removal from the job.
   Richard Hirn, a lawyer for the 1,000-member National Weather
Service Employees Organization, said the random drug testing
program covers about 3,800 weather service employees, including
supervisors and non-union members.
   Hirn said Schnacke's order applies only to union members, who
filed the suit, but is likely to discourage the service from
conducting any random drug tests.
   Schnacke said the government had offered no evidence that drug
problems exist among meteorologists, much less that public safety
is threatened.
   Schnacke said he could envision ``some remote, lonely weather
station where you might want to take some artificial relief to
change the scenery.'' But, he added, ``invading people's privacy on
the premise that someday, somewhere, somehow, some problem might
arise seems to be going too far.''
   In issuing the injunction, he said the union was very likely to
prove in a trial that the testing violated the constitutional ban
on unreasonable searches.
   The injunction, binding until the lawsuit goes to trial, forbids
drug testing of union members without evidence that an individual
employee is using drugs or is under the influence of drugs on the
job.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
