<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 1916EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-CVN--GOP-Platform-Excerpts 8thAdd   08-13 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--GOP-Platform-Excerpts, 8th Add,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NEW ORLEANS: country's future.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Rural Community Development and The Family Farm</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The current drought is an emergency for our entire country. ...
We will focus assistance on those most seriously hurt by the
drought. ...
   In the late 1970s, American agriculture bore the brunt of bad
public policy. ... Inflation drove production costs and farm debt
to their highest levels in history. To top it off, the Democrats'
embargo of grain and other agricultural products dealt a blow to
the nation's heartland from which many farmers never recovered.
   NEVER AGAIN!
   ... Because of Republican policies, America's farm and rural
sector is coming alive again. ...
   Increased agricultural exports, higher commodity and livestock
prices, increased profits and land values, declining farm debt and
surpluses, all these point to a healthier outlook for the rural
economy. ...
   The Democrats offer nothing for the future of farming. Their
plan for mandatory production controls would make productive and
efficient American farmers beat a full-scale retreat from the world
market. ...
   Democrats want to put farmers on welfare while Republicans want
to look after the welfare of all rural Americans. ...
   Republicans will aggressively pursue fair and free trade for all
U.S. products....
   We will ... not use food as a weapon of foreign policy. ...
   We pledge early action to renew and improve the successful farm
programs set to expire in 1990.
   We pledge to continue international food assistance ... to feed
the world's hungry and develop markets abroad. ...
   We call for greater planting flexibility in federal programs to
allow more diversity in farming and more freedom for farmers to
grow what they want to grow and to sell their products to whoever
will buy them. ...
   We recognize traditional State supremacy in water law. ...
   We resolve to lower tax rates for long-term capital gains and to
work for fairer preproductive expense capitalization laws,
including the so-called ``heifer tax'' ...
   We will advance, in Congress and at the State level, rural
enterprise zones to attract investment and create jobs ...
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Energy for the Future</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   We recognize that energy is a security issue as well as an
economic issue. We cannot have a strong nation if we are not energy
independent.
   We are part way there....
   During the Reagan-Bush years, we loosened OPEC's hold on the
world's petroleum markets. The United States built up its Strategic
Petroleum Reserve and persuaded its allies to increase their
emergency petroleum stocks as both a deterrent and a cushion
against supply disruptions....
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Nuclear Power</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   We must preserve nuclear power as a safe and economic option to
meet future electricity needs. It generates 20 percent of our
electricity, and we anticipate the continued expansion of renewable
energy and environmentally safe nuclear power...
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Preserving and Protecting the Environment</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Republican Party has a long and honored tradition of
preserving and protecting our nation's natural resources and
environment....
   A great Republican President, Teddy Roosevelt, once
characterized our environmental challenge as ``the great central
task of leaving this land even a better land for our descendants
than it is for us.''
   ...
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Transportation for America</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Republican leadership has revitalized America's transportation
system. Through regulatory reform, we increased efficiency in all
major modes of transportation. By making our national
transportation system safer, more convenient, and less expensive,
we have both strengthened our economy and served the interests of
all the American people. ...
   As we look to the future, the Republican Party will continue to
press for improved transportation safety, reduced costs, and
greater availability and convenience of transportation through more
open markets and other mechanisms.
</TEXT>
