<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cuba-Angola     08-13 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba-Angola,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports Say Cuba May Keep Troops in Angola as Civilians</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Namibia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba may try to keep its estimated
50,000 military personnel in Angola as civilian workers despite a
commitment to withdraw them under a pact with Angola and South
Africa, a newspaper reported Saturday.
   The independent weekly Expresso quoted unidentified diplomatic
sources in Lisbon in its report.
   It said only Cuba was opposed to the section of the accord on
the withdrawal of its troops from Angola but accepted it under
pressure from the Soviet Union.
   The agreement was announced Monday after the fifth round of
peace talks between South Africa, Angola and Cuba, with the United
States participating, ended in Geneva Aug. 5.
   The accord includes a cease-fire that went into effect Monday
and calls for South Africa to begin withdrawing its 3,000 soldiers
from southern Angola.
   It set a deadline of Sept. 1 to reach agreement on a timetable
for the complete removal of Cuban troops from Angola and calls for
South Africa to give independence to South-West Africa, also known
as Namibia.
   South Africa's white-minority government has administered
Namibia since the end of World War I under a mandate of the defunct
League of Nations. That mandate was abolished by the United
Nations, but South Africa has rejected U.N. demands to give the
territory independence. One reason given by the South Africans is
the Cuban military presence in Marxist-ruled Angola.
   Expresso quoted one diplomat as saying, ``The Cubans are
reluctant to pull out of Angola and they are expected to try to
keep them (the Cuban troops) there by getting them civilian
cooperation worker status.''
   The paper reported Cuba's opposition to repatriating its troops
included concern over problems of reintegrating so many soldiers
back into society.
   Angola gained its independence from Portugal in 1975 and Marxist
forces defeated the pro-Western National Union for the Total Unity
of Angola in the civil war that followed.
   South Africa and the United States have supported the guerrillas
while the Angolan government has received assistance from the
Soviet bloc and Cuba.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
