<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Gambling     08-13 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Gambling,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>All Bets Are Off In Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviets who risk their rubles on everything from
roulette to racing will face tougher penalties against gambling
under new rules adopted by the legislature, Tass said Saturday.
   The official news agency said anybody caught gambling will face
fines of $162 to $810. The average monthly pay in the Soviet Union
is $324.
   ``Persons playing games, like cards or roulette, for money and
valuables and receiving stakes at sport and other competitions in
circumvention of the existing order at racecourses and other
facilities will no longer get off with a warning or a small fine,''
the article said.
   Tass did not say what the fines had been in the past.
   The stricter penalties were in the form of amendments to the
present gambling law. Tass said the Supreme Soviet, the country's
nominal parliament, passed the legislation Thursday.
   The new law calls for severe punishment for repeat offenders.
They could face imprisonment for 12 months, up to two years in a
corrective labor institution, or a fine of $1,620. Authorities
could also confiscate their property.
   Until recently, gambling received little attention in the Soviet
press. But over the last year many newspapers have run stories
warning people of the penalties.
   One Soviet, who asked not to be identified, said she watched a
shell game in progress last week in an underground pedestrian
tunnel.
   The game had attracted a small crowd of people, several of whom
were willing to pay $81 for the chance to guess which of three
thimbles hid a pea.
   ``I watched this for several minutes,'' she said. ``And there
was a lot of money changing hands.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
