<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Flight255-Memorial     08-13 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Flight 255-Memorial,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Relatives Gather For Memorial For Plane Crash Victims One Year
Later</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This story can stand alone or as a sidebar to BC-Flight 255,
which moved in advance on Aug. 10 as b0627 for Sunday release.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crash of Northwest Flight 255 one year ago
showed ``how fragile human life really is,'' one victim's son wrote
in a poem read to more than 1,000 people at a memorial service
Saturday.
   The crash of Flight 255 at Detroit Metropolitan Airport killed
156 people, including two on the ground, and was the nation's
second-deadliest air disaster. Four-year-old Cecelia Cichan was the
only passenger to survive the Aug. 16, 1987, crash.
   In the poem, Stephen Dresch described seeing a double rainbow
two days after his father, Lewis Dresch, died, and called it ``a
sign to tell us to go on and to remember the bright and the good
times with him.
   `In one short instant we really learn how fragile human life
really is.''
   The poem was read by television newsman Bill Bonds, who said
Dresch sent him the poem and asked him to read it at the service.
   The invitation-only observance at Ford Auditorium on Detroit's
riverfront was organized by a survivors' support group called,
``Flight 255: Their Spirit Lives On.''
   A public service will be held Tuesday night at the site on the
road where the jetliner went down.
   Saturday's service drew a family crowd. Children's exclamations
and cries occasionally accompanied the music and remarks. Those who
lost relatives wore blue ribbon pins with the white bird symbol of
the support group.
   The Rev. Ronald Lund, pastor of Bethany Lutheran Church and a
Detroit Police Department chaplain, said the crash victims are at
peace.
   ``But the problem with us is that we are still here. We still
have all the pain and the sorrow and the grief and the crying,''
Lund said.
   Outsiders can help only so much, he said. ``They have no idea
how you feel unless they had someone on that plane. You can help
each other because you do know. This support group will never allow
your loved ones to be forgotten.''
   A slide presentation of crash victims' photos and their names
was interrupted by mechanical problems, but was shown at the end of
the service.
   Lund said later that 40 to 80 members of the support group meet
at least once a month to talk and plan activities such as the
service.
   The observance marked a turning point, said Kay Gleason, one of
the group's founders. ``I don't mean a way of forgetting, but a
year has gone by and you have to let go. This is one way to do
it,'' she said.
   The group wants to erect a monument with the crash victims'
names, said Betty Polec of suburban Mount Clemens, also a founder.
Her 21-year-old daughter, two months pregnant, and her daughter's
husband died in the crash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
