<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Hostages     08-13 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Hostages,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Diplomat Seeking Release of Hostages Meets Iranian
Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British diplomat met with Iranian
officials Saturday to seek the release of foreign hostages held in
Lebanon by pro-Iranian extremists.
   David Reddaway arrived in Tehran Friday for what he said would
be a two-week visit. He said he had a ``useful'' first meeting with
officials from Iran's Foreign Ministry, but he declined comment on
the content of the talks.
   Before leaving London, Reddaway said he would speak with
officials here about the 18 foreigners missing and believed held by
pro-Iranian militants in Lebanon, including Anglican envoy Terry
Waite and two other Britons.
   The British Home Office announced last week that Reddaway also
would seek the release or trial of two Britons, businessman Roger
Cooper and tourist Nicholas Nicola, who have been imprisoned in
Iran since 1986.
   Iran's representative in Britain said Thursday the hostage issue
could be resolved if there is good will on all sides and Iran was
trying to help.
   Nine of the 18 foreign hostages are Americans and Terry
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press,
has been held the longest. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   Waite disappeared in Lebanon in January 1987 while trying to
secure the release of the foreign hostages.
   In London, the Observer newspaper, quoted unidentified Iranian
sources as saying Waite and two other Britons missing in Lebanon
would be released by their abductors ``within weeks.''
   The Observer's Sunday edition reported the sources said Iran
would wait until Reddaway returns to London and then would secure
the release of Waite and television journalist John McCarthy and
teacher Brian Keenan.
   It quoted one Iranian source in London as saying, ``Things are
going smoothly and the hostages should be back within weeks.'' The
report said the source has close links to the Iranian government.
   Keenan, from Northern Ireland, has been missing since April 11,
1986, and McCarthy was kidnapped six days later.
</TEXT>
