<HEAD>4 Injured as Shuttle Bus Veers Into Crowd of Spectators at Car
Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shuttle bus used to transport track
workers crashed through a fence and into a crowd of spectators
watching a car race at Watkins Glen International Saturday,
injuring four people, officials said.
   The accident occurred behind the grandstand near the end of the
final event of the International Race of Champions series, said
J.J. O'Malley, a spokesman for the track.
   The shuttle bus with only its driver aboard ``veered out of
control, went through a ditch and a spectator fence'' and into the
crowd, said O'Malley.
   Other details of the crash and its cause were not immediately
known, Schuyler County Sheriff's Deputy John Pierce said.
   Four spectators were taken to a hospital in Elmira, where two
were treated and released and two were admitted, authorities said.
   Sandy Parrot, 40, of Odessa was in critical condition with a
pelvic injury, said Arnot Ogden Hospital nursing supervisor Kathy
Good. Jim Siles, 24, of Rochester, was listed in serious condition
with hip, leg and neck injuries, Good said.
