<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PlantExplosion 1stLd-Writethru a0620 08-13 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Explosion, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0620,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Explosion At Chemical Plant Ignites Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with fire out and location,
CLARIFIES that plant came under scrutiny after Bhopal. Picks up 6th
graf pvs, `The blast...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INSTITUTE, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion ripped through part of a
chemical plant that produces a toxic gas Saturday, but officials
said no one was injured and a fire ignited by the blast burned out
about seven hours later.
   The explosion occurred in a pipe carrying the flammable gas
ethylene oxide from a storage tank inside the Rhone-Poulenc Inc.
plant, said Jim Lake, the plant's human resources manager. The
blast set off two fires, one of which quickly died. Workers shut
off the flow to the pipe and allowed the second fire to burn itself
out Saturday afternoon.
   ``There is no danger to the community,'' Lake said before the
fire was out.
   The explosion occurred in a part of the chemical plant sold to
Rhone-Poulenc in 1986 by Union Carbide Corp., which still operates
part of the complex. Union Carbide uses ethylene oxide to make
antifreeze and polyoils, said Union Carbide spokesman Leon McClure.
   The then-Union Carbide plant came under close scrutiny after a
leak of a toxic chemical, methyl isocyanate, at a Union Carbide
plant in Bhopal, India, in 1984, killed nearly 3,000 people. The
plant in Institute also produces methyl isocyanate.
   A leak of two other chemicals at the plant in 1985 injured 135
people.
   The blast occurred near a pipe used to carry methyl isocyanate
to a storage tank, but that line was filled with nitrogen on
Saturday, McClure said.
   The Rhone-Poulenc plant is 11 miles west of downtown Charleston
along a 15-mile corridor lined with more than two dozen chemical
plants on the Kanawha River.
   Saturday's 9:30 a.m. explosion shattered windows in nearby
homes, but the area was not evacuated. Lake said the cause of the
explosion was under investigation.
   ``It was scary,'' said Mark Cardwell, who lives in Nitro, about
a mile from the plant. ``I was asleep ... it was a real big boom.
The water bed shook.''
   McClure said ethylene oxide neutralizes as it burns.
   ``I'm sure a small amount got out, but there was no threat to
employees or to the community,'' he said.
   The plant used its own emergency crews to fight the blaze, and
plant officials did not allow police and firefighters inside the
plant. State troopers were finally let in about 10:20 a.m., after
threatening to force their way into the plant.
   McClure insisted Union Carbide cooperated with authorities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880813-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 2131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SriLanka-Slayings     08-13 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka-Slayings,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING TO FIX CYCLE DESIGNATOR</HEAD>
<HEAD>Seven Indian Soldiers Slain At Rail Bridge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected Tamil insurgents shot and
killed seven Indian soldiers Saturday after blowing up a railway
bridge linking Colombo with northern Sri Lanka, Indian authorities
said.
   An official at the Indian Embassy in Colombo said the soldiers
were ambushed near the town of Vavuniya, 135 miles north of Colombo.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
soldiers were patrolling railway tracks in the area after Tamil
rebels blew up a nearby bridge to disconnect links between Colombo
and the Jaffna peninsula to the north.
   The latest ambush raises the number of Indian soldiers killed in
Sri Lanka since last October to at least 544. India said last month
that 537 soldiers had been killed but the embassy official said no
updated figures were available.
   India has at least 50,000 troops in Sri Lanka to enforce a peace
accord aimed at ending the Tamil insurgency on the island. The
rebels reneged on the accord last fall and the Indians have since
attempted to disarm them.
   Tamils form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
Radicals started a campaign for an independent Tamil homeland in
1983, claiming the community was being discriminated against by the
Sinhalese, who comprise 75 percent of the population.
   India brokered the peace accord because of the sympathies of its
own 60 million Tamils for the rebel cause.
</TEXT>
