<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Ortega     08-13 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Ortega,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Says Dukakis Would Bring Better Relations With Region</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said Saturday
a victory by Democrat Michael Dukakis in November's presidential
election could bring improved U.S. relations with Central America.
   Ortega also said Nicaragua would accept an international peace
force to guarantee security along its border with Honduras.
   The president, speaking to Nicaraguan ambassadors now in
Managua, said Dukakis holds different views on Latin American
policy than those of Vice President George Bush, the Republican
candidate.
   Bush's policy ``is the same as (President) Reagan's, a
confirmation of the Monroe Doctrine, while that of Dukakis is
different,'' Ortega said.
   The Monroe Doctrine, outlined in 1823 by President James Monroe,
asserts that Latin America holds special importance for U.S.
security and other nations should not interfere in the region.
   ``If eventually Dukakis reaches the presidency of the United
States and has the opportunity and capacity to implement the policy
he has announced during the Democratic convention, very important
foundations would be laid ... to establish a dialogue that provides
a new type of relations between the United States, Latin America
and the Caribbean,'' Ortega said.
   Dukakis has opposed resuming military aid to Nicaraguan rebels,
known as Contras. Bush supports such aid and the U.S. Senate voted
last week to provide $27 million in humanitarian assistance to the
Contras.
   Speaking of a possible border peacekeeping force, Ortega said
the Nicaraguan-Honduran frontier ``is a powder keg that could be
made to explode at any minute by the United States to justify an
invasion of Nicaragua.''
   He proposed that a border peace force be put together by Spain,
Canada, West Germany and a country from the Contadora group and its
support nations.
   Mexico, Venezuela, Colombia and Panama make up the Contadora
group that was formed in 1983 at a meeting of foreign ministers on
the Panamanian island of Contadora to seek peace in Central
America. Brazil, Argentina, Peru and Uruguay are the support
nations.
   Ortega made a similar proposal after Honduras suggested the
creation of a border peace force in November 1987 at a meeting of
the Organization of American States in Washington.
   Ortega also told the ambassadors that his Sandinista government
will continue a unilateral cease-fire with the rebels until Aug. 31.
   Negotiations on a permanent cease-fire stalled in June. Ortega
proposed Friday that a new round of talks on ending the
seven-year-old war be held in Managua or Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
