<HEAD>With AM-Heat Psychology, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Another dozen record highs bit the dust Saturday as unseasonably
hot weather continued.
   Residents of the Northeast were suffering even as far north as
Portland, Maine, where a stretch of 13 consecutive days of high
temperatures in the 80s or 90s equaled a record established in
1980, the National Weather Service said.
   Milwaukee tied a record for 33 days of 90 degrees or more in a
year. Detroit's high of 92 marked the 37th day of 90-degree or
higher temperatures and broke the mark of 36 days set in 1934, the
weather service said.
   The weather service reported these record high temperatures for
the date, along with the old record and the year it was set:
   Alpena, Mich., 93, 90 in 1978
   Atlantic City, N.J., 95, 90 in 1959
   Baltimore (airport), 99, 98 in 1881
   Baltimore (downtown), 97 94 in 1970
   Beckley, W.Va. (airport), 88, 85 in 1985
   Binghamton, N.Y., 90, 85 in 1985
   Bluefield, W.Va., 88, 83 in 1985
   Elkins, W.Va., 91, tied 91 in 1944
   Greer, S.C., 93, tied 93 in 1977
   Hartford, Conn., 97, 96 in 1944
   Muskegon, Mich., 90, tied 90 in 1944
   New York, 96, tied 96 in 1944
   Traverse City, Mich., 94, tied 94 in 1944
