<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Castro-US     08-13 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Castro-US,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Castro Calls For United States To Back Off In Latin America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuban President Fidel Castro on Saturday
accused Washington of trying to dominate Latin America and said
U.S.-Cuban relations will not improve until America changes its
policies.
   The communist leader said the two nations would remain at odds
``while the United States meddles in our countries, while the
United States practices that role of dominance that it has assumed
for itself.''
   But Castro also said he hoped for improved relations with
America. He said he ``came close to applauding'' U.S. Secretary of
State George P. Shultz when Shultz entered Ecuador's Congress on
Wednesday for the inauguration of Ecuador's new president, a
socialist.
   Castro, Shultz and other international leaders were in Quito to
attend the inauguration of President Rodrigo Borja, who has pledged
a non-aligned foreign policy.
   During a two-hour-long news conference, Castro said the huge
foreign debts owed by Latin American nations could not be paid. He
compared attempts by international bankers to collect the debt with
efforts to extract ``the last drop of blood'' from a dying man.
   On another topic, Castro said Cuban-Soviet relations have not
been hurt by Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev's social and economic
reforms.
   ``I want you to know that there are no problems between
Gorbachev and me,'' he said.
</TEXT>
