<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 2303EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Airline-Antitrust     08-13 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airline-Antitrust,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Allows Much Of $300 Million Airline Antitrust Suit To
Proceed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Edd cq in last graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge, finding evidence that
American Airlines exerted monopoly control over the airline ticket
reservation market, has allowed 12 smaller carriers to proceed with
a $300,000 antitrust suit.
   U.S. District Judge Edward Rafeedie on Friday also found
sufficient evidence of predatory price-cutting and price
discrimination in American's SABRE reservation system to proceed to
trial on those claims.
   SABRE, along with United Airlines' reservation system, delivers
most airlines tickets sold in the United States.
   Smaller airlines, which pay fees for tickets booked through the
systems, contend that American and United abuse their domination in
the computer reservation market by charging high fees and imposing
restrictions that make it difficult for travel agents to switch to
rival systems.
   American and United counter that the fees are needed to
compensate for the millions of dollars invested in computers and
data banks. American says it has invested $400 million in SABRE.
   The judge's decision means a jury may decide whether American
has engaged in anti-competitive business practices and it left open
the possibility that a jury can decide whether United may have
engaged in a limited monopoly over the computer reservation market.
   The judge dismissed claims that American and United wielded a
monopoly over the entire airline industry, saying both airlines
make up only a small portion of the airline market.
   Lawyers for both American and the smaller carriers both
expressed satisfaction with the ruling.
   ``We're pleased that our legal theory has been judicially
vindicated, and we have an opportunity to try these charges,'' said
Maxwell M. Blecher, an attorney for USAir, one of the carriers
challenging American and United.
   ``On balance, we're very pleased with the outcome,'' said
American lawyer J. Edd Stepp Jr. ``To the extent the judge did not
agree with us, all he's said is the plaintiffs have raised enough
of a factual issue that he's not going to decide this (without a
jury trial).''
</TEXT>
