<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Honduras-US     08-13 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-US,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduran and U.S. Troops Finish Two Weeks of Maneuvers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,200 U.S. military personnel
on Saturday ended two weeks of anti-subversion training with 800
Honduran soldiers in central Honduras.
   During the exercises the troops also did construction work,
donated school supplies, distributed food, built furniture for
government schools and provided medical and dental service,
according to the government. About 30,000 people live in the region
around 35 miles northeast of the capital of Tegucigalpa.
   ``Our army has improved its combat capacity with this exercise,
which will allow us to efficiently defend national sovereignty,''
Col. Roberto Martinez Avila, head of the armed forces chiefs of
staff, said at a ceremony closing the maneuvers.
   The United States and Honduras have held more than 60 joint
military exercises since 1982 involving rotating U.S. troops
including National Guard units.
   About 1,100 U.S. military personnel are stationed at Palmerola
air base 35 miles northwest of Tegucigalpa.
   Nicaragua's left-wing Sandinista government has said the
maneuvers jeopardize Nicaraguan sovereigny.
</TEXT>
