<1ST_LINE>u a AM-VanCrash     08-13 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Van Crash,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Team's Outing Ends In Tragedy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The young boys and girls of the Midland
Boys Club had spent the last week practicing for an out-of-town
softball tournament, but their trip ended in tragedy.
   Five lost their lives and 12 others in a Boys Club van were
injured, four of them critically, in a collision Friday with a
tractor-trailer near Sweetwater in west Texas. The truck driver
also was injured.
   ``It's truly a miracle any of them are alive,'' said Nolan
County Sheriff Jim Blackley.
   Elsewhere, multifatality traffic accidents killed a total of 16
people in Illinois, Ohio and Florida.
   Midland Boys Clubs officials Saturday thanked people in the
community for their sympathy and response during the tragedy.
   ``In particular, we are grateful to those who we do not know,
whose faces we have not seen, those who provided swift medical
attention to our children,'' said Chuck Clarkson, chairman of the
board of the boys club.
   Trooper David Gonzales said the van was nearly alongside the
Coca-Cola truck when the van driver apparently dozed off and
swerved onto a grassy median. The driver, attempting to regain
control, oversteered the van directly into the path of the truck,
Gonzales told The Dallas Morning News.
   Gonzales said the van, with 17 passengers, was overloaded. He
said there should have been no more than a dozen passengers.
   The van was returning from a softball tournament in Abilene
earlier in the day. Clarkson said the tournament was to cap the
summer program for underprivileged youth in Midland.
   ``They had been practicing pretty hard for the softball
tournament, and they were really excited about it,'' he said.
   A memorial service was planned for Sunday afternoon.
   The driver of the van and nine occupants remained hospitalized
Saturday in hospitals in Lubbock and Abilene. The truck driver was
released Saturday, but refused interviews.
   In other multifatality accidents:
   _Four students at the Orlando Naval Training Center died
Saturday when a pickup truck crossed the median and struck their
compact car head-on in the Orlando, Fla., suburb of Bithlo.
   _A tractor-trailer truck slammed into a car early Saturday in
Granite City, Ill., killing five of the car's occupants and
injuring two others. In Columbia, Ill., three young women were
killed in a five-car accident Friday.
   _A collision between two vans at a rural intersection in the
northwestern Ohio town of Kenton killed four people and injured
five others Friday night.
</TEXT>
