<2ND_LINE>AM-Tropical Weather, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0623,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Depression Drifts Toward Southeast; Small Craft Advised to Stay In
Port</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs graf 2-5 grafs with 4 grafs to update with forecast for
system to move inland, new location, direction, speed; Picks up 6th
graf pvs: `There were...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Small-craft operators from central Florida to the
Carolinas were advised to stay in port Saturday as a tropical
depression with winds up to 50 mph swept across the Atlantic Ocean
toward the Southeast coast.
   Showers and thunderstorms with gusty winds moved along the coast
from Cape Canaveral, Fla., through Georgia, and the system was
expected to move inland Saturday night.
   At 10:30 p.m. EDT, forecasters at the National Hurricane Center
estimated that the broad, diffuse center of the system was about 85
miles east of Brunswick, Ga., said Bob Sheets, center director.
   The system was moving toward the west-northwest at 15 to 20 mph
and was expected to keep that general course and speed.
   The depression's highest sustained winds were clocked at 35 mph
in squalls and thunderstorms well north of the center. No
significant change in strength was expected before the depression
moves inland and weakens, forecasters said.
   ``There were some squalls off to the north and east of the
center with winds up to 50 miles per hour,'' said National Weather
Service meteorologist Mark Zimmer.
   The small-craft advisory covered the coast from Cape Canaveral
northward to South Carolina's Little River Inlet, near the North
Carolina-South Carolina border.
</TEXT>
