<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Floods, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0591,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Flooded Again, Homeless Toll Rises to 2 Million</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf to CORRECT spelling of Nour el-Dayem; picks up
8th graf pvs: Western relief...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rains again flooded this desert
capital Saturday, and a Cabinet minister said international aid
coming in was not enough for the 2 million people left homeless so
far.
   The latest storm began around midnight Friday and lasted until
midmorning, tearing trees from their roots and leaving huge pools
of water in the streets of downtown Khartoum, a city of 4 million.
   The city's airport was shut down and the Nile river was rising,
fueling fears that it might soon overflow and worsen the damge
caused by the flooding.
   The flooding began with a storm Aug. 4-5 that dumped six times
as much rain on Khartoum as the city received in all of 1987.
   In Cairo, the Egyptian daily Al-Gomhuriya said in an
unattributed dispatch from Khartoum that 400 people had died from
the flooding. The Sudanese government has reported 39 deaths.
   Al-Ahram, another Egyptian daily, quoted Sudanese Finance
Minister Omar Nour el-Dayem as saying the number of people left
homeless in Khartoum and three cities in eastern and northern Sudan
had risen to 2 million.
   Nour el-Dayem defended his government against charges it was not
efficiently handling the distribution of relief. He said
international aid already received was ``a drop in the ocean when
compared to the size of the disaster.'' The government has
estimated the damage caused so far at $200 million.
   Western relief agencies urged the Sudanese government to allow
non-governmental organizations help distribute relief supplies.
They said the Sudanese army, which is handling most of the
distribution, was not reaching some of those affected.
   The Cairo daily Al-Akhbar quoted unidentified relief agency
officials as saying the renewed rains, together with the expected
flooding of the Nile, delayed distribution of aid and shortages of
electricity, drinking water and food, creating ``an extremely
dangerous situation'' which was getting worse.
   The officials were quoted as saying the army was having
difficulty distributing blankets, tents, food and other medical
supplies and in some cases, refused to distribute the relief for
``reasons we do not understand.''
   News reports Friday said hundreds of tons of supplies were
waiting in Khartoum for distribution.
   Some of those hardest hit by the flooding were nearly 1 million
people who fled drought and civil war in Sudan's rural areas to
seek refuge in squatter settlements ringing Khartoum.
   One such settlement, Marzouk west of Khartoum, was reduced to a
sprawling collection of crumbling walls and collapsed hovels.
Journalists touring Marzouk encountered no one among its 15,000
residents who said they received any emergency relief.
   ``We need tents and plastic sheets,'' said Abdullahim Idris
Kody, 32. He said his family had slept outside since floods
destroyed his two-room hut.
   Kody said no food or medicine reached Marzouk and children there
were beginning to develop intestinal problems and coughs.
   Several soldiers stood outside six orange army tents, where a
young woman said she was handing out less than 2 pounds of wheat
flour per family daily in addition to supplementary foods including
sardines, dates and sugar.
   But no distribution was seen, and residents complained the
rations were being distributed along political lines and only to
``special families.''
   Information on the relief operation in Khartoum was scarce, and
it was not possible to determine whether the situation at Marzouk
was typical of other settlements.
   Abdul Mohammed of the Sudan Council of Churches said local
non-governmental organizations were trying to care for displaced
people at the settlements but lacked staff and supplies.
   Most of the assistance received so far has come from Arab
nations in the form of government-to-government aid.
   On Friday, Western deliveries began to pick up with the arrival
of Dutch, U.S. and UNICEF cargo planes carrying supplies earmarked
for non-governmental agencies, such as the Sudan Council of
Churches.
   Mohammed said such groups could handle only 15 percent of the
displaced population's needs and would help only the most desperate.
</TEXT>
