<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Obit-EllaUdall 1stLd-Writethru a0659 08-13 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Ella Udall, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman's Wife Dies In Apparent Suiide</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: REFOCUSES lede</NOTE>
<DATELINE>McLEAN, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ella Royston Udall, 59, the wife of Rep.
Morris Udall, D-Ariz., was found dead in her garage Saturday
morning, an apparent suicide from carbon monoxide poisoning. Police
are investigating.
   Fairfax County Police spokesman Warren Carmichael said Udall
found his wife's body about 10 a.m. in the front seat of her
automobile parked in the family residence.
   ``It's being investigated as a suicide from carbon monoxide
poisoning pending a test by the medical examiner,'' Carmichael
said, noting reports from fire and rescue workers of ``a very heavy
concentration of carbon monoxide in the garage area.''
   Mrs. Udall, who was not breathing when her husband found her,
was rushed to Fairfax County Hospital, but she could not be
revived, he said.
   Robert Neuman, Udall's administrative assistant, said no note
was found, and that Mrs. Udall had been in good spirits.
   A native of Loudoun County, Va., Mrs. Udall had served as a
staff assistant on a subcommittee of the House Post Office and
Civil Service Committee before her Dec. 1, 1968 marriage to the
Arizonia congressman.
   Mrs. Udall, who frequently said she considered being a
congressman's wife a full-time career, is survived by her son,
Vincent Fabrizio Jr., from a previous marriage, and Udall's six
children.
   Udall, 65, has been suffering from Parkinson's disease. However,
he announced his decision in April to seek his 15th in Congress.
</TEXT>
