<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Obit-Williams 2ndLd-Writethru a0647 08-13 1041</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Williams, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0647,1,000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Well-Known Attorney Edward Bennett Williams Dies At 68</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 3 new grafs after third graf beginning ``Williams,
who had suffered ...'' to include more comment.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Famed criminal attorney Edward Bennett
Williams, whose clients included union leader Jimmy Hoffa,
congressman Adam Clayton Powell and former Texas Gov. John B.
Connally, died of cancer Saturday in Georgetown University
Hospital. He was 68.
   Williams, who was admitted to the medical facility on Wednesday,
died at 6:15 p.m., according to Georgetown hospital spokeswoman
Anne Klass.
   Williams, who secured his own niche in American trial lore while
still in his 30s moved into the sports world as a part owner and
former president of the Washington Redskins football club and then
as owner of the Baltimore Orioles baseball club.
   Williams, who had suffered from cancer for more than a decade,
was an exponent of what he called ``contest living,'' obsessed with
victory. He gave no quarter, even to the disease that finally
killed him after he had fended off its assault with oft-tortuous
therapy and at least seven operations. Virtually to the end, he
worked hard as ever. ``Either it's going to beat me,'' he said of
his cancer, ``or I'm going to beat it.''
   Joseph Califano, a former law partner and a member of the
President Carter's cabinet as head of the then-Health, Education
and Welfare Department, said, ``He was the best everything. He was
the best father, the best husband, the best lawyer, the best
partner, the best friend...and he was extraordinarily brave.''
   Baltimore Mayor Kurt Schmoke said, ``The death of Edward Bennett
Williams is a great loss to Baltimore, Washington and the nation.
Mr. Williams was a towering figure in Baltimore as the owner of our
beloved Orioles and even though he did not live here, he proved
time and again his commitment to the city through his involvement
in the local community and more recently signing a long-term lease
to keep the Orioles in Baltimore.''
   Bob Douglas, a spokesman for Maryland Gov. William Donald
Schaefer, read a statement which said in part: ``Although he was
the toughest negotiator I ever encountered, he was always true and
fair in his dealings. And this spring, he kept his promise to never
move the Orioles by signing a long-term lease which commits the
ballclub to Baltimore for the next 15 years.''
   Morris Siegel, a Washington newspaper columunist and friend of
Williams, said from his hospital bed in Atlanta, Ga., ``It is
really sad _ even when you know it is coming.''
   Duke Zeibert, owner of a downtown Washington restaurant where
Williams often had lunch, said ``If ever there was a fighter, he
was it. He would never give up.''
   ``I loved this guy, he was just amazing. Just being around him
you learned things, he was just a wonderful human being,'' Zeibert
said. ``There ain't too many like him.''
   Williams enchanted juries, befuddled prosecutors, defended
pariahs and befriended the mighty. Inside the courtroom, he beat
the best the government could offer; outside of it he gave his best
to government, performing a variety of tough legal missions abroad
and advisory roles at home.
   In one of his last high-profile cases, Williams defended
millionaire industrialist Victor Posner, who eventually pleaded no
contest last Sept. 29 to evading more than $1.2 million in federal
taxes by inflating the value of land he donated to a bible college
as a tax exemption.
   Sentencing was delayed twice last December after Williams
telephoned the judge to say he was to undergo surgery in Washington.
   Williams' customers also included the Democratic National
Committee _ he served two years as the party's treasurer _ and The
Washington Post, the Ford Motor Co., and Gulf & Western as well as
gangster Frank Costello, CIA director Richard Helms, Sen. Joseph R.
McCarthy and Bobby Baker, an aide to Sen. Lyndon B. Johnson.
   By his own account, Williams personally lost only one ``major''
case, the 1967 fraud and income tax evasion trial of Bobby Baker,
an aide to Lyndon B. Johnson. Williams went home with him, Baker
said, and burst into tears.
   He couldn't stand losing outside the courtroom, either. As
president of the Redskins, he spent to get the best, first hiring
the legendary Vince Lombardi (``Winning isn't everything, it's the
only thing'') as coach, and then, after Lombardi's death, George
Allen.
   When Jack Kent Cooke bought out his share _ and virtual control
_ of the football team, Williams already had acquired another toy,
baseball's Orioles in nearby Baltimore. The team won the 1983 World
Series with manager Joe Altobelli, but when it began to slump in
1985, Williams promptly dumped him and lured another coaching
legend, Earl Weaver, out of retirement.
   As it turned out, even Weaver couldn't rejuvenate the Orioles'
pitching, and he retired again after the 1986 season.
   Cal Ripken Sr., the 1987 manager, got the ax after the Orioles
dropped six consecutive games to open the 1988 season. He then
hired Frank Robinson to now avail - they lost another 15 straight.
   Despite his deteriorating health, Williams remained in active
control of the Orioles until late May, when he turned over
day-to-day operations to law partner Lawrence Lucchino.
   Williams, born May 31, 1920, was the only child of a floorwalker
in a Hartford, Conn., department store. When his father was laid
off during the Depression, he all but abandoned his hopes of going
to college, but the vice principal of his high school got him a
scholarship at Holy Cross, the rigidly disciplined Jesuit college
at Worcester, Mass.
   He joined the Army Air Force in World War II, but was soon
injured in the crash of a training plane _ everyone else aboard was
killed _ and was discharged. He enrolled at the Georgetown
University Law School in Washington.
   Even before he passed the bar, Hogan & Hartson, then the
capital's second-largest law firm, hired him on Georgetown's
recommendation.
   After marrying his boss's daughter, Dorothy Adair, Williams hung
out his own shingle. She died, at age 34, of a respiratory illness,
and Williams married Agnes Neill, then a top lawyer in his own
firm, a year later. He had three children by his first marriage,
four by the second.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
