<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-Arias     08-13 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Arias,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Pay Homage to Former President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of mourners paid homage to
three-time President Oscar Arnulfo Arias Madrid on Saturday as his
body was brought back to Panama from Miami, where he had been
living in exile.
   The Harvard-educated physician, overthrown by the military in
each of his presidencies, died of a heart attack Wednesday in
Miami. He was 86.
   Mourners lined the 15-mile route of the funeral cortege from the
airport to Panama City's Metropolitan Cathedra.
   Some people shouted, ``Mr. President, your people are present,''
and ``Arnulfo, Panama cries for you'' as the hearse and hundreds of
other vehicles in the procession passed by.
   Arias founded the Authentic Panamanian Party and was elected to
three, four-year presidential terms beginning in 1940. But he was
ousted in 1941, then was re-elected and served for 18 months in
1949-1951 and only 11 days in 1968.
   He ran again for the presidency in 1984 but lost to a military
candidate in elections the opposition said were fraudulent.
   A nationalist and anti-communist, Arias backed legislation that
gave women the vote and created Panama's social security system
during his terms in office.
   He went into self-imposed exile in Miami in December. Arias was
a critic of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the head of Panama's
Defense Forces and power behind the civilian governnment but he did
not actively participate in opposition efforts to force Noriega to
resign.
   Noriega was indicted by federal grand juries in Florda last
February on drug trafficking charges and the United States has
imposed economic sanctions on Panama as Noriega has refused to step
down.
   Arias' body will lie in state at the Roman Catholic cathedral
until Monday when burial services will be at the Garden of Peace
cemetery. Arias would have been 87 Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
