<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JailSuicide     08-13 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jail Suicide,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Murderer Commits Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CROWN POINT, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who confessed to two killings
because he believed the statute of limitations had run out
committed suicide hours after he was convicted of murder.
   George L. Bonner, 58, hanged himself in his Lake County Jail
cell shortly before 5 a.m. Thursday, said County Police Chief James
Reyome and Coroner Daniel D. Thomas.
   Reyome said Bonner, who faced a maximum penalty of 150 years in
jail, wrote a suicide note indicating he did not want to serve any
more time behind bars.
   Superior Court Judge Richard J. Conroy had to tell jurors about
the suicide early Thursday when they returned to decide whether
Bonner was a habitual criminal, so they could recommend a sentence.
``It was very difficult for them and me,'' Conroy said.
   Public defender Kevin Relphorde said he and jurors re-examined
the case afterward. ``Jurors asked me why (Bonner) didn't take the
witness stand. He wanted to do it, but I advised him not to. I
wonder if there are other things I could have done,'' Relphorde
said.
   Jurors convicted Bonner of killing Eunice Souters, 67, and
Othell Crenshaw, 49, on April 28, 1979, in the victims' apartment.
   The crime had remained unsolved until last year when Gary police
Sgt. William Hlas arrested Bonner in an unrelated crime.
   Relphorde said Hlas told jurors Bonner confessed to the killings
thinking he could no longer be prosecuted because too much time had
elapsed. He didn't realize there is no statute of limitations for
murder.
</TEXT>
