<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0033EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Cannibalism     08-13 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Cannibalism,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Refugee Agency Reserves Judgment On `Boat People' Episode</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. refugee agency will reserve judgment on
reports of cannibalism among a boatload of Vietnamese refugees
until Philippine authorities complete their inquiry, a spokesman
said Friday.
   Sergio Vieira de Mello, head of the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees bureau for Asia and Oceania bureau, told The Associated
Press he did not know how long the inquiry will take.
   Vietnamese `boat people' have international refugee status and
come under the agency's protection, which can be withdrawn if
refugees commit crimes.
   The captain of the USS Dubuque was temporarily relieved of his
duties this week pending an investigation of charges that his ship
did not adequately assist the refugees when it encountered them in
the South China Sea.
   The Navy is helping investigate reports of murder and
cannibalism that appeared this week in a Manila newspaper. The
Vietnamese eventually were rescued near the Philippines and are in
a refugee camp there.
   Survivors were quoted survivors as saying they killed and ate
some of their fellow passengers to stay alive after they
encountered the Dubuque on June 9. Two victims reportedly died of
starvation, but three others allegedly were murdered through
drowning and then eaten.
   Some survivors said the Dubuque refused to take them aboard even
though their boat was disabled and they were dying of exposure and
starvation. The ship's crew them food and water.
   Robert Cooper, the U.N. refugee agency's Manila representative,
said 52 refugees survived 37 days at sea but 58 people died. The
refugees set out from the Mekong Delta town of Ben Tre on May 22
aboard a 35-foot wooden boat. Its engine failed two or three days
later.
   Navy regulations say warships may pick up refugees on the high
seas if the vessel is judged unseaworthy, bad weather is
approaching or there are ``other special circumstances.''
</TEXT>
