<HEAD>Ex-President Summoned to Testify on South Korean Uprising</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A parliamentary investigating
committee controlled by the opposition voted Friday to subpoena
former President Choi Kyu-hah to testify about the bloody civil
uprising in Kwangju in 1980.
   The opposition intends to prove that another former president,
Chun Doo-hwan, played a role in the military suppression of the
uprising in which about 200 people died.
   The current president, Roh Tae-woo, is linked to Chun. Roh was
one of the generals who helped Chun take control when Choi resigned
in 1980.
   After seven hours of heated debate, the committee voted, 15-0,
to summon Choi. Twelve committee members from the governing
Democratic Justice Party boycotted the vote and an independent
member was absent.
   Choi served as president for 10 months after President Park
Chung-hee was assassinated in October 1979. The Kwangju rebellion
took place while Choi was president in May 1980.
   The opposition hopes eventually to bring Chun before two
parliamentary committees. It wants to look into Chun's role not
only at Kwangju but in financial and other scandals involving his
seven-year presidency.
   Chun left office in February and was succeeded by Roh, who was
voted into the presidency over a divided opposition.
   A brother of Chun, Chun Kyung-hwan, is now on trial on charges
of embezzeling millions of dollars in official funds.
</TEXT>
