<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sweden-Soviets     08-13 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Soviets,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Jewish Couple Sail to Sweden</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Israeli Embassy gave travel
documents Friday to a Jewish couple who left the Soviet Union in a
20-foot sailboat, with the Kremlin's blessing, and docked in Sweden
on their way to Israel.
   Alexander Berman and his wife Luba Padas said they were the
first people allowed by Soviet authorities to emigrate in a boat.
Private ownership of a vessel is uncommon in the Soviet Union.
   ``We sold everything we owned and borrowed the rest from
friends'' to buy the boat, Berman, 51, said through an interpreter.
He said they paid 6,130 rubles (about $9,800) for it a year ago.
   Berman has written books about traveling in the Soviet Arctic
and his 33-year-old wife, a musician, has gone on sailing and
mountain-climbing expeditions.
   He said he had not been involved in Zionist activities and
encountered no problems in obtaining an emigration visa, with the
process taking three months.
   ``I know refuseniks have had a difficult time, but others have
had a very easy time'' in getting permission to leave, he said.
``For us it was very easy.''
   Refusenik refers mainly to Soviet Jews but also to other Soviet
citizens whose applications for exit visas are refused by the
government.
   After a four-day, 180-mile voyage from Riga, Latvia, the couple
landed on the Swedish island of Gotland in the Baltic Sea on
Tuesday.
   Berman said his greatest fear was that storms would blow his
small craft back to the Soviet Union where they were barred from
landing after relinquishing their Soviet citizenship.
</TEXT>
