<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Hormones     08-13 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Hormones,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scandal over giving calves hormones spreads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUESSELDORF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scandal involving the illegal
use of growth-enhancing hormones on calves in North
Rhine-Westphalia state has become a national problem.
   Klaus Matthiesen, agriculture minister of North
Rhine-Westphalia, on Friday ordered the confiscation of
15,000-20,000 calves belonging to a single company.
   He did not identify the owner of the animals but said the North
Rhine-Westphalia firm had calves in several parts of the country.
   Matthiesen said it is believed the company treated the calves
with the hormone testosterone in an attempt to increase veal
production.
   West German law forbids the use of testosterone in raising
cattle. Some scientists have said the hormone is a suspected
cancer-causing agent, but West German scientists said the amounts
of testosterone found in the calves posed no danger to humans.
   In Baden-Wuerttemberg state, the agriculture ministry reported
calves treated with illegal hormones had been discovered there and
several cattle raisers were under investigation. It said 300 calves
were immediately taken off the market.
   Earlier this week, North Rhine-Westphalia officials accused
cattle-raiser Felix Hying of using hormones on thousands of calves.
   They ordered the slaughter of 4,200 of Hying's calves that
tested positive for the hormone and said more than 10,000 others
more were being tested.
   Werner Chory of the federal Health Ministry said: ``Firm
punishment must be handed out to those responsible. We are of the
opinion that there must be quick and comprehensive investigations
of every suspected illegal use of hormones.''
</TEXT>
