<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Serbia     08-13 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Serbia,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Serbian Rally Draws 5,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOVA PAZOVA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 Serbs rallied Friday
in support of Slobodan Milosevic, the hard-line leader of the
Serbian Communist Party, in his drive to strengthen the unity of
Yugoslavia's largest constituent republic.
   The gathering was held near the border of Serbia's autonomous
province of Vojvodina. Milosevic recently accused Vojvodina's
leaders of hampering efforts to amend the Serbian constitution to
give Serbia greater control over its two autonomous provinces.
   Vojvodina and the troubled southern province of Kosovo, though
formally parts of Serbia, were given broad administrative autonomy
under the 1974 constitution adopted while the late Josip Broz Tito
was president.
   Serbia's leaders want to reduce that autonomy in hopes of
curtailing ethnic strife in Kosovo, where the ethnic Albanian
majority is said to be terrorizing the Serbian minority and forcing
a Serbian exodus from the province.
   ``We don't want divisions!,'' ``A unified Serbia!,'' ``We don't
give them Kosovo!,'' chanted the demonstrators, many of whom turned
out in traditional Serbian national dress.
   It was the third such demonstration in the area since July 9.
All of them were widely believed to have been orchestrated by
Milosevic himself in an effort to demonstrate popular support for
his policies.
   Nova Pazova, a farming community, lies less than 15 miles west
of Belgrade in Yugoslavia's breadbasket region.
   Earlier demonstrations led to public accusations by the
Vojvodina Communist leadership that Milosevic was using unethical
pressure tactics to achieve his goal of a unified Serbia.
   Speaker after speaker at Friday's meeting assailed the
leadership in both Vojvodina and Kosovo, calling the leaders
``cheap opportunists'' who were unwilling to sacrifice personal
privilege for unity of the republic.
</TEXT>
