<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gibraltar-Britain 1stLd-Writethru a0666 08-13 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gibraltar-Britain, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0666,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Drill Before IRA Slaying Inquest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-4 UPDATE with ``fourth man'' report. PICKS up 3rd
graf pvs, The 1{-hour ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces in this British colony staged a
counterterrorism exercise Friday in preparation for a Sept. 6
inquest to be held here into the shooting deaths of three unarmed
members of the IRA by British soldiers.
   In London, a TV news broadcast reported Friday that Gibraltar
police wanted to question a suspected IRA guerrilla held in Dublin.
It said they long believed a fourth guerrilla was involved in
purported plans to bomb a British military guard.
   The Independent Television News program identified the suspect
as Peter Rooney, charged in Dublin's High Court with membership in
the illegal Irish Republican Army. Bail was set at $17,100, but
Rooney was ordered confined to jail while the identities of those
posting bail were checked. The news report did not give the source
of its information and could not be independently confirmed
immediately.
   In Gibraltar, Col. P. Fisbourne, chief of staff to Gov. Sir
Peter Terry, said ``Operation Clamp'' was carried out by the
280-man Gibraltar Police Force and British military police in
accordance with measures introduced into the colony since the IRA
attack on March 6.
   The 1{-hour exercise took place near the Rock Hotel where the
mock terrorist attack would have occurred, and it was designed to
test the ability of security forces to seal off all exits from the
2{-square mile limestone rock, according to a statement from
Fishbourne's office.
   On March 6, members of the British Special Air Services shot and
killed Mairead Farrell, Sean Savage and Daniel McCann as they were
walking toward the gate that separates Gibraltar from mainland
Spain.
   British Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe told Parliament in
London two days later the three were believed to have planted a car
bomb set to go off two days later near Gibraltar's main square at
the time of a ceremonial changing of the guard.
   Howe later said the three were unarmed and the car did not
contain explosives.
   The IRA, which seeks to drive the British out of Northern
Ireland, said the three had been ``on active service'' at the time
of their deaths.
   At a preliminary hearing July 5, Coroner Felix Pizzarello ruled
the seven Special Air Services members involved in the shooting
must be visible to the jury when they testify at the inquest,
although they will be screened from the public and the press.
   An attorney for the Crown and the Gibraltar Police Force, which
is under the direct control of the colony's British governor,
wanted the identities of the seven hidden to protect them and their
families from revenge attacks.
   The purpose of the inquest is to determine whether the shootings
constitute a crime.
   The Gibraltar attorney general has the power to return
indictments if the inquest or his indepedent investigation
determines a crime was committed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
