<HEAD>Tavern Owner Countersues Victims' Families</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Claiming mental anguish and loss of
business, a tavern owner has countersued the parents of five of the
victims of the fiery church bus crash near here that killed 27
people.
   Joann Osborne of Tubby's Tavern filed responses, including the
countersuits, to five of 65 lawsuits filed against her in Carroll
Circuit Court. She denied that her employees negligently allowed
Larry W. Mahoney to become intoxicated May 14, the date of the
wreck.
   Her lawyer, William Carter, has not yet filed responses to the
other 60 lawsuits, court officials said. There was no answer Friday
afternoon at Carter's office.
   Mahoney has pleaded innocent to charges of murder, assault,
wanton endangerment and drunken driving. His trial is scheduled for
January.
   Mrs. Osborne declined comment on the countersuits. She has said
that Mahoney came to her tavern just outside Carrollton between 3
and 3:30 p.m. May 14, about eight hours before the crash. She said
he drank one beer and left but was not drunk.
   Police say Mahoney's blood-alcohol level was more than twice the
legal limit and he was traveling the wrong way on southbound
Interstate 71 when his pickup truck crashed into the bus from the
First Assembly of God Church in Radcliff. Twenty-four of the 27
victims were children.
