<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Toledo-Blacks     08-13 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toledo-Blacks,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suit Seeks To Halt Random Police Stops Of Black Youths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal civil rights suit was filed Friday
seeking an end to a ``patently offensive'' new police department
policy of randomly stopping and questioning black teen-agers in a
racially mixed neighborhood.
   The suit was filed by a black lawyers' group, the Thurgood
Marshall Law Association, on behalf of Walter Wade Jr., 19.
   The black teen-ager was followed and then stopped by police in
front of his house Wednesday, but was not charged with any offense,
the suit said.
   The suit claims Wade was ``a victim of a policy which was
patently offensive on its face and lacked any constitutional
guarantees of protection from undue police harassment, interference
of invasion of privacy, freedom of association and to be free from
undue and illegal search and seizure.''
   U.S. District Judge John Potter set a Monday hearing on the
suit, which names as defendants Police Chief Martin Felker, Mayor
Donna Owens, City Manager Philip Hawkey and the city of Toledo.
   City officials did not immediately answer telephone messages
seeking comment. However, Felker has defended the policy as
necessary to stop violence in the neighborhood; Ms. Owens and
Hawkey also have supported it.
   The suit seeks a temporary restraining order to keep officers
from carrying out Felker's July 8 directive, which calls for random
stopping of black teen-agers in the Old West End neighborhood. The
order followed complaints by residents who had reported three
violent incidents involving black youngsters.
   Wade's lawyers also seek $1 million in punitive and compensatory
damages.
   The suit contends the city's policy violates federal civil
rights law and the first and fourth amendments to the Constitution,
which provide for freedom of association and freedom from unlawful
search and seizure.
   About 17 percent of Toledo's 340,000 residents are black, and
the city has experienced racial friction recently.
   The Interdenominational Ministerial Alliance, which includes
ministers from a variety of church congregations here, recently
asked the Justice Department to investigate what the ministers
called a conspiracy against black officials in Toledo.
   The group contends that local media and officials have conspired
to treat blacks differently from whites _ most notably, by firing
one city employee and disciplining two others for alleged
mismanagement of city housing programs.
   A civil rights group also has been threatening to boycott
businesses that do not hire and promote blacks as a way of ending
what it calls economic injustice in Toledo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
