<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SupercomputerKids     08-13 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Supercomputer Kids,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Team From Virginia Wins Competition and $1 Million Computer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Virginia team won a national
competition among high school students with a prize of a $1 million
supercomputer, it was announced Friday.
   The nine-month competition was sponsored by ETA Systems Inc.,
the supercomputer division of Control Data Corp. A team from Thomas
Jefferson High School for Science and Technology in Alexandria,
Va., was named the winner at an awards ceremony.
   Sixteen students from four high schools spent seven weeks this
summer doing research as part of the competition on the ETA10-P,
which is similar to the one to be awarded to Thomas Jefferson High
School.
   The school will also receive two years of operating costs for
the computer, worth $7,000 to $10,000 a month, and a company
employee to advise on the machine's use.
   The computer is one of the fastest and most powerful available
for scientific engineering and computation. It will be installed in
time for the fall semester, and ETA officials said it will make
Thomas Jefferson the first secondary school in the world with a
supercomputer.
   The teen-age competitors worked on individual projects but were
judged together in teams representing their high schools. The
schools will each get a $3,000 stipend for taking part in the
``SuperQuest'' contest.
   The runners-up were teams from Montgomery Blair High School,
Silver Spring, Md.; North Florida Christian School, Tallahassee,
Fla.; and James Logan High School, Union City, Calif.
   Each of the runner-up high schools will receive a $50,000
Control Data Corp. Cyber 910 graphics work station.
   The contest was the brainchild of ETA's president, Carl
Ledbetter, who said he hopes it will encourage Americans to focus
more attention on math and science education.
</TEXT>
