<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Panama-Cocaine     08-13 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Cocaine,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendant Pleads Guilty In Military Cocaine Conspiracy; Trial Set
For Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former soldier who unveiled a conspiracy
to import cocaine from a U.S. military post office in Panama
pleaded guilty Friday in the case, and trial was set for next month
for nine other defendants.
   Jackie Lee Bigelow, 27, pleaded guilty before U.S. District
Judge J. Robert Elliott to charges of conspiring to possess cocaine
with intent to distribute.
   Bigelow agreed to cooperate with authorities after a traffic
stop in Moultrie last May led to the discovery of 8.5 kilograms of
cocaine in his car trunk. Nine other people have been indicted in
the case, including three unidentified individuals from Panama,
said Assistant U.S. Attorney Deborah Fowler.
   Elliott scheduled a trial for the remaining defendants for Sept.
12. Bigelow is to be sentenced following completion of a
presentence report.
   The cocaine conspiracy scheme came to light shortly after
Bigelow's arrest in May, said Colquitt County Sheriff Gene Beard.
After Bigelow agreed to cooperate with investigators, other arrests
followed as well as the seizure of two packages of cocaine _ one
weighing 18 pounds and one 24 pounds _ that had been mailed to
three Georgia women from the military post office in Panama.
   An FBI affidavit released in June said Bigelow admitted he had
traveled to Panama twice this year to meet with others in the
cocaine conspiracy to set up shipments. Bigelow served in Panama
while in the Army.
   In court Thursday, Ms. Fowler said the conspiracy had brought in
163 kilograms of cocaine from February 1987 until June 1988.
   Also Thursday, Elliott refused to set bond for Gary King, age
unavailable, of Doe Run, another former U.S. Army soldier charged
in the case. None of the other defendants has been released on bond.
   The Army has said it is continuing investigations into
allegations of drug trafficking from U.S. military posts in Panama
and elsewhere.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
