<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Salvador Laurel today
accused President Corazon Aquino of incompetence and called for her
to resign. He threatened to quit the coalition government if she
refuses.
   In a four-page letter to the president, which he read to
reporters, Laurel said Mrs. Aquino was not adequately fighting the
nation's 19-year communist insurgency and was allowing corruption
on the scale of her deposed predecessor, Ferdinand Marcos.
   Mrs. Aquino, who took office in February 1986, accused Laurel of
not taking an active role in government and said at times he was
more interested in playing golf than in attending important Cabinet
meetings.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shops in Burma reopened today and
streets filled with happy-looking people rejoicing after the
resignation of hard-line leader Sein Lwin, travelers and news
reports said.
   ``Burma's Hitler was brought down by the might of all the
people,'' Japan's Kyodo News Agency quoted one Burmese as saying.
``It was late in coming but it's only natural that the most
unpopular person is overthrown,'' said another.
   The news agency said in a report from the capital, Rangoon, that
troops had withdrawn from the city and tensions were eased after
four days of anti-government protests that left at least 95 people
dead. The city of 3.5 million had been under a daytime curfew since
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic lawmakers say departing Attorney
General Edwin Meese III's order calling for independent counsels to
investigate members of Congress suspected of criminal conduct is
unnecessary and vindictive.
   Meese, in his final act Friday after 3{ controversial years at
the Justice Department, said he wanted to ensure that legislators
and top executive branch officials be treated equally under the law.
   But legislators pointed out that Meese has established a system
with crucial differences for members of Congress. Sen. Carl Levin,
D-Mich., said Meese had a good idea but he ``messed it up'' by
stipulating that the attorney general _ not a court _ would appoint
the independent counsel.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Long lines of curious filmgoers turned out to see ``The Last
Temptation of Christ'' in nine cities, greatly outnumbering the
protesters who denounced as sacrilegious the film that debuted in
guarded theaters.
   Many movie patrons left sold-out theaters Friday wondering what
all the fuss was about, while others said protesters were trying to
suppress free speech and religious toleration.
   ``It's just a movie, and you can't really condone it or say
anything about it until you've seen it,'' said James Aguiar, 23,
one of hundreds of patrons who lined up around the block at New
York's Ziegfeld Theater.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and the Soviet Union are
resolving what officials describe as a minor incident in which
American technical experts removed some materials as ``souvenirs''
from a Soviet nuclear test site without authorization.
   The three U.S. experts are being relieved of their duties as
members of an American team assigned to monitor Soviet atomic
blasts. They were in the Soviet Union at the Semipalatinsk test
site as part of a joint verification program when the incident
occurred last month.
   Administration spokesmen said Friday the items found by Soviet
authorities in crates being prepared for shipment back home
included a small hammer, a piece of barbed wire, and several rock
and core samples from a hole being drilled at the site.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency says a
record $2.5 million settlement involving a commercial hazardous
waste facility in Louisiana should send the message to other
companies that failure to comply with environmental rules will
prove costly.
   ``EPA will not tolerate hazardous waste mismanagement in this
country, especially by the nation's major disposal companies,'' EPA
Administrator Lee M. Thomas said in announcing the settlement
Friday.
   ``This significant penalty should send a signal to all waste
handlers that the cost of non-compliance with our requirements will
be more costly than compliance,'' Thomas said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduras' foreign minister accused
the United States of shirking its responsibility in Central
American peace efforts and said the Reagan administration should
work with the Soviet Union on a plan to end the region's wars.
   Nicaragua's president, Daniel Ortega, offered Friday to hold new
peace talks with U.S.-supported Contra rebels either in Managua or
Washington. He said the government was ready to meet rebels in
Managua on Aug. 26-29. Adolfo Calero, a rebel leader, rejected
Managua as the site for talks but did not address the possibility
of talks in Washington. He demanded that Ortega attend any future
negotiating sessions.
   Honduran Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras said the United
States' and Soviet Union's backing of warring parties in Central
America threatens the security of his nation, a key U.S. ally.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New research provides a possible explanation for
one of the mysteries of AIDS: how a few infected cells lead to the
downfall of the body's entire immune system.
   The research also suggests serious obstacles may stand in the
way of finding a vaccine to keep people from catching the AIDS
virus.
   ``I wouldn't say impossible, but it's very unlikely that one
would be able to develop a successful vaccine,'' said Dr. Ellis L.
Reinherz, senior author of the study published in Friday's issue of
the journal Cell.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rains lashed this desert capital
today, exacerbating flooding that left 1.5 million people homeless
and hampering efforts to distribute emergency supplies.
   The rains began about midnight and created huge pools of water
in the streets of downtown Khartoum, a city of 4 million. The
airport was closed, and the Nile was rising. The downpour continued
through the night.
   Relief agencies and donor nations began airlifting blankets,
tents, food, medical and other supplies to Khartoum on Friday, 48
hours after a storm dumped six times as much rain on the city as it
received in all of 1987.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FOOTEDALE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amid the hills of rural Pennsylvania,
where the Holocaust's horrors seem long ago and far away, a Polish
parish is converting a church basement into a museum evoking the
concentration camp where the ``Saint of Auschwitz'' died 47 years
ago Sunday.
   ``I lived through the cruelties and atrocities of World War II,
and I would like the people in this country to have some idea what
transpired,'' said Stanislaw Dziob, 55, an engineer from Krakow,
Poland.
   He and another visitor from Poland are transforming the basement
of St. Thomas Roman Catholic Church into a museum made to look and
feel like the concentration camp where St. Maximilian Kolbe died.
While honoring all those killed by the Nazis, the museum spotlights
the Polish victims, especially Kolbe, a Franciscan friar who
volunteered to die so a fellow prisoner at Auschwitz might live.
</TEXT>
