<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush knows all about the frantic
suspense surrounding late announcements of a presidential nominee's
running mate. He got his own 11th-hour call from Ronald Reagan in
1980.
   Now, he's doing his best to keep a dozen or so Republicans on
the same edge.
   With his silence on a vice presidential choice, Bush is
providing the only element of suspense in an otherwise suspenseless
Republican National Convention.
   Bush says he hopes to make up his mind before he gets to New
Orleans _ even if he doesn't announce that decision until Wednesday
or Thursday _ but aides insist the vice president still has not
decided.
   He was working on his campaign acceptance speech Saturday while
still keeping his own counsel on the vice presidential selection
process.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With all the restraint of an elephant doing
the full-tilt boogie, the party town and the Grand Old Party are
celebrating this week what they have in common.
   Party. More than 500 separate bashes are scheduled for
convention week, enough to send George Bush into the presidential
fray on a tidal wave of Hurricane rum punch. The Republicans plan
some business, for sure. But, after all, this is New Orleans.
   ``New Orleans will use anything for an excuse for a party. No
matter what happens, there's a party,'' said Doris Finney, a
celebrant Friday night at, well, a party. ``Bring on the
Republicans. New Orleans will party all week.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private man in public life, George Bush
admits to discomfort in discussing such personal matters as his
family. Typically, he calls them ``our gang'' and reverts to terms
coaches use for their best players.
   As well they may be. For as Bush heads into the fall campaign
against Michael Dukakis, his energetic brood is being unleashed as
a formidable political weapon.
   ``We're not political pros, but we've got political seasoning,''
says George W. Bush, the vice president's eldest son and a top
campaign strategist, in what may be a bit of understatement.
   The Bushes are veterans of many years spent in the public eye as
Bush trekked from Congress to diplomatic posts, in China and at the
United Nations, to the CIA and then to the No. 2 spot at the White
House.
   His wife Barbara has been described as an indefatigable
campaigner who shrugs off talk about herself, such as that she dye
her white hair, but bristles when her husband is criticized.
   George Jr. has run for Congress, with brother Neil his campaign
manager, and his other siblings are active in grass-roots party
politics. All are delegates at the GOP convention in New Orleans.
And all are actively involved in trying to get their father to the
top spot in the White House.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis,
who cites the Pentagon purchasing scandal in almost every campaign
speech, oversees a procurement system described by the
Massachusetts inspector general as ``almost a standing invitation
to fraud, waste and abuse.''
   Inspector General Joseph Baressi, a fellow Democrat, has
delivered scathing attacks on three aspects of the state's
purchasing system: its procedures for buying supplies and
equipment, its guidelines for obtaining services through
consultants and its laws governing purchases by city, town,
district and county governments.
   A spokesman for the Massachusetts governor said many of the
problems have been corrected internally in recent months but
Baressi's office, while praising some of the steps taken to protect
against fraud, said only new laws will correct giant flaws in the
system.
