<1ST_LINE>s i BC-ChinaToday-Problems Adv21   08-13 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China Today-Problems, Adv 21,0669</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 21, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Post-Mao Life Better in China, but Problems Remain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-China Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIEJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Life has improved for the Chinese since the dark
ages of Mao Tse-tung's tumultuous Cultural Revolution in 1966-76.
But serious problems remain.
   These are the major ones:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CORRUPTION _ It is endemic among Communist Party and government
officials. Gao Shangquan, vice minister of the State Economic
Restructuring Commission, has said, ``Power abuse for personal
gains, illegal reselling at high profits, graft and bribery are
seriously hampering normal economic operations, damaging the
reform's reputation and directly affecting the interests of both
the state and masses.''
  
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   OVERPOPULATION _ China's population control policy, lauded for
its successes and condemned for its draconian methods, is in
trouble.
   The birth rate, pumped up as a 1960s baby boom generation begins
having families, hit 2 percent in 1986 and stayed there in 1987,
well above the 1.5 percent pace China needs if it is attain its
goal of holding the population, now at 1.07 billion, to 1.2 billion
in the year 2000.
   The baby explosion has been set off mainly by affluent peasants
who are willing to pay the fines and other penalties for violating
the one child per family policy, at least until they have a boy.
With the return of family farming, extra children means more hands
in the fields.
   A poem of the countryside goes: ``Why be afraid of being fined?
It just means I buy a high-priced boy. A sum of money is dead
treasure. A son is a live treasure.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CRIME _ Greater mobility (China has an estimated 50 million
``floaters'' including peddlers and drifting construction workers),
and fewer social controls has meant increased crime.
   The public security chief, Wang Fang, said 58,000 major criminal
offenses were recorded in the first five months of the year, up a
third from last year. Premier Li Peng warned law enforcement
officers they must adopt ``concrete measures to deal with
troublemaking, riots, all kinds of foreign sabotage and serious
crimes.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDUCATION _ The education system, hobbled by Mao's
anti-intellectual biases and the ravages of the Cultural
Revolution, is severely underfinanced despite steady budget
increases in recent years.
   Although the government in 1986 promulgated a nine-year
compulsory education law, it acknowledges it will be decades before
all children go to school for a complete education. Currently only
two-thirds of those finishing the sixth grade continue their
education.
   Thousands of rural schools are closing because many teachers,
among the lowest paid people in China, are resigning, and others
are so poor they can't buy chalk.
   The situation is hardly better for the 2 percent of students
able to attend college. Dormitories house eight to a room, books
are often unavailable and classrooms are unheated and ill-equipped.
   Student discontent erupted in the winter of 1986-87 with
nationwide pro-democracy demonstrations.
   Thousands of disaffected youth are trying to leave the country
or refusing to return from overseas study programs. Only a fourth
of the 36,000 students who have gone to the United States have
returned, although it is not clear how many will eventually stay
abroad.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE ARTS _ Chinese artists in 1988 are beginning to relax again
after the chill of last year's anti-bourgeois liberalization
campaign. Nude paintings and D.H. Lawrence's novels are back in
good graces. Chinese authors are again dissecting the nation's
social upheaval and two earthy films depicting the impoverished
countryside, ``Old Well'' and ``Red Sorghum,'' have won
international prizes.
   But intellectuals have always been the first to suffer in
China's political campaigns. Many, hearing officials again intone
Mao's 1957 slogan ``Let a hundred flowers bloom, let a hundred
schools of thought contend,'' remember that in 1958 Mao launched a
campaign of retribution against those who dared to speak out.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sun Aug. 21</NOTE>
