<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 15,0659</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Monday Aug 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Dashed Hopes of Industrial Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In raising the discount rate, the Federal
Reserve dashed the hopes of a large percentage of middle-class
Americans, especially those in industrial jobs, says a pioneer in
consumer behavior studies.
   ``Their expectations fell right through the floor,'' said Albert
Sindlinger.
   Sindlinger had just finished three days of telephone interviews,
358 in all that lasted from 15 to 18 minutes each, in which
Americans were asked about their finances and expectations.
   Conditioned as he was to hearing bad news, Sindlinger
nevertheless was shocked by the computer analysis of the results.
``The very people we needed to help we hurt the most,'' he said. He
said it was a tragedy.
   These people, he explained, are ordinary American workers with a
small amount of savings and investments but no stocks or mutual
funds. Many of them are buying houses financed by adjustable
interest loans.
   That, he suggested, was enough to lower expectations about their
economic well-being six months from now. But there was more. Many
had just recently climbed up out of the financial hole; they saw
themselves tuumbling back down.
   Sindlinger, who began his telephone interviews more than three
decades ago, developing over the years a reputation for using such
data to make economic projections, observed that two years ago many
of these people were jobless.
   In late 1986, for example, his interviews suggested that no less
than 31 states, most dependent on manufacturing, oil, mining or
agriculture, were in recession.
   Disguising the plight of these states, at least in the national
statistics, were the good times experienced in the coastal areas.
The latters' results smoothed out the negatives being reported from
the interior.
   By the fall of 1987, however, all but four states were out of
recession. Once-idle blue-collar workers found jobs, and others
moved up from low-paying service-sector jobs to better paying
positions in manufacturing.
   Job data offer some documentation.
   From Aug. 2, 1987, to Aug. 1, 1988, Sindlinger & Co., in
Wallingford, Pa., found a 17.24 percent increase in production,
trade and craft jobs in manufacturing. The category showing the
next biggest rise was ``operators, fabricators and laborers.''
   These are the people hurt the most by the discount rate
increase, Sindlinger said. First, he said, their hopes were raised,
and then they were dashed. They feel betrayed, he said; ``they feel
like they've been hit with a one-two punch.''
   ``All of them expect a decline in household income within six
months,'' he said. They fear their savings will diminish. They fear
bigger expenses.
   In his opinion, the Federal Reserve made a terrible mistake in
raising the discount rate to 6.5 percent from 6 percent. First, he
said, inflation was not that big a threat. Secondly, he said, the
Fed misread the employment data.
   The Fed, he said, believed that inflation was roaring because
weekly earnings went up last month. But, he said, this was not a
case of wages rising in an inflationary manner. It was, he said,
simply the upgrading of jobs.
   As he put it: ``Workers who had been flipping hamburgers in the
service sector found better-paying jobs moving pipes around in the
manufacturing sector.''
   These are politically important people, he continued. ``They are
swing voters,'' he said. ``They put Reagan and Nixon in office, and
they could do the same with Dukakis.''
   Seldom an admirer of the Fed, Sindlinger prepared to offer
clients of his weekly service a personal opinion. He wrote:
   ``The USS Fed shot down the U.S. Economy Airbus over the Gulf of
Ignorance, using its trusty discount rate surface-to-air missile.
   ``Responsibility must be placed on the shoulders of the
commanders for gross errors of judgment.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Mon Aug 15</NOTE>
