<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv13-14   08-13 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 13-14,0623</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 13</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Aug. 13-14</NOTE>
<HEAD>Hike in Discount Rate is `Godzilla' for Treasury Auctions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They weren't your ordinary, run-of-the-mill
quarterly Treasury auctions.
   The Federal Reserve's surprise hike in its key discount rate
this past Tuesday caught the bond market off-guard and wreaked
havoc on the three auctions of Treasury securities that followed
the move, analysts said.
   The government bonds were not well bid. Many foreign investors,
who play a critical role in financing the nation's $2.5 trillion
debt, apparently were driven away from the sales.
   ``The Fed really threw the market a curve ball _ and did it at
the last minute,'' said Robert Brusca, chief economist and senior
vice president of the fixed-income division at Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc.
   He likened the impact of the discount-rate boost on the auctions
to ``what Godzilla did to Tokyo.''
   The increase in the discount rate, the interest the Fed charges
on loans to major financial institutions, was the first such hike
since last October's stock market crash. A rise in interest rates
sends bond prices lower.
   The central bank raised the rate a half-percentage point, to 6.5
percent, in order to stem inflationary pressure on the economy.
Many market watchers had expected the Fed to tighten its reins on
the money supply _ but few were anticipating that dramatic a move.
   Consumers felt the ripples two days later, on Thursday, when the
nation's major banks responded by upping their prime lending rates
to 10 percent from 9.5 percent. The prime rate is used as a
benchmark for a range of loan charges for consumers and businesses,
such as home mortgage rates and credit card interest fees.
   Bond investors, meanwhile, were feeling shock waves. The three
auctions, on Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday, made up the
Treasury's third-quarter refunding aimed at raising cash to finance
the federal debt. The government sold a total $29 billion in 3-year
notes, 10-year notes and short-term cash management bills.
   The discount-rate move and the economic uncertainty it stirred
up couldn't have come at a worse time, analysts contend.
   The auction results ``were pretty dismal,'' said Elizabeth
Reiners, a vice president at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``The demand
that everybody had thought was out there pretty much dried up at
the auctions.''
   The government issues fetched low prices, driving up interest
rates on the bonds to sky-high levels.
   Yields on the $11 billion in 3-year Treasury notes on the
auction block climbed to the highest level in three years. The
average yield was 8.77 percent, up sharply from 8.23 percent at the
last comparable auction on May 10.
   Another $11 billion in 10-year notes didn't fare much better.
Their average yield rose to 9.27 percent, up from 9.06 percent at
the last similar sale on May 11 and the loftiest level in nearly
three years.
   Foreign investors _ especially the usually bond-hungry Japanese
_ seem to have stayed away from the auctions in droves.
   ``They stayed home,'' said Ward McCarthy, chief financial
economist for Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   The 50 percent or so participation by foreign investors that
usually marks the quarterly auctions shrunk in half, traders said.
   Compounding the problem was the absence of 30-year Treasury
bonds, normally a staple of the quarterly sales and a favorite of
Japanese investors.
   Since the Treasury has used up almost all its congressional
authority to issue long-term securities, it was forced to strike
30-year bonds from the slate of the auctions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Aug. 13-14</NOTE>
</DOC>
