<NOTE>$adv 14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release In Weekend Editions Aug 13-14</NOTE>
<HEAD>Will Drought Stifle Booming Soy Ink Business?</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be followed later in cycle with an ADD containing weekly
commodity price trends</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspaper ink made from soybean oil is a runaway success, but
the high price of soybeans is likely to drive up the price of soy
inks, forcing some publishers to return to the petroleum-based
variety.
   The choice may be purely economic for large metropolitan papers
like the Boston Globe, which switched to soy-based inks exclusively
for its color printing work about a year ago.
   But the issue could become stickier for rural newspapers in the
Farm Belt, where printing with soy-based ink is seen as one way of
helping the local soybean growers.
   ``It's pretty hard not to commit to the farmers here,'' said Lon
Myers, director of operations for the Cedar Rapids Gazette, one of
the first newspapers in the country to use soy ink in early 1987.
   But, Myers said, ``everything is subject to evaluation. There's
obviously some business judgment that has to be used.''
   So far, ink manufacturers have been willing to absorb the sharp,
drought-driven increase in soybean oil prices just to get customers
to try soy inks, and many have. Approximately 600 U.S. newspapers
are using soy ink for color reproduction, said Wilson Cunningham,
research manager for the Reston, Va.-based American Newspaper
Publishers Association, which developed soy-based ink in response
to environmental concerns about petroleum-based inks.
   Soy inks in the most frequently used colors _ blue, red and
yellow - sell for $2.50 to $3 a pound, about 5 percent more than
their petroleum-based counterparts. Newspapers say the superior
performance of the colored soy inks offsets the slightly higher
cost.
   Black soy ink, at about 90 cents a pound, costs nearly twice as
much as black petroleum ink and hasn't caught on with newspaper
publishers. As far as quality comparisons, ``black is black,''
Myers said in a telephone interview.
   The Midwestern drought has withered soybean crops and pushed the
price of crude soybean oil up dramatically on the Chicago Board of
Trade, from about 21 cents to about 27 cents a pound since the
start of the year.
   In a crop production report released Thursday, the Agriculture
Department estimated soybean oil prices for the coming
October-through-September marketing year would average 25.5 cents a
pound. The USDA estimated soybean oil production for the period at
11.1 billion pounds, 14 percent less than estimated production of
12.9 billion pounds for the current marketing year.
   Despite the lower production, surplus stocks of soybean oil
should be adequate, said Stan Pendlum, an economist with the St.
Louis-based American Soybean Association.
   Herb Edelman, vice president of operations for the United States
Printing Ink Corp., a national ink distributor based in East
Rutherford, N.J., said the price of soy-based inks likely will rise
``in time.''
   ``I think we'll have to address that before the end of the year
after the situation stabilizies,'' he said.
   J.M. Huber Corp. of Edison, N.J., another major manufacturer of
newspaper ink, also has held the line on its soy-based inks despite
the rise in soybean oil prices.
   ``We're hoping the drought is a temporary blip and soy oil
prices will come down to ordinary levels,'' said Dennis Sweet,
Huber's market specialist for newspaper inks.
   The Boston Globe would almost certainly switch back to
petroleum-based ink if the price of soy ink rose significantly,
said John Bopp, the newspaper's quality control manager.
   Bopp said the color capabilities of new petroleum inks approach
the quality of soy inks.
   Traditionally, ``the cheapest price buys the ink'' at most
newspapers, said Cunningham of the ANPA.
   ``The superior quality of soybean inks may make someone be
willing to pay a higher price, but it's hard to say,'' he said.
   On the other hand, both Cunningham and Myers pointed out that
petroleum ink prices may also rise. Many energy market analysts
expect crude oil prices to increase after the Iran-Iraq cease-fire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
