<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SAfrica-Economy     08-13 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Economy,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Announces Rise In Fuel Prices, Surcharges On Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced major
steps Friday to shore up the economy, including a 15 percent
increase in fuel prices and higher surcharges on luxury imports.
   Consumer and business groups complained that the increase in
fuel prices would halt a recent decline in the inflation rate,
which has fallen from 17 percent in 1987 to 12.4 percent.
   The Black Consumers Union said the fuel price increase would be
a particular hardship to poor blacks who rely on lamp fuel to light
unelectrified homes.
   George Bartlett, deputy minister of economic affairs, said the
price for high-octane gasoline will increase by 15.9 percent to
about $1.60 a gallon. Similar increases in low-octane gasoline and
other fuels will be introduced.
   Finance Minister Barend du Plessis and Economic Affairs Minister
Dawie de Villiers announced a separate package of economic
measures, including restrictions on installment purchases to curb
borrowing and higher surcharges on imports such as motor vehicles,
tobacco, televisions, coffee, tea and jewelry.
   On many items, the existing 10 percent surcharge will be raised
to 60 percent.
   The ministers said the steps had been caused by high domestic
spending, which placed pressure on interest rates and led to
increased imports.
   If consumers curtailed spending, they said, the government could
avoid ``further and more painful steps.''
   The higher consumption had boosted imports of crude oil and
moved South Africa away from ``desired levels'' of energy
self-sufficiency, Bartlett said.
   South Africa is the target of international oil embargo but
imports an estimated $3 billion worth of oil a year. It does not
disclose details of its oil needs.
   Economists say the increased fuel imports have been a major
factor in a recent severe reduction in South Africa's balance of
payments surplus. South Africa's currency, the rand, has weakened
as a result and the cost of imported fuel has risen.
   Business organizations conceded the need for a fuel price
increase but said the announced rise was excessive.
   In a separate development, the government announced it would
implement a new labor bill Sept. 1 despite ongoing negotiations
between employers and black trade unions to resolve disputes over
the legislation.
   The Labor Relations Amendment would effectively outlaw sympathy
strikes and consumer boycotts in connection with labor disputes.
   A committee of employer representatives had agreed to recommend
that the government remove six controversial sections from the bill.
   The country's two largest black labor federations responded by
calling on employers to pledge that they would not invoke some of
the provisions in the bill that could weaken unions.
   They called the government's decision to implement the bill
despite the negotiations amounted to ``pandering to minority
right-wing interests.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
