<1ST_LINE>r f AM-StockFine     08-13 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stock Fine,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NY Investment Firm, Maine Broker Fined $110,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York-based investment firm and a
broker in Maine were fined $110,000 after being charged with
selling unregistered stocks and misrepresenting a risky stock to
investors, Maine's attorney general said Friday.
   The investment firm Gruntal & Co. and Portland broker Richard A.
Liberty neither admit nor deny guilt to the charges outlined in the
consent decree, which was signed Thursday by Superior Court Justice
Morton Brody.
   Attorney General James E. Tierney said the complaint filed in
Kennebec County Superior Court alleged that Gruntal and Liberty on
more than 100 occasions sold to Maine residents stock in a computer
software company that was unregistered in the state.
   Although Gruntal and Liberty told investors that the stock in
MicroShare Corp. of Utah was an ``excellent investment,'' it was
actually ``highly speculative and risky'' because MicroShare is a
new company in a highly competitive market, said the attorney
general's complaint.
   Rufus E. Brown, lawyer for Gruntal and Liberty, took issue
Friday with the charge that Liberty misrepresented the stocks. He
said ``most if not all'' buyers signed statements in which they
indicated they understood the stocks were speculative.
   The consent decree orders Liberty to pay at least $20,000 of the
fine and Gruntal to pay at least $75,000. Liberty is a cousin of
Portland real-estate developer Michael Liberty, according to the
defendants' lawyer.
   The consent decree also enjoins the defendants from selling
unregistered securities in Maine.
   Tierney said the complaint arose from an investigation by the
Maine Banking Bureau's Securities Division.
</TEXT>
