<DOCNO> AP880813-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ChickenTrademark     08-13 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicken Trademark,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Burger King Has Rights To `Chicken Tender' Trademark</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A frozen poultry producer's decision to call its
bite-sized pieces ``chicken tenders'' violated Burger King's
exclusive right to the name, a U.S. District Court jury concluded
Friday.
   The jury, which deliberated for about four hours following eight
days of unorthodox and amusing testimony, rejected Pilgrim's
Pride's claim that ``chicken tenders'' is a generic term and should
not be subject to trademark regulations.
   Alan Greer, an attorney for Miami-based Burger King Corp., said
the fast-food giant will file motions within 30 days seeking an
order from Judge Eugene Spellman to prohibit Pilgrim's Pride from
using the name.
   The company also will request payments equal to the profits
Pilgrim's Pride received on the $4.5 million in boneless chicken
morsels sold since early 1986, said Greer.
   In the meantime, Greer said Dallas-based Pilgrim's Pride uses
the chicken tender name ``at their peril.''
   ``Burger King is very pleased by the verdict,'' said Burger King
spokesman Doug Timberlake, reading from a prepared statement.
   But Pilgrim's Pride Chief Executive Officer Lonnie ``Bo''
Pilgrim maintains that the tender, or tenderloin breast, is an
accepted name used in the poultry industry for many years.
   ``The jury missed the point,'' said Pilgrim. ``It puts us in a
situation of not knowing what to call our product. ... Burger King
learned about the name tender from the chicken industry.''
   Pilgrim said the company has not decided if it will appeal the
verdict ending the nine-day trial, which included technical debate
over chicken anatomy and a dramatic dismembering of a raw bird.
   Throughout the trial, jurors were presented with tough talk
about the mysterious 2{-inch ``tenders'' by a parade of
entertaining witnesses discussing poultry, linguistics and
advertising. Color, texture and even aftertaste were examined.
   Miami-based U.S. Department of Agriculture spokesman Harold
Havner testified he believed tenders was a generic term.
   In turn, Burger King attorney Louis Pirkey claimed Pilgrim's
Pride used the name tenders to ``ride the coattails'' of a $20
million Burger King advertising campaign launched in early 1986 to
hail the arrival of the chicken tenders around the nation.
   ``You might say they had 20 million reasons to call it chicken
tenders,'' said Pirkey last Tuesday.
   ``I don't steal,'' responded Pilgrim, a Texas farmer who
oversees the 20,000-pound-an-hour Pilgrim's Pride processing plant.
   In one of the most dramatic moments of the trial, University of
Arkansas professor Tommy Lee Goodwin on Tuesday dismembered a
plucked 3-pound bird with a butcher's knife to give jurors an
intimate look at the disputed section of the chicken, technically
known as the pectoralis minor.
   Spellman had to give written permission to allow the carving
knife into the court building.
   ``People who know chickens will still be calling them tenders no
matter what the jury said,'' Pilgrim said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880813-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Lawyer-InsiderTrading     08-13 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lawyer-Insider Trading,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Pleads Innocent to Insider Trading Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former partner in a major Chicago law firm
pleaded innocent Friday to federal charges he used information
gained through the firm for illegal stock trades.
   Alfred Elliott, 44, a former partner in Schiff, Hardin and
Waite, pleaded innocent before U.S. District Judge Marvin Aspen.
   A 70-count indictment returned against Elliott in July charged
he made over $680,000 between March 1984 and April 1986 on insider
information about the takeover of nine companies.
   Elliott was one of two lawyers at the firm who represented
companies in matters related to imminent mergers or acquisitions.
   The lawyer is charged with one count of racketeering, 34 counts
of wire fraud, 34 counts of securities fraud and one count of
income tax evasion, according to the indictment.
   In a 1986 civil case filed in federal court by the Securities
and Exchange Commission, Elliott paid more than $500,000 in damages
and repaid profits from similar allegations, according to his
attorney, Matthew F. Kennelly.
   In return for paying the money back, the lawyer did not have to
admit or deny charges of insider information, according to records
from the 1986 case.
   Elliott left the law firm in March, 1986. Kennelly said he did
not know why Elliott left.
   Aspen set a tentative trial date for Jan. 9.
</TEXT>
