<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AmericanStores     08-13 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American Stores,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grocery Chain Plans Sale of Florida's Kash n' Karry Chain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Stores Co., the new owner of the
Lucky grocery chain, announced Friday it would sell Lucky's 95 Kash
n' Karry supermarkets in Florida to a management group for $305
million.
   The deal is the second of a number of expected asset sales to
help American pay off the $2.6 billion in loans it took out to
finance the purchase of Lucky Stores Inc. in May.
   American also said it had completed the previously announced
sale of Lucky's 38 ABCO Markets in Arizona to a management group
there for $75 million.
   American, which owns Alpha Beta stores in California, other
supermarkets in several states and the 27-state Osco drug chain,
completed its purchase of the Lucky chain May 20.
   The merger has tentative antitrust approval from the Federal
Trade Commission, but California regulators oppose the deal on
grounds it would lessen competition. A final FTC decision is
expected about the end of the year.
   Present Kash n' Karry employees would keep their jobs under the
proposed acquisition by a management-allied group including Ron
Floto, president and chief executive officer. Kash n' Karry, with
headquarters in Tampa, has 95 supermarkets in central and western
Florida.
   Financing for the management buyout is being arranged by
Gibbons, Green, van Amerogen, which has financed many such
management buyouts, the partnership said in a news release.
   American acquired Lucky in a leveraged buyout, meaning the
purchase was financed by loans. Assets of the acquired company
often are sold off to pay the debt from such purchases, but
American spokesman Troy D'Ambrosio declined to say if more sales
were pending.
   American moved its corporate headquarters from Salt Lake City to
this Orange County community July 1, seeking improved access to
financial markets.
   American, with sales of $14.27 million last year, owns Jewel
Food stores in Chicago, Acme markets in Philadelphia, Star Markets
in Boston, Skaggs-Alpha Beta in the Southwest and Buttrey food
stores in Montana, Wyoming and Idaho.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
