<DOCNO> AP880813-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-88 0800EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-EconomyRdp     08-13 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wholesale Prices Jump; Interest Rates Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Long-term interest rates have risen to an eight-month high in
response to the Labor Department's report that wholesale prices
rose at a 5.7 percent annual rate in July.
   The yield of the Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond rose
Friday to 9.42 percent, its highest point since 9.44 percent on
Dec. 11, 1987, rounding out a bad string of performances for the
bond market.
   ``It's just been a lousy week,'' said Mitchell Held, chief
financial economist for Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co., referring
to the slide in the bond market.
   Inflation fears made for a bad week on Wall Street as well. The
Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 1.78 to 2,037.52,
extending its loss for the week to 81.61 points.
   The dollar was mixed Friday against major foreign currencies,
while oil futures prices declined.
   In another indication of rising rates, a nationwide survey
Friday found interest rates on new one-year, adjustable-rate
mortgages surged this week to 8 percent, the highest level since
last November.
   Fixed-rate mortgages jumped to 10.57 percent, just below the
peak of of late May and early June, according to the survey by the
Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   On the inflation front, the Labor Department said the 0.5
percent rise in its Producer Price Index in July occurred in spite
of smaller increases in food prices. That compared with a rise of
0.4 percent in June.
   Analysts were concerned that, unlike previous months, the
biggest increases were not in the normally highly volatile food and
energy sectors but across a wide spectrum of consumer and capital
goods.
   Drugs, men's clothing, tires, soaps, cosmetics, home electronic
equipment, glassware, tobacco products and construction equipment
all rose at annualized inflation rates in the double digits.
   ``These prices will slow down, but something else ... will pick
up the slack,'' said Donald Ratajczak, director of economic
forecasting at Georgia State University. ``There's a lot of
inflation kicking around.''
   Ratajczak predicted the August figures will look even worse when
they come out next month as energy prices rebound and the impact of
the Farm Belt drought wends its way through the food production
process.
   Consumer food prices on the wholesale level rose just 0.4
percent in July. The price decline was led by falling meat costs as
drought-plagued farmers and ranchers rushed their herds to
slaughter rather than continue feeding them high-cost grains.
   In a related report on the inflationary front, the Commerce
Department reported Friday business inventories rose 0.7 percent in
June despite a 1.5 percent increase in sales.
   That indicated some businesses were stocking up on inventories
to beat expected price increases, said Allen Sinai of the Boston
Co., a money management firm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
